TFTC </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="24.6645" lon="9.739833"><time>2003-02-08T00:00:00</time><name>GCE0A6</name><desc>Le gardien de Safar by JOKAJI</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCE0A6</url><urlname>Le gardien de Safar</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="57510" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Le gardien de Safar</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>JOKAJI</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="107825">JOKAJI</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="0">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="0">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Algeria</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Near left neolithic pictures n° XIII5E1,in a vertical crack , 1.5 meter above ground, behind a small stone.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description /><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1299748079"><groundspeak:date>2025-05-21T11:08:34</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="107825">JOKAJI</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Archivée car il m'est impossible d'assurer la maintenance</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1292780608"><groundspeak:date>2025-04-20T16:20:19</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3947453">Luiyo</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Este geocacher informó que el contenedor está dañado.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1329064777"><groundspeak:date>2025-04-19T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54042110">Espiran</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Beautiful place!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1329064424"><groundspeak:date>2025-04-19T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="53446752">jairsan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We found during a trip to the Tassili n'Ajjer in April. Really awesome place and a great way to discover geocaching. Thank you for the cache!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1292799378"><groundspeak:date>2025-04-19T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="49518499">Snowy_AN</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Impresionante lugar en el que encontrar un caché! Cerca del gran dios marciano. Merci beaucoup pour le caché. TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="42.561033333333334" lon="1.5436"><time>2002-03-16T00:00:00</time><name>GC42E3</name><desc>Casamanya by vicam</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC42E3</url><urlname>Casamanya</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="17123" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Casamanya</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>vicam</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="20094">vicam</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="33" inc="1">Motorcycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="34" inc="1">Quads</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="1">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="37" inc="1">Horses</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Andorra</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This is the first geocache placed in Andorra.&lt;br&gt;
You can leave the car in the village of Ordino, then walk to the nearby small village of Segudet and follow the path to the twin peaks of Casamanya.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The cache is near the trail (at the left side of the path if you are going up)at an altitude of approx. 1.500 meters, under an inclined fallen rock of about 1 meter x 0,60 meter.
&lt;p&gt;
The cache is a regular transparent plastic box.
&lt;p&gt;
Aquest va ser el primer cache creat a Andorra. La ruta d'accés més curta es des d'Ordino i Segudet, seguint la pista ampla que va cap al cims bessons del Casamanya.&lt;p&gt;
El cache es a prop de la pista (al costat esquerra pujant-hi) i a una alçada aproximada de 1500 metres. Està a sota d'una pedra inclinada que fà aprox. 1 metre per 60 cm.&lt;p&gt;
El cache es un contenidor transparent de plàstic.

Bona sort!
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>From the cache location you can see both the village of Ordino and one of the peaks of Casamanya.

Des del lloc del cache s'hi veu a l'hora Ordino i un dels pics del Casamanya.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364808053"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T14:37:25</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18764369">Lucie110</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Tijdens ons ver6in Andorra pakken we de oudste natuurlijk mee. Bedankt voor het zo lang in stand houden van deze cache!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364804776"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4318424">peugeotje</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We zijn vanuit Barcelona doorgereisd naar Andorra, waar we een nacht hebben gestaan tussen de indrukwekkende bergen. Na een mooie reis zijn we vandaag op pad om Andorra al geocachend te ontdekken. Samen met Lucie110, Jibby67 en Marsso gaan we op zoek naar bijzondere caches en genieten we van de prachtige omgeving. Een mooie combinatie van avontuur, natuur en geocaching. Op naar weer veel leuke vondsten en mooie herinneringen!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364179536"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="22142248">Carrotking</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">🥵 From the parking lot to this oldie, it is aporox. 1.5km BUT 200m in altitude difference 🥵 We took the shortest route - which is quite steep and not so easy to walk 🧗‍♀️ There is an easier oath which is about 500m longer and much easier to walk 🤓
But HEY - we are talking about an oldie 🥳 In GZ, I had no problem to find it &amp; put my name in the logbook 😅
T4TOLDC, Carrotking</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364801130"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13743385">danjoa</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hier in Andorra waren wir zwei Tage auf dem Campingplatz.

Da wollten wir unbedingt auch den ältesten Cache Andorras finden.

Vielen Dank und einen Gruss 


**danjoa**


aus Ahlem (Hannover, Germany 🇩🇪)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363765252"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T10:18:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="20508592">stephi83</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Heute war unser zweiter Tag in Andorra. Dabei haben wir uns einige Caches heraus gesucht, die wir auf unserer Tour besuchen wollten. Teils konnten wir kurze Stopps einlegen, teils mussten wir etwas weiter wandern, um den Cache zu erreichen. Es waren sehr schöne Gegenden und Wege dabei. 

Danke fürs Herführen und Legen des Caches.

Avui ha estat el nostre segon dia a Andorra. Vam triar alguns caixes que volíem visitar durant la nostra ruta. En alguns casos vam poder fer aturades ràpides, mentre que en d'altres vam haver de caminar una mica més per arribar al caixe. Hi havia zones i senders realment preciosos pel camí. 

Gràcies per portar-nos-hi i per amagar el caixe.

In: FP</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-9.36275" lon="13.154583"><time>2007-06-03T00:00:00</time><name>GC13NMV</name><desc>Luanda - Barra do Kwanza - Bico by Rodolfo Sousa e Paulo Arroteia</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC13NMV</url><urlname>Luanda - Barra do Kwanza - Bico</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="622601" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Luanda - Barra do Kwanza - Bico</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Rodolfo Sousa e Paulo Arroteia</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="995066">rsousa</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="0">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="1">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Angola</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Luanda, Barra do Kwanza - Bico</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>You can choose ocean water or river water...

Good place to fish too.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1228068095"><groundspeak:date>2024-04-16T10:42:01</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Due to no response from the CO after the request to maintain or replace the cache, I am archiving it to, stop it showing on the listings  and/or to create place for the geocaching community.

The [Geocache Maintenance guideline](http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) explains a CO's responsibility towards checking and maintaining the cache when problems are reported. 

Please note that if geocaches are archived by a reviewer or Geocaching HQ for lack of maintenance, they are not eligible for unarchival. This is explained in the [Help Center](http://support.groundspeak.com//index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=70)

If the CO feels that this cache has been archived in error please feel free to contact me within 30 days,  via email or message via my profile ,quoting the GC number concerned

Thank you for understanding

Knagur Green</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1208360359"><groundspeak:date>2023-12-12T17:25:16</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings 

We have received a request to archive your cache page as the physical cache appears to be in need of maintenance and there has been no recent indication that timely maintenance may be forthcoming.

 I'm temporarily disabling it, to give you an opportunity to check on the cache, and take whatever action is necessary.

You are responsible for occasional visits to your cache to ensure it is in proper working order, especially when someone reports a problem with the cache (missing, damaged, wet, etc.) or posts a Needs Maintenance log. Temporarily disable your cache to let others know not to search for it until you have addressed the problem.

Please enable your cache by selecting 'enable' on the right hand side of the listing , once the cache has been replaced/repaired, or checked that it is still in situ.

The [Geocache Maintenance guideline](http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) explains a CO's responsibility towards checking and maintaining the cache when problems are reported. 

Caches that have been archived for lack of maintenance will not be unarchived. This is explained in the [Help Center](http://support.groundspeak.com//index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=70)

If you no longer wish to maintain the cache then the listing should be archived.

**Please respond to this situation in a timely manner (i.e., within 30 days) to prevent the cache from being archived for non-responsiveness. If you plan on repairing this cache,but cannot get to it within 30 days, please log a note to the cache page (not email) to let the community know**

Thank you for understanding 

Knagur Green
Groundspeak Volunteer Reviewer

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1208108476"><groundspeak:date>2023-12-09T23:30:16</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Needs Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3968299">Kesj-Sjeng</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This CO is not acting against bogus logs by trolls, which is one of the tasks of a CO. If no further action is taken, the cache should be archived!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1208108394"><groundspeak:date>2023-12-09T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3968299">Kesj-Sjeng</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">JD2115420692137 is a TROLL. Please delete his log... His account is already locked by Groundspeak HQ...

The three other logs beneath it are clearly also bogus logs!!! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1207099993"><groundspeak:date>2023-11-27T00:45:40</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="47924091">RoRoLannyandPiper</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Sh</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="17.129717" lon="-61.886233"><time>2002-05-08T00:00:00</time><name>GC5D78</name><desc>Lookout Point by TonyD</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC5D78</url><urlname>Lookout Point</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="23928" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Lookout Point</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>TonyD</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="52409">TonyD</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="10" inc="1">Difficult climb</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Antigua and Barbuda</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Beautiful site high above Deep Bay. Short hike is required up a steep rocky slope. Park at footbridge at end of road. While the climb looks ominous it can be made in 10 - 15 minutes at a leisurely pace. At the top you will be rewarded with a breathtaking view of Deep Bay, St. John's and the Northwest coastline.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;big&gt;CELEBRATING 20 YEARS! Thank you to the 358 Geocachers that found this site over the first 2 decades!! Looking forward to many more adventurous visitors.&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Fort Barrington was built by the British in 1779 as a lookout to protect the island's sugar cane fields from the French.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To verify that you found the cache and claim credit for the find e-mail me the number of rooms inside of the fort. Don't post your answer on the web site.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364115697"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="16647547">cacheregisterer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hiked up the hill while moored at Deep Bay during a catamaran trip around the island with friends.  The stretch with the rope was interesting, but the view was worth it!  TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1353977095"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3487834">der_asterix</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Während meiner 2-wöchigen Karibik-Cruise mit der Mein Schiff 2 konnte ich verschiedene Inseln und Länder besuchen.
Jede Insel war anderes und vielfälltig.

Ob Tradi, Eartchcache, Virtueller oder Multi, alles war dabei.
Die benötigten Antworten bze Fotos sind dem Log beigefügt bzw dem Owner zukommen gelassen.

Vielen Dank an alle Owner für die versteckten Doen in  einem für mich neuen Gebiet

Tftc 


During my two-week Caribbean cruise on the Mein Schiff 2, I was able to visit various islands and countries.

Each island was different and diverse.

Whether traditional, earthcache, virtual, or multi-cache, there was something for everyone.

The required answers and photos are attached to the log or have been sent to the cache owner.

Many thanks to all the cache owners for the hidden caches in a new area for me.

Tftc
30.03.26 16:24
der_asterix
8731</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1348545002"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-10T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4171204">wdo66</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Was für ein geschichtsträchtiger Ort! Heute ging es hinauf zum Fort Barrington, um diesen Klassiker aus dem Jahr 2002 zu besuchen. Der Aufstieg bei der karibischen Wärme war zwar kurz, aber knackig – die Aussicht über die Deep Bay entschädigt jedoch für jeden Schweißtropfen. Mega Aussicht ! Alleine das lohnt sich schon.
Besonders spannend war es dann, die alten Gemäuer zu erkunden. 
Die Beobachtungsaufgabe wurde an TonyD geschickt.
Vielen Dank an TonyD für das Legen und die jahrzehntelange Pflege dieses Virtuals. Es ist toll, durch unser Hobby an solche Orte geführt zu werden! Ein blaues Schleifchen (Favoritenpunkt) ist hier Ehrensache. FP in. TFTC [:)]</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1347319221"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-03T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="23833049">oz8118</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Answers sent! I just had to target Goat Hill with historic Fort Barrington today which had THREE caches along the trail. It was a steep climb, and in that sense it reminded me a little bit of home. I took my time and spend about an hour here, hiking up and down, and looking for all the caches, taking photos, and admiring the spectacular views. 
Greetings from Denver, Colorado USA, the Mile High City (that’s 1,609 meters in elevation)! I’m on vacation visiting the beautiful Caribbean to cure my winter blues, and find lots of caches along the way. It’s so exciting to have lots of nice caches to find in paradise. I’m perusing around with a rental car today that I picked up at the airport. Then it’s the Beyoncé song 🎶 in my head all day…”to the left, to the left, everything ya own to the left.”

Thanks for placing and maintaining this cache so I could earn a smiley TonyD!  Lookout Point -  GC5D78, is number 8163 that I have found. The cache was located on Tuesday, March 3, 2026. Happy caching, cheers! 🙂</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1350825309"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-02T19:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5978522">Yvne</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Unseren Urlaub genossen wir 14 Tage auf der Mein Schiff 2, 
mit der wir in der Karibik die kleinen Antillen besuchten
und neben den traumhaften Stränden auch hübsche 
Orte und Natur erlebet haben.

Im Anschluss haben wir noch eine Woche auf Puerto Rico verbracht. 

Diese wunderbare Insel haben wir mit einem Leihwagen bereist 
und waren von dem Regenwald sowie den Bergen und den Wasserfällen fasziniert.


Grüße und Danke an alle Owner, die uns eine wundervolle Reise nebst vielen erstaunlichen Blickwinkeln und tolle Aussichten in dieser beeindruckenden Natur gezeigt haben.


Yvne auf toller Reise sonnig unterwegs 
mit dem besten Reiseleiter DreiD [:D]</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-31.253617" lon="-57.975233"><time>2001-08-21T00:00:00</time><name>GC181D</name><desc>Geocache by pirata morgan</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC181D</url><urlname>Geocache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Unknown Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="6173" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Geocache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>pirata morgan</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="20316">____Pirata_Morgan</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Unknown Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Argentina</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Cerca de Concordia y el Lago de Salto Grande. El camino pasa al lado. Una piedra sera la clave.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Dentro de un viejo baul, un tesoro que te refrescara.
Cuidado, no sacar con las manos, puede haber serpientes venenosas. Usa un palo, es mas seguro. </groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Nada sera dicho aqui.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1324438771"><groundspeak:date>2025-07-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5669630">VCX1302</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Together with Valeetje I embarked on a very special journey : A little trip around the south of South America of find our second APE cache and to add some new countries to our list. We started in Brasil, where we visited Sao Paolo, Intervales, Rio de Janeiro, Paraty and finally Iguazu. And yes, we visited Rocinha as well ...

From Foz de Iguasu we visited Paraguay and crossed the border into Argentina. From Puerto Iguassu we went to Buenos Aires, Concordia, Sante Fe and Rosario. And we ferried across to Colonia de Sacramento to find the oldest cache in Uruguay as well.

Then we went further south ... Visiting the whales near the Valdes peninsula, going to marvel at the Perito Moreno glaciar and finally reach our southernmost destination : Ushuaia and Tierra del Fuego.

Time for another country! Chili is just nearby ... Puerto Montt was our first destination there. After a visit at the Petrohue waterfalls (with the fabulous view on the Osorno vulcano) we drove due north to end up in Conception. Along the way we were able to visited some fantastic landmarks : the Laja waterfalls, Conguillio, Captren waterfall, ...

Next on the list : San Pedro de Atacama, with a roadtrip in the vicinity to visit the famous Vale de la luna, Chaxa, Vale de Jere, ... And we had a little fotoshoot when crossing the Tropic of Capricorn.

Finally we crossed the border (at 4000m abocee sealevel) into Bolivia for a 3 day 4x4 trip to the Salar de Uyuni. Wonderfull places and views were plentifull! In Uyuni we enjoyed the musical procession and stayed overnight in a converted railway coach.

What else did we visit in Bolivia? We went down into the silvermines of Potosi and climbed to the "Ojo de inca". In Sucre we admired the dinosaur trail in Cal Orck'o and the amazing view from recoleta. We went to Cochabamba for the oldest Bolivian cache and managed to log an FTF along the way. And finally we ended our trip in La Paz, but not without first visiting Tiwanaku and the Isla del Sol in Titicaca.

A very big "Thank you" for Valeetje is in order! She managed to conceive, plan and organize this fantastic journey! And she managed to put up with me during 44 days, which seems incredible ;)

I would like to thank all CO's for placing and maintaining your caches! They helped us greatly to devise such a great adventure!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1322161441"><groundspeak:date>2025-07-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5310011">valeetje</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This summer, we (Valeetje and VCX1302) were fortunate enough to spend 45 days in South America. We started our trip in Brazil. From there, we headed to Paraguay, Argentina, Uruguay, Chile, and finally, Bolivia. We mostly picked the cherries off the cake, taking lots of excursions in a rental car or tour van. We were able to enjoy all that beauty thanks to geocaching. Thanks to all the contributors who are part of this. I think my buddy's log is much more comprehensive; enjoy our story there!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1249704581"><groundspeak:date>2024-07-11T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="50250045">Gigas12</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Buscamos entre 3 personas y no lo pudimos encontrar. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1156579203"><groundspeak:date>2023-04-02T17:47:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="41850704">Kingpirux</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">el nuevo</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1156578749"><groundspeak:date>2023-04-02T17:45:26</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="41850704">Kingpirux</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">no lo encontré :( tenia mucha ilusión... dejamos uno Nuevo en ziplock porque es lo único que tenía a mano.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="12.602251" lon="-70.02626"><time>2002-05-17T00:00:00</time><name>GC5A9A</name><desc>Wish Rock Garden by Steve White</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC5A9A</url><urlname>Wish Rock Garden</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="23194" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Wish Rock Garden</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Steve White</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="29289">scwhite</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="55" inc="1">Short hike (&lt;1 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Aruba</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;p&gt;April 2019 - My most sincere gratitude to CCSGA for replacing the container and contents. Also for sending me the old log book. I can't thank him enough!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;On the North shore toward the West end of the Wish Rock Garden area of the island.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;The Wish Rock Garden is an area nearly a mile long along the North Shore. People have for years made small stacks of rocks that are meant to protect this island from storms and other evils. There are probably hundreds of thousands of stacks of rocks along the road.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The location will require that you have some form of transportation. The tours go by here but don't stop long enough for you to find this cache. I rated it difficult because you will need a vehicle and the site itself is so full of rocks that you will probably have to search pretty hard to find it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Initially I placed several Aruban souveniers in the cache that includes postcards, 2 key rings, 1 bottle opener, a log book &amp;amp; pen, and The Stamp Collector Travel Bug.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>[No hiding this hint- This is hard enough as it is. You will have to rely heavily on your GPS. The cache is under a large boulder South of the road and up the hill. There are some spent rifle shells in front of the boulder. I have included a photo that shows the area. I was sitting on the boulder when I took the photo. A good starting point is the California Lighthouse. Stay out of the sand but take the dirt road to the east along the coast.]</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1362282831"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T08:23:14</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="30795561">kayajean1999</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Fun find. Trackers left</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362282753"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T08:20:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="30795561">kayajean1999</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Difficult find, Breezy day on the island. Dropped  of trackers</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354244854"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-09T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5105270">Zascandiles</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Alcanzar la Zona Cero no ha sido sencillo. Íbamos en un vehículo tipo turismo y nos hemos sdentrado en la pista con cuidado. Cuando estábamos a unos 900 metros del caché,  el terreno se ponía más complicado y hemos optado por dejar el vehículo y seguir a pie. Así hemos alcanzado la Zona Cero y, tras buscar en la zona indicada por el GPS,  hemos encontrado el caché más antiguo de Aruba con gran alegría y alborozo.  Hechas las fotos de rigor (no las publicamos en el logbook para no destripar) iniciamos el descenso y caminata de regreso.

Punto favorito 

Muchas gracias Steve White por el caché y por mostrarnos este lugar.

Puedes seguir nuestras aventuras en Instagram: @geozascandiles

https://www.instagram.com/geozascandiles?igsh=dzlxemZ1ZDZhN2d0</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354166686"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-09T11:40:37</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1406954">biggdipper</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found with the FOT crew of geocachers. Thanks for the fun</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354581824"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-08T14:23:42</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1838490">beemerdon</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Here with the caching and cruising group, Castaway Cachers, on the Regal Princess this week. Nice hide! Favorite point for the oldest cache. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-33.78755" lon="151.14625"><time>2000-05-18T00:00:00</time><name>GC3E</name><desc>Lane Cove by Paul Edwards</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC3E</url><urlname>Lane Cove</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="62" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Lane Cove</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Paul Edwards</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="692">kerravon</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Australia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>New South Wales</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Australia's first cache - but now virtual
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;This geocache is/was located in the Lane Cove National Park, in the lower-north suburbs of Sydney, NSW, Australia. It is/was Australia's first cache, planted 2000-05-18.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first geocache in the southern hemisphere was GC45 in New Zealand, which was placed on 2000-05-12. This was apparently trashed by a muggle, never officially found (I personally would have counted the bucket itself as a find), and archived. A plaque has apparently been placed there, but I don't think that is findable for some reason. Regardless, I personally consider Australia beaten fair and square by GC45.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
My cache was originally a traditional cache, but the bucket was confiscated by whatever the "rangers" are called (I think they don't like being called that). I think someone suggested that I make it "virtual", so at some point I edited the description to say it was virtual. I wasn't involved in geocaching myself at the time (the second cache in Sydney or Australia - "Sydney Cache"? - had a snake waiting for me when I attempted to find it (by cutting through the bush) and I decided to find a hobby that had fewer physical literal snakes). So I didn't know "virtual" was a field (note that my cache predated geocaching.com even existing, I believe - probably the word "cache" too - it was "stash" in the very early days). Years later Geocaching NSW explained to me that it was a field, and organized getting permission to have it grandfathered as a virtual and helped me with questions that accompany virtuals. I think almost everyone is happy that the rules were bent, but please note that that was a group decision for historical reasons that was considered to benefit the hobby, not something I did unilaterally. Probably GC45 being located a long way from the nearest opera house (albeit a lot closer to boiling mud) gave it less care/attention/interest. Another factor is probably that traditionally there are only two countries in the entire world that ever care about or use the phrase "first in the xyz hemisphere".
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyway, as explained further below, this cache was placed in an unfortunate position, so DO NOT GO TO THE EXACT SPOT. There is nothing to see, and with the cache removed, and 7-metre accuracy, I can't even recognize the exact spot myself.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note that it is illegal to plant caches in national parks without permission. Something which should be obvious, but the sort of people who would hang around a newsgroup like sci.geo.satellite-nav are not necessarily experts at the bleeding obvious, unlike Sybil (ref: Fawlty Towers).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This spot was chosen because it was believed to be remote and uninteresting, so that no-one would ever stumble on it by mistake. Unfortunately, life isn't that simple. Some places in the park have been designated as remote places suitable for growing rare plants. I managed to place mine where they were growing Darwinia Biflora. Secondly, people normally stick to the walking tracks (as they are supposed to), rather than heading into the scrub. So placing the cache there provides unexpected attention to some normally undisturbed scrub. Thirdly, your shoes carry weeds from one place to another, and with cache hunters arriving from unexected directions, this causes unexpected problems. Fourthly, during bushfire season, backburning may be done, and the rangers need to know of unexpected people before they commit homicide! :-)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, history can't be changed, and these are the coordinates of Australia's first geocache, and people still regularly go to it. Some consider it to be the Mecca of Australian geocaching, and indeed, it was the site chosen for the Australian gathering of the 10 year (and 15 year) anniversary of geocaching. In addition, I was wrong about it being a non-descript area. I actually went so deep into the bush (from the nearby park with toilet facilities) that I almost reached an official walking track. The official walking track even has stairs. Do not go to my cache via any entrance other than the official stairs!!! In addition, the walking track takes you to a beautiful outlook (located S33 47.252 E151 08.804) to the Lane Cove River, so make sure you see that.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are a number of entrances to the National Park, and the one I used was at S33 47.5649 E151 09.3768 and (as of 2010), it costs $8 to enter the national park with your car. However, if you're just here for the cache, there is free and convenient parking at the end of Plassey Rd (S33 47.322 E151 08.584). You get there by turning off Delhi Rd (intersection is S33 47.695 E151 08.466 - could someone please confirm?). After parking your car, it is a short walk (400 meters, maybe 5 minutes walk) to the stone stairs you need to go to. You will pass by a park which has toilet and BBQ facilities. In actual fact, sometimes the gates are open so that you can drive even closer to the stairs. You probably can't park exactly at the stairs and instead will need to park at the park. Note that it takes about 30 minutes to walk from North Ryde Station (located at S33 47.667 E151 08.282 - could someone please give an accurate waypoint?) to the cache.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache's position was averaged for about 30 minutes so has an estimated accuracy of 7m.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since this cache is now virtual, please email me with the answers to the following questions:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1. How close (I'm requesting the answer in metric to encourage Americans to enter the 19th century) can you get to GZ without leaving the track that goes around it? [hint - this also doubles-up as an incentive to stay on the walking track, because that's where the answer is, not GZ]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;2. You enter the walking track via a set of stone stairs (S33 47.225 E151 08.801) on Plassey Rd. How many steps are there at this location? Count both the bottom step and the very top. I just need the number for the single block of stairs. Don't worry about the wooden steps a little further from the top, and the solitary sandstone step after that.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please do not put the answer to these questions in the log, otherwise I will encrypt the log. Also, since most people will get the answer right (this isn't rocket science), if you don't receive a reply from me within 24 hours, you can assume that you are right and log the visit. Note that I operate on the honor system. I do read and validate the answers provided, but I do not reply unless there is a direct request or question. So if you would like me to do something specific, please speak up. Note that we are attempting to get a plaque of some sort placed near GZ. Hopefully something will come of that in the future. In the meantime, enjoy!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here is a summary of the important waypoints:&lt;br /&gt;
CACHE S33 47.2527 E151 08.7752 Do not go here, nothing to see&lt;br /&gt;
BEAUTY S33 47.252 E151 08.804 Beautiful outlook to Lane Cove River&lt;br /&gt;
FREEPK S33 47.322 E151 08.584 Free parking in Plassey Rd&lt;br /&gt;
PAYENT S33 47.5649 E151 09.3768 $7 entry fee on Delhi Rd&lt;br /&gt;
INTERS S33 47.695 E151 08.466 Intersection of Delhi Rd and Plassey Rd&lt;br /&gt;
NRYDET S33 47.667 E151 08.282 North Ryde train station&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you would like to know more information about how this cache became Australia's first, go to this link: http://mutazilah.org/kerravon/gps.htm especially http://www.geocachingnsw.asn.au/index.php/geocaching/what-is-geocaching/127-first-geocacher and http://mutazilah.org/kerravon/gpswhyme.htm&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1361586412"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-17T16:52:24</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="35240472">fourtwelve</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings from this Victorian Cacher! Cache-specific stuff in this paragraph; generic stuff for this big trip in subsequent paragraphs. Thank you for placing this cache, which I have attended today, on day 7 of my trip. Attached photo taken nearby, showing some of the lovely wildlife enjoying the morning. Answers will be sent shortly. Favourite point awarded too.

I am currently on a 3.5-week trip during rostered 4-weeks of annual leave. Overall intent for the trip is to go in a hired geomobile the coastal way from home through Lakes Entrance and Jervis Bay Territory, thence Wollongong, a detour for the Thirlmere festival of steam, and thence continue around the outer suburbs of Sydney, thence up the coast to Cairns, with some detours inland for Tamworth, Toowoomba and Charters Towers, with hired geomobile to be returned in Cairns. Thence from Cairns, via overnight train to Brisbane for a day with a (muggle) friend I only see infrequently, thence a couple of daytime trains to Sydney and Victoria (with a full day in Sydney for more caching too). Aiming to get a lot of challenge caches signed along the way, plus many other caches too.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361506496"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-17T06:11:12</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21641700">Tiango3</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Het was mijn droom hier ooit een geocache te doen. Ik ben blij dat ik deze VIRTUELE heb kunnen oplossen. 
Paul Edards bedankt om deze te tonen.  👍👍👍</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359670125"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-08T09:31:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5240613">Teahan_family_hk</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A bucket list cache ticked off. Awesome. I have also found the iconic Nz and Ireland oldest caches as well. Lovely
Walk in the park. TFTC. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358501124"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="12986343">ullyssia</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thank you! It's the first day of caching for me and papillon367 while on a short visit to Sydney. 
Happy to make the find here while visiting the national park. This cache was actually the  number one priority for the trip, as papillon367 wanted to celebrate a caching milestone.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358437602"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-02T11:33:49</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8502824">papillon367</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thank you for the cache kerravon, a special cache that I saved to be my 10,000th find 🙂!!!
Teamed up with ullyssia and came across from WA to discover the area and fill out several Jasmer spots, including this one.
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="818939595"><groundspeak:date>2018-12-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">What a small world it is!  Thanks to Seemyshell who I meet at the Giga in Cinci last summer when he was caching across America.  A few weeks ago, I posted on the Geocaching NSW holiday party event that I would be in Sydney and would love to attend but would have to workout transportation.  A couple days later, I get an email that he will pick me up!  Had a great time at the event / picnic (except the giant spider) and on the way back to the hotel, he detoured to get me close to GC3E, the oldest geocache in Australia!  Thanks Mate!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="47.571783333333336" lon="13.606916666666667"><time>2001-07-23T00:00:00</time><name>GC1298</name><desc>Salzig Hund by blackfrancis, FloToZach, Steff &amp; Mister</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1298</url><urlname>Salzig Hund</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="4760" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Salzig Hund</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>blackfrancis, FloToZach, Steff &amp; Mister</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="2530">blackfrancis</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Austria</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Oberösterreich</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>As this cache is located near the summit of a mountain, one should expect a good 2 to 4 hour hike to reach it. The altitude change is from about 800m to 1950m.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Begin in the Austrian town of Hallstatt at 500m above sea level. From there, you may hike all the way up to the summit, or you may take the tram up to 850m where there is an entrance to the salt mines (hence the "Salzig" part of the name). The hike from there will take from 2-4 hours, depending upon your stamina. I went up with some good friends from Austria named Flo, Tobi, and Steff, and we were joined by Dorli &amp; Steff's dog named "Mister" (hence the "Hund" part of the name). These guys had climbed this mountain many times and didn't seem too winded. I was hurtin', but I don't think I slowed them down too much. I was relieved to hear that their legs were as sore as mine for the next few days.&lt;BR&gt;
Since there are many possible trails, I'll give the hint that you're looking for the summit with the large cross placed on top of it. From the summit you will have a brilliant view of the Hallstaetter See, and also of the Dachstein Glacier. The cache is not right at the summit, but slightly lower. Beware the sheep!&lt;BR&gt;
Hallstatt is a nice alpine lake town, so you'll find good camping, pensions, hotels and restaurants there. We camped in Hallstadt, but I've heard that the camping in nearby Obertraun is better.
&lt;P&gt;
At the beginning, the cache contains a speaking watch (speaks only German!), a disposable camera, a logbook with a pen, a beer bottlecap with a 10 ATS coin, and a pair of large sunglasses. You should bring your own pen and/or pencil because the cold air might render the pen useless. I didn't have a pencil with me, so if you visit the cache, please bring one to leave there.
&lt;P&gt;
OK, Viel Spass!</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The cache is in an ammo box at the side of a field where some sheep were grazing. In the field are three or four depression holes that look like old bomb craters (filled in with grass now). The cache is near a fixed boulder and covered with rocks.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364819293"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2125804">Beetovy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">🧮5238 ⌚13:45
My friends and I are on a cycling vacation in the Alps. Our base is in Bad Goisern and go on day trips from there.
Today we did 59,09km and 1465m ascent. I did extra 4,45km and with 495m ascent hiking for the cache. I had to take opportunity to find the oldest cache in Austria. It wasn't so easy in cycling shoes. 

Thank you for the cache. Greetings from Czechia.
IN: FP OUT: TB</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1324621939"><groundspeak:date>2025-09-17T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1555829">MZCacheHunter</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**Zur Info**
Aktuell ist zumindest der beschriebene Weg aufgrund umfangreicher Bauarbeiten in Hallstatt nicht möglich. 
Weder ist die Hallstatter Bergbahn in Betrieb noch der Wanderweg begehbar, da abgesperrt. Siehe Bild. 
Vorläufig ist der Cache also nur über alternative Wege zum Gipfel von Norden oder Osten aus erreichbar. 

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1321668807"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2866496">jozefeg</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#10235

This year we didn’t go to the Tatras, so I thought of going to Austria and checking out the oldest cache there. Baladiska protested for a bit but then agreed to come along. After all, the hill isn’t that high.
And since we were already there, we planned to explore the surroundings and see some beautiful lakes. That was the plan. We stayed for three nights in Gosau, where Baladiska had been on a family vacation about 20 years ago. The irony is that back then, she didn’t really like it here and wanted to go to the sea instead. And yet, here she was again.

On the first day, we were surprised by the closure of the official trail due to construction work and a light rain that lasted the entire hike up to Plassen. Only at the top did the sun come out, and within an hour I even got sunburned. Our shoes were completely soaked, Baladiska was miserable, and she predicted she’d get sick from the cold. So far, she’s okay.

We found the cache without any problems, which was nice. In this weather, though, it was a bit more challenging.

Big thanks to blackfrancis, FloToZach, Steff &amp; Mister for creating and maintaining this cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1320537340"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10102634">PaLaRunCa</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Austria's oldest, the last highlight and main goal of our summer holidays! The only goal today was getting all 4 of us up the mountain and at this old treasure! The hiking trail up to Salzwelten was closed due to construction works, so the only option we had was to take the cable car up at 9 am. If we would work at the same speed in our job at home as they opened the ticket office, I'm sure we wouldn't be here on holidays now... Anyway, at about 9h45 we could finally start our hike up. At our own secure pace, we ascended the steep slopes step by step, meter by meter, at times with a climbing percentage of over 35%! Also the rope part was tackled. After over a decade of back problems, especially for mama getting to this cache is a huge achievement!! So the only goal we had to day was bring our whole family to this iconic cache, no matter how long it took us! Of course, we also took our time for birdwatching, taking plenty of pictures, picknicking and so on. We reached gz and found the cache at 14h22. Mission accomplished!!! I'm so extremely proud that we made it here together!!! We were back at the cable car at 18h10, 10 minutes to late to take the last cable car ride down. The only option we had was to go through the construction works and climb past the fence to hike all the way down, so we hiked back down the full 1417m of altitude! Back at the car at 19h21. We rewarded ourselves with a few big, big beers, schnitzel and apfelstrüdel! :) 

Austria is the 46th country where we find the nation's oldest! Of course, a huge favo for this beautiful oldie and for our own achievement!!! 😀❤️🇦🇹


---

General log for our summer holidays:

Deze zomer maken we met het hele gezin een 18-daagse roadtrip door de Balkan. We doorkruisen in totaal 10 landen (waarvan 5 nieuwe op onze gc-kaart): België 🇧🇪, Duitsland 🇩🇪, Oostenrijk 🇦🇹, Slovenië 🇸🇮, Kroatië 🇭🇷, Bosnië en Herzegovina 🇧🇦, Montenegro 🇲🇪, Servië 🇷🇸, Noord-Macedonië 🇲🇰 en Albanië 🇦🇱. Eigenlijk zijn het er 11, alleen wordt Kosovo 🇽🇰 jammer genoeg nog niet als geocacheland gezien. 

In alle landen waar we komen proberen we zoals steeds de oudste te vinden, daarnaast waar mogelijk ook 1 of meerdere challenges en zoveel mogelijk types en favo-waardige plekjes te bezoeken (ook al ligt er geen geocache). Misschien brengen wij daar dan zelf wel verandering in. We zien wel... 😉

Alhoewel onze 6000 km lange route grotendeels op onze favoriete hobby gebaseerd is, gaan we vooral ook gewoon genieten van de mooie natuur, de lokale keuken, de cultuur en natuurlijk van mekaar.

Hoogtepunten (om er toch een paar te noemen): Sarajevo, het Durmitor gebergte, de mooie natuur in Kosovo, Skopje en het meer van Ohrid, de bergen bij Theth, Kotor, Mostar, de kust bij Trogir, de watervallen van Plitviče, Pula en Istrië. Stille getuigen uit het oorlogsverleden en de vele lost places die je hier nog kunt aantreffen, maken een diepe indruk en de verhalen van destijds pijnlijk tastbaar. 

Bedankt aan alle leggers om hier weer een memorabele reis van te helpen maken! Groeten uit België!

---

This summer, we're taking an 18-day road trip through the Balkans with the whole family. We'll be crossing 10 countries in total (5 of which are new to our GC map): Belgium 🇧🇪, Germany 🇩🇪, Austria 🇦🇹, Slovenia 🇸🇮, Croatia 🇭🇷, Bosnia and Herzegovina 🇧🇦, Montenegro 🇲🇪, Serbia 🇷🇸, North Macedonia 🇲🇰 and Albania 🇦🇱. Actually, there are 11 countries, but unfortunately, Kosovo 🇽🇰 isn't considered a geocaching destination yet.

In every country we visit, we'll try, as always, to find the oldest ones, and whenever possible, we'll also take on one or more challenges and visit as many types and favorite spots as possible (even if there's no geocache). Maybe we'll change that ourselves. We'll see... 😉

Although our 6,000 km route is largely based on our favorite hobby, we'll also mainly enjoy the beautiful nature, the local cuisine, the culture, and of course, each other!

Highlights (to name a few): Sarajevo, the Durmitor Mountains, the beautiful nature in Kosovo, Skopje and Lake Ohrid, the mountains near Theth, Kotor, Mostar, the coast near Trogir, the Plitvice Waterfalls, Pula, and Istria. Silent witnesses from the war past and the many lost places you can still find here leave a deep impression, and the stories from that time are painfully tangible.

Thank you to everyone who helped make this another memorable trip!  Greetings from Belgium!

Tftc blackfrancis, FloToZach, Steff &amp; Mister!

Discovering our world one box at a time! 🌍 #31185

Rating when found: D3.0/T3.0

Feel free to discover the trackable on our gc profile! 🐒🦍</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1332116588"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3442087">discrepancy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Der Salzig Hund stand schon lange auf meiner To-Do-Liste. Ich habe zwar schon 5 ältere Dosen gefunden, 4 davon in den USA. Aber den ältesten Cache Österreichs wollte ich trotzdem unbedingt einmal in Händen halten.

Los marschiert bin ich in der Früh von Gosau. Irgendwie dachte ich mir, das wäre eine gute Idee. Kürzere Autofahrt und dem Trubel in Hallstatt entgehen… Der Zustieg hat sich dann aber doch recht gezogen, mir aber andererseits einen wunderschönen, einsamen Bergtag beschert. Ich habe versucht, die Forststraße wo möglich zu vermeiden, was die Sache dann aber auch sehr abenteuerlich gemacht hat. Beim Aufstieg bin ich dem Pfad über Marxenalm und Schreieralm gefolgt. Die Querung der steile Waldflanke nach der Marxenalm war wohl die Schlüsselstelle der Tour und ist bei Nässe sicher nicht zu empfehlen. Den Rückweg habe ich über die Rossalm genommen, wobei der auf OSM eingezeichnete Fußweg kaum noch erkennbar ist. Ohne Karte am GPS wäre ich mehrmals vom Weg abgekommen. Der eigentliche Aufstieg auf den Plassen über den Nordgrat war im Vergleich dazu ein Spaziergang.

Den Cache konnte ich nach kurzer Suche finden. So eine schöne Ammo-Box aus den Urzeiten unseres Hobbys! Ich habe mir viel Zeit genommen, im Originallogbuch zu schmökern. Leider war es recht feucht. Ich habe es in die Sonne zum trocknen gelegt, während ich EC und Gipfel besuchte habe, um es dann, um einiges trockener als vorgefunden, wieder einzupacken.

Vielen Dank für diesen tollen Cache und die schöne Wanderung. Gerne lasse ich einen FP da.

Cache #4721 gefunden um 12:01 Uhr.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="39.994417" lon="49.40575"><time>2007-09-30T00:00:00</time><name>GC16BJJ</name><desc>Mud Volcano Cache by David</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC16BJJ</url><urlname>Mud Volcano Cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="702294" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Mud Volcano Cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>David</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1293982">david.guymon</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Azerbaijan</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Mud Volcanoes near Gobustan, AZ. Rocky terrain, sandals not reccomended.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Located on a small volcanic rock formation within view of several mud volcanoes.  Nestled in a small depression, covered with rocks dissimilar to their immediate surroundings.  The cache is a 100 x 200 x 60mm Plastic, outdoor electrical junction box, inside a clear plastic bag. The origional contents of the box are: Log book, small plastic compass, several small keychains, candle, lighter, and other goodies.

This cache requires a flat head screwdriver to open.  A small bright orange screwdiver has been placed at the base of a power pole just off the access road.  The location of the screwdiver was chosen such that the best access road would be used.

The location of the screwdriver is:
N 39deg 58.416min
E 49deg 23.589min

Since there are no road maps for Azerbaijan(that I know of at least), turn off the highway at:
N 39deg 57.963min
E 49deg 24.362min</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1361988224"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-16T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15085111">Keen Barete</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Between Caucasian mountain peaks, rough gravel roads and Soviet relics, our journey took us across Georgia, Armenia and Azerbaijan — partly by plane, but mostly by car on roads that sometimes barely deserved the name.

We drove through deep green valleys, past snow-covered mountains, across endless serpentines and rocky tracks that often pushed both car and nerves to their limits. Behind every curve another world appeared: remote villages where time seemed to have stopped decades ago, vast empty landscapes without another soul in sight, and suddenly magnificent cities filled with grand architecture, clean parks, monuments and art installations on nearly every corner.

Especially in Armenia and Georgia, stray dogs were everywhere. Even in abandoned places they suddenly emerged from ruins or side streets, silently watching us. Cows, horses, pigs and chickens roamed freely through villages and across roads as if humans were merely guests in their world. In Azerbaijan, however, cats seemed to dominate the streets and old towns.

One of the most memorable moments of the journey was meeting the honorary consul Aleksan Ter-Minasyan, who personally guided us through his collections and shared countless fascinating stories about Armenian culture and history. Equally unforgettable was the stressful border crossing between Georgia and Armenia, which demanded patience and strong nerves.

We explored ancient churches and monasteries, visited breathtaking cave and rock cities, hiked through untouched nature and stood before mountain ranges still covered in snow. Many villages felt like stepping back into the times of the former East Germany — old Ladas, crumbling facades, improvised workshops and a unique atmosphere somewhere between past and present.

But it was exactly these contrasts that made the journey so special. The different mentalities of the people, the constantly changing landscapes and the feeling of entering completely new worlds every single day turned this trip into a true adventure.

This journey will stay in our memories forever.

Zwischen Kaukasusgipfeln, Schlaglöchern und sowjetischen Relikten führte uns diese Reise quer durch Georgien, Armenien und Aserbaidschan – mit dem Flugzeug, vor allem aber mit dem Auto über Straßen, die diesen Namen manchmal kaum verdienten.

Wir fuhren durch tiefe grüne Täler, vorbei an schneebedeckten Bergen, über endlose Serpentinen und Geröllpisten, die uns mehr als einmal den Atem anhielten ließen. Hinter jeder Kurve wartete eine andere Welt: abgelegene Dörfer, in denen die Zeit scheinbar stehen geblieben war, riesige Weiten ohne Menschenseele, dann wieder prachtvolle Städte mit sauberen Parkanlagen, monumentalen Gebäuden, Denkmälern und Kunstobjekten an nahezu jeder Ecke.

Besonders in Armenien und Georgien gehörten wilde Hunde zum Straßenbild. Selbst an verlassenen Orten tauchten sie plötzlich aus Ruinen oder Seitengassen auf und beobachteten uns aufmerksam. Kühe, Pferde, Schweine und Hühner bewegten sich dort mit einer Selbstverständlichkeit über Straßen und Wege, als würden die Menschen eher bei ihnen zu Gast sein als umgekehrt. In Aserbaidschan dagegen prägten Katzen das Bild der Städte und Gassen.

Unvergessen bleibt die Begegnung mit dem Honorarkonsul Aleksan Ter-Minasyan, der uns persönlich durch seine Sammlungen führte, Geschichten erzählte und uns einen tiefen Einblick in Kultur und Geschichte Armeniens gab. Ebenso werden wir den nervenaufreibenden Grenzübergang zwischen Georgien und Armenien nicht vergessen, der Geduld und starke Nerven verlangte.

Wir standen vor uralten Kirchen und Klöstern, erkundeten Felsen- und Höhlenstädte, wanderten durch nahezu unberührte Natur und blickten auf Gipfel, die selbst im Frühjahr noch schneebedeckt waren. Viele Orte fühlten sich an wie eine Reise zurück in die DDR-Zeit – alte Ladas, bröckelnde Fassaden, improvisierte Werkstätten und Dörfer, in denen Moderne und Vergangenheit auf bizarre Weise ineinander übergingen.

Doch gerade diese Gegensätze machten die Reise so besonders. Die unterschiedlichen Mentalitäten der Menschen, die wechselnden Landschaften und das Gefühl, immer wieder in völlig neue Welten einzutauchen, machten jeden einzelnen Tag zu einem Abenteuer.

Diese Reise wird uns noch sehr lange in Erinnerung bleiben!

Vielen Dank an david.guymon für den Traditional-Cache! Gefunden am 16. Mai 2026</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362815055"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-16T10:59:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8143449">AmoebeST</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">After arriving in Aserbaidschan 🇦🇿 we discovered the country by looking for some caches. 😎 We were happy to find some caches near our sightseeing route. 
"Mud Volcano Cache" was one of them and we could find it. We enjoyed our visit. 😊

Thanks David and greetings from Germany 🇩🇪 ‼️</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354993859"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-13T14:27:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3958287">Tomas99</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Great Adventure. TFTC 😁</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1351014998"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5254980">SOLRAC TWO</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I came just in time. Enough bubbles and from the big one the big blub.    TFTC 😎 🇩🇪</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1334992938"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-17T15:01:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4889380">Asterix.</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Yay, what an adventure to get here via southern approach, but luckily we avoided all the taxi drivers. 
Great place, thank you for bringing us here.
A FP well deserved.
Cheers from Croatia and TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="25.998133" lon="50.592567"><time>2005-06-01T00:00:00</time><name>GCP4ZC</name><desc>The Tree of Life by The Softies</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCP4ZC</url><urlname>The Tree of Life</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="249068" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>The Tree of Life</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>The Softies</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="391278">The Softies</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Bahrain</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Short scramble from the nearest parking spot.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>While now signposted from the Al Awali district it is still not that easy to find as the signposts are both intermittent and, in one case, wrong. It you reach the Airbase you have missed it. 

The Tree of Life stands alone in the desert some 2k from Jebel Dakhan. It is estimated
to be 400 years old and in such an arid spot there is no known source of water – still the tree lives on!

The cache is near here on the low hills across the road. It is not difficult to reach or find and contains goodies for both adults and children. 


</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1345609599"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-19T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1572075">Boreal Walker</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">انتهى بي المطاف اليوم برحلة إلى شجرة الحياة مع بعض الأصدقاء. ليسوا من هواة البحث عن الكنوز الجغرافية، لكنهم تقبلوا بروح رياضية بحثي عن الكنوز في الصحراء. ساعدنا أننا لم نعثر إلا على القليل منها في موقع مميز. كانت هذه أول تجربة لي في البحث عن الكنوز في البحرين. هذا الكنز موجود تحديدًا عند شجرة الحياة، لكنه كان قريبًا بما يكفي لإقناع بقية المجموعة بالانضمام إليّ في البحث. وجدنا مكانًا لركن السيارة بجوار موقع الكنز الجغرافي، ثم مشينا عبر الصحراء إلى نقطة البداية. استمتعنا بالتزحلق على المنحدر. سألني أحدهم إن كنت قد تفقدت مكانًا معينًا. لم أكن قد فعلت، وهذا ما كشف لي عن الكنز. رائع! لم أكن أخطط للعثور على أقدم كنز في البلاد، لكنني سأكتفي بهذا. كل شيء على ما يرام هنا بعد 20 عامًا.

I ended up taking a trip to the Tree of Life today with some friends.  They aren't geocachers, but were still good sports about me looking for treasures in the desert.  It helps that we only grabbed a few at an interesting location.  First time caching in Bahrain.  This one is exactly at the Tree of Life, but it was close enough to convince the rest of the group to join me in the searching.  We found a place to park by the earthcache and then walked out through the desert to ground zero.  We had fun slip sliding around on the slope.  One of the others asked if I had checked out a particular spot yet.  I hadn't and it revealed the goods.  Nice.  I wasn't planning on finding the oldest cache in the country, but I will take it.  All is well here after 20 years.  T:TB LNSL TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1343959350"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-04T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2225990">erglis</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nach dem Besuch des Baumes wollte ich natürlich auch noch den zugehörigen Geocache haben. Das Gelände ist nicht ganz einfach. Viele lose Steine. Nach etwas klettern konnte ich die alte Dose doch finden. 

After visiting the tree, of course, I also wanted to have the associated geocache. The terrain is not easy. Lots of loose stones. After a bit of climbing I could find the old stash.

Danke für die Dose Paldies par šo Cache Thanks for that Cache Merci pour la Cache Dzięki za Cache Grazie per questo Cache Takk for at Cache Obrigado por isso Cache Gracias por el Cache شكرا لأن ذاكرة التخزين المؤقت Díky za keš Ačiū už tą talpyklą Aitäh selle eest Cache Спасибо за то кэш 感谢您的缓存 Kiitos, että Cache Tack för att Cache Tak for denne Cache</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1343342762"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5231988">Tooltime_2011</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Meine liebe Cuxine und ich sind für einige Zeit auf einer Reise um die Welt und inzwischen sind wir Bahrain angekommen. Manama ist eine wirklich schöne Stadt und Bahrain kann mit vielen Sehenswürdigkeiten und interessanten Orten aufwarten … so wie auch hier am Tree of Life. Vielen Dank für diesen alten Traditional Cache und schöne Grüße aus Wünsdorf bei Berlin.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1343108867"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9330776">Cuxine</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Heute haben mein lieber Tooltime und ich einen kleinen Ausflug quer durch Bahrain gemacht. Diese älteste Dose in Bahrain wollten wir auch gerne besuchen und hatten sie uns zu Hause bereits auserkoren zu suchen! Ein bischen "bergsteigen" mussten wir schon und mein lieber Tooltime war schneller oben als ich gucken konnten und so hatte er auch recht flott die richtige Idee und das Döschen in der Hand, so dass wir uns hier im trockenen Logbuch eintragen konnten. Der Cache wartet jetzt in seinem Versteck wieder auf den nächsten Besucher! [;)] Einen TB haben wir mal mit auf Reisen genommen. 

Herzlichen Dank an The Softies fürs Herlocken und natürlich auch fürs Legen, Hegen und Pflegen des Tradis  "The Tree of Life" hier an diesem Ort über diesen langen Zeitraum!
Liebe Grüße von der Nordsee aus Deuschland von Cuxine 🌊🌊🌊☀️</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1343300406"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-16T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="23245541">NoPoS</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Today I rented a car and pretty much drove around the whole island with it. My plan was to find many caches and visit some well known tourist attractions. This was an easy find. TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="13.083233" lon="-59.602617"><time>2002-11-14T00:00:00</time><name>GCA952</name><desc>The Barbados Museum by Peabody</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCA952</url><urlname>The Barbados Museum</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="43346" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>The Barbados Museum</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Peabody</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="29701">Peabody</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="1">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="26" inc="1">Public transportation nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="29" inc="1">Telephone nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Barbados</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>For an island visitor, or a newcomer to Barbados, this entity is a great source of information and ideas for further discovery.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Virtual cache challenge question 1: When looking at the main gate entrance, email me the number and colour of the cannons you can see in front of the building.

Virtual cache challenge question 2: When facing the main entrance, looking at the right, email me the day(s) that the museum is closed.

Virtual cache challenge questions 3: Indicate what mode of transport you used to arrive in Barbados and on what date was your arrival.

The Barbados Museum is divided into a number of galleries, a research library, and is housed in a former military prison. It is considered by some to be a "must see". What visitors may find most fascinating are the antique maps in the Aall Gallery and the artefacts depicting the social history of Barbados from the pre-Columbian period.
The Children's gallery is also very popular and informative.
The museum is located across from the Garrison Savannah track.
It is a short taxi ride from the cruise ship dock, and well located for those who are already on the South coast of the island. (Please note there is an admission charge; most of this information was transcribed from the Barbados in a Nutshell booklet available to visitors)</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>East of the horse stables! North of the Barbados Defense Forces base.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1361015305"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-14T20:13:25</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1014955">keruha</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it on 05/05/2026, sent my answers to the author, but never heard back... Figured it's okay to log now. 
I was in Barbados for 2 weeks, my first time there. A few days ago I visited the museum which we really enjoyed, saw horse racing at the Savannah the second day in Barbados, I think it was "race #8". The apartment was a walking distance to the cache and to the Pebble beach. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359065923"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-03T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6200639">2-hobbits</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Great day on the south coast of Barbados today. Made several stops between Needhams Point and Ragged Harbour lighthouse to see some sights and visit some geocaches.

Back at the hotel we rested up a bit before I headed up here before dinner.

This virtual,  the oldest active geocache on the island, has been a target since arrival last week.

The museum was closing as I arrived but collected the answers necessary.

Answers sent to CO. TFTvC and greetings from Newfoundland, Canada 🇨🇦! A favourite!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358171582"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-01T04:50:45</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25640551">GeoPatricia</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">After a great day swimming at the beach, we moved over here for a quick cache stop. TFTC!
Greetings from 🇸🇰</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359211442"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-14T10:16:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="594365">Barbie&amp;Bruettler</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Auf unserer 4-wöchigen Reise von der Karibik über Mittelamerika ins Mittelmeer auf der "Mein Schiff 1" haben wir 15 Länder bereist und natürlich auch in jedem Land zumindest einen Cache gefunden.

During our 4-week trip from the Caribbean via Central America to the Mediterranean on the "Mein Schiff 1" we visited 15 countries and of course found at least one cache in every country.

Answers sent with PM, unfortunately no time to visite the museum.

Greetings from Germany, 
Barbie&amp;Bruettler
Thanks to Peabody

*13140*</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355608044"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-12T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6346099">1311</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings from Kentucky, USA!  My wife and I are on a Caribbean adventure hopping from one island to the next! We started our adventure in Sint Maarten followed by Antigua, St. Lucia, Barbados, Domenica, then St. Kitts &amp; Nevis.

The goal was to find at least one cache at each island.  I am happy to say that we exceeded that goal.  Even more exciting is that we got to explore new places and learn about these places.  

This Virtual was another simple one.  This is a really interesting area.  Be sure to check out the George Washington house down the road!

All caches that required information/answers to be sent to the cache owner have been sent.  All physical logs have been signed.  All physical caches have been returned to their configuration as we found them.  Thank you for the caches and the memories!
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="53.9193" lon="27.6939"><time>2009-06-24T00:00:00</time><name>GC1V5WY</name><desc>The Second in Belarus by ly2kw</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1V5WY</url><urlname>The Second in Belarus</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1292638" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>The Second in Belarus</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>ly2kw</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="639369">ly2kw</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="0">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="0">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Belarus</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>The cache is hidden in the outskirts of Minsk on my cycling trip to
Belarus and Russia. I hid the cache after failing to find &lt;i&gt;The
First in Belarus&lt;/i&gt; that was most likely muggled.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;img src="http://ly2kw.com/geocaching/images/second_in_belarus/is_virsaus.jpg" /&gt;
 &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
So this is your second chance to flag Belarus as a country you
cached in. Nothing very spectacular, just plain forest that needs
quite a bit of CITO. It should take 40 to 50 minutes on a bicycle
from downtown Minsk. You can use instructions on public transport
on &lt;i&gt;The First in Belarus&lt;/i&gt; cache description and logs.
Initially the cache is preloaded with some Lithuanian coins and
Lithuanian Flag Geocoin. Good luck.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src="http://ly2kw.com/geocaching/images/second_in_belarus/cache.jpg" /&gt;
 &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The coords provided are only approximate. As with all my hides I
try to do as much sampling as possible, but seldom get a
professional precision. Don't expect to find the cache exactly at
the numbers your GPSr reads. Other than plainly logging "off
coords" please add your version of correct coords, this will make
your entry useful both for cache owner and other seekers.
Appreciate your cooperation.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href="http://s04.flagcounter.com/more/lVb1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://s04.flagcounter.com/count/lVb1//bg=FFFFFF/txt=000000/border=CCCCCC/columns=5/maxflags=50/viewers=Listing+visitors+come+from/labels=1/pageviews=0/" /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src="http://ly2kw.com/geocaching/images/second_in_belarus/dvirka.jpg" /&gt;
 &lt;br /&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Ladder</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1345448934"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-18T17:59:56</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="22356557">FroggyBearReviewer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hello, 

your geocache has been temporarily disabled for too long time without your reaction to reviewer notes, asking you to repair / replace the cache. Therefore I'm archiving this abandoned cache page, so it won't be displayed on Geocaching map and in Search results any longer.
 
 **More information:**
Guidelines - [Keep cache page active](https://www.geocaching.com/play/guidelines#listingmaintenance)
Help Center - [7.4. Maintenance expectations](https://www.geocaching.com/help/index.php?pg=kb.chapter&amp;id=38&amp;pgid=57)
Help Center - [7.15. Archive or unarchive a geocache](https://www.geocaching.com/help/index.php?pg=kb.chapter&amp;id=38&amp;pgid=56)


I want to thank you for the time that you have taken to contribute to Geocaching in the past and I am looking forward to seeing you back in the game.

Best Regards,

------------
FroggyBearReviewer (Michal) - Community Volunteer Reviewer
[Geocaching.com](http://www.geocaching.com) | [Help Center](https://www.geocaching.com/help/index.php) | [Guidelines](https://www.geocaching.com/play/guidelines)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1332545383"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-01T12:09:30</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="22356557">FroggyBearReviewer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**Message for owner:**
 
Your geocache has been replaced by another player. If you want to keep on maintenance yourself, please:

* check your new box of the cache, if it was placed on the correct place
* update information in the listing (size, hint, difficulty, terain), if something changed
* write [Owner Maintenance log](http://support.groundspeak.com/index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=404), it seems that you made maintenance
* write [Enable listing log](http://support.groundspeak.com/index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=235), it seems that your cache is ready to be found

If you don't want to keep on maitenance of the cache, write [archive log](https://www.geocaching.com/help/index.php?pg=kb.chapter&amp;id=38&amp;pgid=56).
 
Best Regards,

------------
FroggyBearReviewer (Michal) - Community Volunteer Reviewer
[Geocaching.com](http://www.geocaching.com) | [Help Center](https://www.geocaching.com/help/index.php) | [Guidelines](https://www.geocaching.com/play/guidelines)

---

What to do if your cache has been replaced by another player? More info Help Centre: [6.11. Respond to "throwdowns"](https://www.geocaching.com/help/index.php?pg=kb.chapter&amp;id=38&amp;pgid=427).</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1316802611"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-11T03:03:46</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3421196">19Dude65</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**WE SUPPORTED THE CO AND CHECKED THE USABILITY AND THE SAFETY OF THE LOCATION. EVERYTHING IS JUST PERFECT. SO WE PLACED A NEW PET-PREFORM WITH A NEW LOG.**


Maintenance is done. Search can be continued. 
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1316005849"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-07T23:31:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3421196">19Dude65</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">&gt;  ☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆

----------

&gt; **Roadtrip Heading North**

----------

&gt; ☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆☆

We started our trip in the evening on August, 1st. Our trip got us from Linz to Kaunas where we attended the MEGA. Next stop was Kaliningrad, followed by Riga and Vilnius. As we haven’t been to Belarus we made a day trip to Minsk and returned in the evening to Vilnius. On our way back home we stopped for a day in Warsaw and Wroclav. 

To get the most out of our journey we chose quite some caches which we either solved or at least translated. Whenever we are abroad we try to get as many different cache types as possible. And we love to do Adventure Labs because most of them bring you to amazing places. 

We also enjoyed the local food and were surprised how kind the people were we met on different occasions. Yes, the language barrier was a challenge but at the end our questions were answered and we always got tasty food and a nice place to stay. 

The trip was a balanced experience with little adventures, entertainment, education and sightseeing enriched with food po•n and meeting fellow geocachers and kind locals. 

Thank you **ly2kw** for providing and maintaining the cache **The Second in Belarus**

This is my find #**29533** on **07.08.2025**.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1316029645"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-07T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="390054">guelin</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Wir - Werner85, 19Dude65 und ich - starteten am 1. August unsere 10-tägige gemeinsame Reise.
Unser erstes Ziel war das Mega-Event in Kaunas. Anschließend gings nach Kaliningrad und danach nach Riga und Vilnius. Auch nach Minsk in Weißrussland machten wir einen Tagesausflug. Dauerte dann etwas länger, denn wir brauchten für den Grenzübertritt nach Belarus ganze 9 Stunden und zurück nach Littauen dann nochmals fast 17 Stunden. Wir übernachteten dann in Kaunas, bevor es weiter nach Warschau und am letzten Tag nach Breslau ging.
Wir konnten auf unserer Reise viele Cachetypen absolvieren. Auch spazierten wir einige Lab-Serien, Wherigos und Multis entlang. Bei den Virtuals und Earthcaches konnten wir sehr viele schöne Plätze in den jeweiligen Städten entdecken. So manchen Tradi der am Weg lag besuchten wir auch. Bei ein paar Events lernten wir viele Geocacher kennen. Kulinarisch waren wir sehr sehr zufrieden.
Diese Reise war ein Erlebnis.
Danke für den Tradi.
Danke an alle Owner fürs Verlegen der Caches und fürs Erstellen der vielen Virtuals, Earthcaches und LAB-Serien.

We – Werner85, 19Dude65, and I – started our 10-day trip together on August 1st. Our first destination was the mega-event in Kaunas. We then went to Kaliningrad, then to Riga and Vilnius. We also took a day trip to Minsk in Belarus. It took a bit longer, because it took us a full 9 hours to cross the border into Belarus, and then another 17 hours to get back to Lithuania. We then spent the night in Kaunas before continuing on to Warsaw and, on the last day, to Wroclaw.
We were able to complete many types of caches on our trip. We also walked along several lab series, wherigos, and multis. With the virtual and earth caches, we were able to discover many beautiful places in the respective cities. We also visited a few traditional caches along the way. We met many geocachers at a few events. We were very, very satisfied with the food.
This trip was an experience.
Thank you for this tradi.
Thanks to all the cache owners for placing the caches and for creating the many virtuals, Earthcaches, and LAB series.

Thx, guelin
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="50" lon="5"><time>2000-07-07T00:00:00</time><name>GC40</name><desc>Geocache by Pierre Cao, Speerpunt, adopted by Grokky</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC40</url><urlname>Geocache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="64" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Geocache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Pierre Cao, Speerpunt, adopted by Grokky</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="22897">Grokky Grokson</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Belgium</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Namur</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This is the oldest cache that you can log on continental Europe.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
It is one of the first caches ever in Europe and was placed 7/7/2000 by Pierre Cao.&lt;br /&gt;
It was transferred to Speerpunt in 2003 and he maintained it for 13 years.&lt;br /&gt;
He transferred it to Grokky in 2016, but Speerpunt remains involved in maintaining the cache.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Parking is available about 100 meters from the cache.  Be careful when crossing the road though: this is a busy road, the parking is in a curve in the road so you will have bad visibility, and cars drive really fast here.  So be extremely careful, especially when you have children with you.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Only 6 caches placed in 2000 are still active in Europe:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="550" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC43"&gt;GC43&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;3 Jun 2000&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Europe's First&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Ireland&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC40"&gt;GC40&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;7 Jul 2000&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Geocache&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Belgium&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC4D"&gt;GC4D&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;11 Aug 2000&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Match Stash&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Sweden&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC72"&gt;GC72&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;30 Sep 2000&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Sun Gear&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Finland&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC6A"&gt;GC6A&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;30 Sep 2000&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Kippers in the Jungle (Denmarks First Cache)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Denmark&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCF0"&gt;GCF0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;15 Dec 2000&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;Scotland's First&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;UK&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
You are visiting a part of geocaching history, so please take good care of the cache.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table&gt;
&lt;tr align="left" valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Haut-Fays Geocache - GPS Stash Hunt This is the second GPS Stash Hunt to be set in Belgium. It was set on the 6th of July, 2000 near Haut-Fays [map]. The idea of this one came from the Degree Confluence Project although it is not an "official" point for this project. Why? Because for latitudes above 49 degree they drop every third point :-( This one is in south of Belgium, not far from France, in the Haute Lesse area. That is a very attractive and touristic area in the belgian Luxembourg province, though the stash is actually in the Namur province. There are many other things to visit and enjoy after you will have found the stash. You will be just some kilometers west of the European Space Agency ground station in Redu. This site is operated by Ciset and controls more than 80 geostationary satellites (no, not the Navstar satellites that your GPS uses!) A more recreational site about space is the Euro Space Camp. The small village of Redu is also known for being a "book town". There are more than 20 bookshops that you can visit in a friendly and relaxing environment. The geocache is located in the woods at about 10 meter from a paved road (N835). A 1/200.000 Michelin road map (sheet 214) should be enough if you want to go by car or road cycling. We chose to leave our car at the Redu's ESA station and go with a mountain bike. To get to the stash it was a 17km westward ride, mainly in the woods and trough the village of Gembes. We came back mainly by paved roads and trough the village of Daverdisse for a total of 39km round trip [map]. The topomap was absolutely necessary. The IGN 1/25000 sheet 64/1-2 (Haut-Fays - Redu) covers this area. Be aware that the coordinates on that map are not WGS84. More details on that on the IGN web site: in French or in Dutch. The stash is a ammo box. It is burried between the roots of a large stump (on the side facing north). The ammo box is coverd with some leaves and small branches but remains evident for the one who searches for it. It is marked in big blue letters "Geocache - GPS Stash Hunt" and the coordinates. We took some pictures and they will be published here (it may take some time, though...). The initial contents: a log book and a pencil of course, plus some roller pens, orange juice, green-and-white "antistress" ball,... No batteries in this one but genuine belgian chocolate (56% cocoa, 0% other vegetable fat). As the rule says: take something, leave something, write in the log book.. And now for the coordinates: after a 15 minute averaging, the Garmin GPS III Pilot confirmed the cache is at: N50°00.000' - E005°00.000' (WGS84) That position was determined with 9 sats, DOP 1.2 and EPE 5 meters. The averaging showed first E004°59.997' and Estimated Precision 4.6m. This geocache was visited for the first time on July 16, 2000.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr align="left" valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&lt;img src="https://d1u1p2xjjiahg3.cloudfront.net/f75e2097-d1e6-4de5-ae2e-62b758a263f2_l.jpg" width="500" height="500" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364790791"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:18:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="53670579">Rexry</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Das war ein schönes Erlebnis,  diesen uralten Cache zu loggen. Gleich daneben ist noch ein Lab Cache zur Geschichte des Cache. Toll gemacht, Dose top gepflegt.  Vielen Dank fürs Legen und Hegen </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364655712"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T18:29:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="29862845">Mystery09</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Wenn wir schon einmal im Urlaub in der nähe sind, muss natürlich auch dieser alte Schatz geloggt werden. Nach dem Parkplatz der mittlerweile gut ausgebauten Cacher Autobahn gefolgt, und die Dose schnell entdecke können. Danke fürs aufrecht erhalten dieser wirklich alten Dose!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364394684"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T18:10:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8241">Arizona</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Many thanks for this nice cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364308307"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:14:10</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1177896">Dr. Explain</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Back at GC40 after my first visit 16 year ago</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364210518"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T12:12:09</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2919701">harwin</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Auf dem Weg in den Irland Urlaub haben wir den ein oder anderen Cache eingesammelt.
Hier vorbei zu fahren und diesen Methusalem zu besuchen war Ehrensache. Dafür gibt es einen FP

DfdC und Gruß 
harwin</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="17.224867" lon="-88.090733"><time>2001-01-06T00:00:00</time><name>GC15D</name><desc>Oh so blue by Jonathan, Catherine, Fran, Dick, Tom, Louise</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC15D</url><urlname>Oh so blue</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="349" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Oh so blue</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Jonathan, Catherine, Fran, Dick, Tom, Louise</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1095">sailor</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>4.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Belize</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Due to the nature of the place, the proprietor is holding the cache. Please see Ricardo for information.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Most of the islands in Belize are overgrown with mangroves. They are the home to exotic birds, abundant fish, and manatees. Inland, you would also find fresh-water crocs of up to 15 feet in length. They are terrified of people.
&lt;p&gt;If you wish to find this cache, you need to visit the coordinates entered. I gave the difficulty as hard because of the remote location and the fact that the only accessibility is by boat. Further, the coordinates indicate an excellent anchoring spot. Other areas in the small cay are either difficult or impossible to hold an anchor overnight.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The proprietor/owner of the island has been given the cache for safekeeping. It would be environmentally destructive to leave the rectangular plastic box in the mangroves.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I would very much like to hear about it if you make it to this wonderful place. Wayne (Finn) was reported to have died a couple of years ago, but in fact is still alive (but not working for Ricardo any longer and can no longer be reached). The owner (Ricardo) is holding the cache. I spoke with him on the phone and he's aware of the situation. He's happy to take calls of inquiry. Please be respectful. He's a very nice person. Be sure to mention our names: Jonathan, Catherine, Fran, Dick, Tom (recently deceased), and Louise.&lt;/p&gt;
Note that this log was updated with new contents, since the old cache is AWOL (although it could show up, according to the latest from Ricardo).
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
This cache is still active and can be found. If someone has information contrary to this, please let me know, and I will correct the situation! Note that this cache was the oldest unfound cache until relatively recently.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The Bluefield Range. The owner of the island is Ricardo. He wasn't there when we were, but his employee, Wayne agreed to give him the cache for us. We explained and showed him the contents. Ricardo's cell phone number (from the US) is 011-501-661-1127.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1228276074"><groundspeak:date>2023-12-15T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1516884">gonefishing2</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We are down here in Belize for vacation. After all the rain and canceled snorkeling trips the resort agreed to take us here. The water was a little choppy going out but much better coming back.  

Favorite point given. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1140280235"><groundspeak:date>2022-12-07T16:58:14</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="106095">BIG BEAR.</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This is one of the main ones I wanted to tag while I was here a short detour and we were on our way</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="911165788"><groundspeak:date>2020-03-01T11:18:30</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="26748903">a101eagle</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Diving Belize!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="910442404"><groundspeak:date>2020-02-28T07:52:32</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="26756977">dawnanderson4</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Did a drive by as we were out scuba diving!!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="896017941"><groundspeak:date>2019-11-27T12:25:07</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="19767648">l18cp</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hello from Belize City (I am here on a cruise)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="7.182633333333333" lon="1.9838833333333334"><time>2009-01-14T00:00:00</time><name>GC1N8B0</name><desc>Abomey Royal by DingoCZ</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1N8B0</url><urlname>Abomey Royal</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1146041" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Abomey Royal</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>DingoCZ</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1263847">DingoCZ</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Benin</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Save place in Fascinating Royal City Abomey.
First Cache in Benin!
Secure place en ABOMEY - citee rozal fascinee.
Premier cache au Benin!</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Round box hide bellow small concrete blocks. Owner is aware about  the cache. You should contact the owner Ottis DIOGO T:+229-22500289/M+229-97720916/97725651. otiscool@yahoo.fr
He speaks little english, helpful with accomodation, transport and also sightseeing. Seldom to find in Africa so reliable person! Trust me.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>[En]Bellow watertower. By Marie Josee.
[Fr]Au dessous de chateau d`eau. Chez Marie Josee.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1336130970"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2892866">Lustiger Koala</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This was quiete a bit of a trip... For not too much exiting sightseeing. I liked yesterday better (Porto Novo, Rivière Noire...) . Got home early so that I can cool down in pool now. Nevertheless Thanks for the cache. Caches in Benin are so rare:-)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1326029644"><groundspeak:date>2025-09-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10420067">Alixander77</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This day Vollseiler and me took a long ride from the coastline to the old king‘s town Abomey.
A pity the world heritage rewarded Kings Palace was closed. The guard was telling us it is because of some kind of rebuilding or reconstruction…..hard to believe, but okay.
Afterwards we drove to this cache.
Straight ahead to GZ is not possible anymore, the doors to the Bellow Watertower are closed also, but right in front of this we replaced a new cache.
Honestly spoken, this is a lousy hideout because of all the garbage and dirt.
But hey, the oldest cache of Benin deserves to surive, so…..

Thanks for an adventurous tour to Abomey and the idea of a cache.
Greetimgs from Germany.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1323675341"><groundspeak:date>2025-09-11T22:05:15</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="52338216">Kokomelon2011</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">😀</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1317127344"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-12T16:18:12</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="53324189">Theot1e</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Åkte hit från Sverige endast för cachen tack</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1309612883"><groundspeak:date>2025-07-10T09:50:41</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="50194323">benjus420</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="32.380433333333336" lon="-64.67621666666666"><time>2002-04-09T00:00:00</time><name>GC4B5C</name><desc>Deliverance by The VNI Venturers</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC4B5C</url><urlname>Deliverance</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="19292" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Deliverance</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>The VNI Venturers</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="31278">VNI Venturers</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Bermuda</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>The "Deliverance" is in The Parrish of St. George's.&lt;P&gt; How tall is the Mainmast? How long is the waterline of the ship? How tall is the mizzenmast?&lt;P&gt;  E-mail your answers to me to verify your find, don't post them here!</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The Deliverance is a replica of a ship that once saved the crew of the shipwrecked "Sea Venture" in 1609.&lt;br&gt; It was built by the survivors of the wreck from parts of the Sea Venture. The little ship later sailed to Jamestown with some of the survivors on board who sent help.
     </groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>When you see the "ducking" look to the sea and over the bridge.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1166019592"><groundspeak:date>2023-05-10T17:27:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="115500">Crow T Robot</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The target of this virtual cache is gone and the cache cannot be logged as published.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1163044762"><groundspeak:date>2023-04-29T14:30:08</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10490566">KiwiAoraki</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">2 for 2 today and I'm now up to 10 finds in Bermuda. The ship is gone, however. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1161204596"><groundspeak:date>2023-04-21T14:53:20</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="39240845">WorldTraveller2000</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found the empty place where the ship used to be ...</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1161203857"><groundspeak:date>2023-04-21T14:50:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="39240845">WorldTraveller2000</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This is the place where the ship used to be ... </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1158652694"><groundspeak:date>2023-04-05T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6273461">DarelLlama</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="27.612883" lon="90.890117"><time>2009-10-17T00:00:00</time><name>GC20P0Z</name><desc>Tang Treasure by Pagenz</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC20P0Z</url><urlname>Tang Treasure</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1457094" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Tang Treasure</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Pagenz</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1682674">Pagenz</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Micro</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Bhutan</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Ugyen Choeling Manor in the Tang Valley, Bumtang.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>** GPS reception may be limited so please read the detailed description on location. **

In the middle of 14th century Longchen Rabjampa built a retreat here. Then the revered Dorje Lingpa settled here and the place has been occupied by his descents ever since.
The central tower, a former residence is now a private museum (small admission fee) which is well worth a visit. It has several floors with themed rooms: kitchen, armoury, clothing etc – my favourite was the porcelain room.

Access: Follow the twisting unpaved road to its end, and then walk up through the trees and countryside on a crooked path to the manor house. 

**Location: Facing the  museum there is a significant temple to the right. Walk clockwise around the temple until you reach the North corner (rear of the building). In the second group of prayer wheels, north end beneath and behind two stones (slates)

Cache: Camo micro eclipse mint container.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Far back corner, lift the stones.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1334775210"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-16T16:58:02</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25974479">es777</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1334482814"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-09T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6642403">Winnie Pu</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Auf unserer wunderschönen Bhutan Reise von Ost nach West auch hier vorbeigekommen.
Ein toller und sehr interessanter Ort ist das hier!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1332005327"><groundspeak:date>2025-10-28T10:38:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1977121">Aischa</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">My first Cache in Bhutan - Thanks</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1326963092"><groundspeak:date>2025-09-29T13:43:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="288883">kyffme</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">My first Cache in Bhutan! And this place is absolutely wonderful.
However, I was very surprised: according to the logbook on site (place as described in the listing), I was the first visitor since more than a year...
Greetings from Germany
kyffme</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1297765025"><groundspeak:date>2025-05-11T12:36:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13409236">angela_e_h</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We found the cache but did feel a little awkward as it's hidden behind a prayer wheel - sorry for the information but the description didn't help us find the item fully, we didn't know if it was in the wall opposite or in the wall/prayer wheels. Difficult with pilgrims walking past. Hopefully this was created by a person with local knowledge and it's acceptable to hide a cache here. Also description said two pieces of slate, but there was just one. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="43.916067" lon="18.421133"><time>2004-06-12T00:00:00</time><name>GCJVHV</name><desc>Bukovic Mountain #1 by Blanco Cactus Jack &amp; Wander Woman</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCJVHV</url><urlname>Bukovic Mountain #1</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="150657" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Bukovic Mountain #1</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Blanco Cactus Jack &amp; Wander Woman</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="241549">Blanco Cactus Jack</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="0">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="1">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="10" inc="0">Difficult climb</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Bosnia and Herzegovina</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Cache is at the crest of a long, bare ridge coming off Bukovic Mountain just north of Sarajevo</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Cache has been here since 2004 but has been muggled so there may be no physical container any longer although (see the Hint) there may be.  I should transition this into an Earth Cache once I figure out how to do that as the view of Sarajevo from the site is magnificent! Best access is from Nahorevo. At the bus turn around take the right hand road going downhill, keeping the war memorial on your left.  Go down, then up, up, up.  Stay on the main road (but don't take the asphalt road that goes uphill to the left). Keep the Loviste hut on your left and wind up the mountain to the cache.  As this IS Bosnia &amp; Herzegovina you need to BEWARE OF LANDMINES!  Most of Bukovic Mountain seems to be mine free (at least we never stepped on one).  But DON'T go wandering around off trails any closer to Sarajevo as that was where the front lines were and the nasty things are still around. We've tromped all around the cache site and wandered all over the ridge so things are probably fairly safe...but there is never a guarantee of total safety in Bosnia so be careful.

If you get to the location and find the clump of bushes, give yourself credit.  The hike and the view make it well worth the effort!

Finally, look north across the valley and you can see the Mocioci Stecci at N 43 degrees 55.503'; E 018 degrees 26.473'.  A long hike for another day.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>In December 2018, a cacher (Noach from The Netherlands) reportedly placed a substitute cache at a bush approximately 10 meters to the East of the clump of bushes.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1359877191"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-09T11:36:54</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7394303">Xiefehl_en_Mozique</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We found the original petling! Log will follow later.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360047187"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-09T11:32:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7394303">Xiefehl_en_Mozique</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Vanaf 7 mei reizen we door de Balkan. Deze vakantie staat in het teken van vieren, geocachen en genieten van al het moois dat de Balkan te bieden heeft.
**Dag 3:** Vandaag gingen we op de zoek naar de oudste actieve cache van Bosnië Herzegovina en we bezochten de Skischansen van de Olympische spelen bij de Igman berg.

Starting May 7, we will be traveling through the Balkans. This holiday is all about celebrating, geocaching, and enjoying all the beauty the Balkans have to offer.
**Day 3:** Today we went in search of the oldest active cache in Bosnia and Herzegovina and visited the Olympic ski jumps at Mount Igman.

*First, we went looking for the oldest active cache in Bosnia and Herzegovina. To reach this cache, you had to take a long uphill walk. It turned out that you could also drive up the mountain, until we arrived at the actual hiking trail. Only 750 meters as the crow flies, but naturally much further zigzagging along, we went up the mountain via the Marathon Trail. We ascended from 887 meters to 1,159 meters. It was quite steep at times. After 1.5 hours, we reached the top and the cache. It was supposed to be gone, but we found it anyway, with a 10-meter deviation. So the replacement went back in the backpack. Despite the clouds, we had fantastic views along the way. There were all kinds of beautiful flowers along the path and it was quiet... so quiet. It felt like being alone in the world.*
FAVO for this great adventure!

Blanco Cactus Jack TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1352723311"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-03T21:34:11</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7394303">Xiefehl_en_Mozique</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We planned to do this cache around may 8th or 9th. So if we get there we will hide something new. Greetings from Holland</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1346775867"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="241549">Blanco Cactus Jack</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We left this cache in place when we departed Bosnia and Herzegovina because there were so few caches in the country. Dozens of people have enjoyed the cache in the 22 years it has been there.  Geocaching HQ indicates the cache needs maintenance. So, if you are going after this cache can you please take some materials (a small container, cache log, pencil, etc) to maintain it?  Otherwise, they will archive it and other cachers will not get to experience this special place.  Thank you from Texas!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1329648090"><groundspeak:date>2025-10-13T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="12520303">MarTini20</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Auf meiner heutigen Tour konnte ich den Cache gut finden und das Logbuch signieren.

Vielen Dank für den Cache und liebe Grüße. 

PS: Ich platziere mein Stempel oder Lognamen nicht immer an chronologisch letzter Stelle im Logbuch, sondern nutze auch leere Seiten oder Plätze weiter vorne um Leerstellen auszufüllen. Schon alleine aus Rücksicht dem Owner gegenüber um sinnlose frühzeitige Wartungsarbeiten zu vermeiden. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-20.18385" lon="25.300133"><time>2003-09-23T00:00:00</time><name>GCGYHZ</name><desc>Aardvark by Steve (Licorice)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCGYHZ</url><urlname>Aardvark</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="93962" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Aardvark</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Steve (Licorice)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="28262">Licorice</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="1">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="26" inc="1">Public transportation nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="31" inc="1">Camping nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="29" inc="1">Telephone nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Botswana</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>A virtual cache located southeast of Maun.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;img src="http://www.geckobeach.com/GPS/licorice45.jpg" width="240" height="180" align="right" /&gt;An easy virtual cache on the road southeast to Maun. Find the rather large aardvark along side the road and take a picture of yourself infront of it with your GPS clearly visible. Upload the picture with your log entry to score a find.
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br clear="all" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363685381"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10420067">Alixander77</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On our way to Kubu Island we made a stop for this old cache.
Construction sites nearby wasn‘t disturbing.

Thanks so much, greetings from Germany.

This stash was visited and found by Vollseiler and me during a trip in Zimbabwe, Zambia and Botswana.
Independently by ourself through various Nationalparks and of course the mighty falls of Victoria. With lots of sun, wild animals and great vast landscapes.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357796771"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1991443">Maruffel</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">When travelling in a muggle group, it 
is Not easy to search for Geocaches. I could persuade  our Guide and bus Drive to make a short stop at the aardvark. I was happy to log at least this  Virtual GC slthough there are some more in this area.
The next geocache was very close, I could approach to up to 15m, Then came the whistle to come back and continue. What a Pity!

Thanks for showing this Giant aardvark</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1353883780"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-03T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3747041">tomine193</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nice place came here together with Koto66, very impressive country - TFTC and kind greetings from [pyhrnPriel Area](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rctx9tFemVw) 🇦🇹 🧗‍♀️ 🌞 🚴‍♀️📚 🍻 🇦🇹</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1351264725"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-11T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1315012">Pfadi1991</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Heute habe ich diesen Virtual-Cache gefunden. Vielen Dank an Steve (Licorice)
Ich logge dort, wo Platz ist.

Today I found this Virtual-Cache, Thanks a lot to Steve (Licorice)
I put my log whereever is space.

1.0/ 1.0

# 16639

Feel free to discover:
GLH6EQ
PCRR2Y
PC1KHD
GX15NF</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1347114394"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9500488">struzzi24</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Very nice place. Greetings from Luxembourg.tftc</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-24.274817" lon="-48.402183"><time>2001-06-14T00:00:00</time><name>GCC67</name><desc>Mission 4:  Southern Bowl by Project APE</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCC67</url><urlname>Mission 4:  Southern Bowl</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Project APE Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3175" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Mission 4:  Southern Bowl</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Project APE</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="3946697">JRintervales</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Project APE Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="67" inc="1">GeoTour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="9" inc="1">Significant hike</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="23" inc="1">Dangerous area</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Brazil</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>São Paulo</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>As the authorities begin to close in on our ranks we decided it was time to go global. Hopefully this will allow our trail to turn cold and leave the authorities in a clueless fog. To date, our advantage over the government has been the fast action and stealth abilities of all our hunters in the field. Those advantages remain imperative to our operation as we continually attempt to out wit and out duel the federal agencies.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Here are the notes from our agent in Brazil. It sounds like an amazing cache. Be safe and be strong.
&lt;p&gt;“The cache is located in the countryside of one of the Southeast States of Brazil. The place is one of the few reserves of the “Mata Atlantica” (Atlantic Forest) left in the country. It is a state park, protected by UNESCO, full of rivers, waterfalls, lakes, caves and a lot of threatened animal species, such as the “Onça Pintada” (Spotted Panther). If you still don’t know where it is at, we’ll give you a clue: the “Caverna Colorida” (Colorful Cave) and the “Cachoeira do Arcão” (Big Arch Waterfall) are some of the attractions of the Park.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As you get to the administration office of the park, you will have to walk about 30 minutes to the cache. The trail is not difficult, but you will have to look beyond it in the dense forest near an area full of dropped leaves. There, you will also be able to enjoy the scenic view and admire the beauty of the park.”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Português&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Este item está localizado no interior de um dos estados da região Sudeste do Brasil, em uma das poucas reservas de Mata Atlântica restantes no país. O local é um parque estadual, protegido pela UNESCO, repleto de rios, cachoeiras, lagos, cavernas e muitas espécies de animais ameaçados de extinção, como por exemplo: a Onça-pintada. Caso você ainda não saiba qual é o parque daremos uma dica: a “Caverna Colorida” e a “Cachoeira do Arcão” são algumas das principais atrações do parque.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Após a chegada à administração do parque, a caminhada até o local deverá levar aproximadamente 30 minutos. A trilha para chegar ao local é de facil acesso, porém para encontrá-lo você terá de sair alguns metros da trilha e procurar na mata densa em um local repleto de folhas caídas. Para compensar a caminhada, o local é um ótimo ponto para admirar a beleza do parque.&lt;/p&gt;
OK folks here’s the deal with people logging this cache with out being there. Yes I do know that additional logging requirements are not allowed any more here on Geocaching,com , but it sure would be easier for me to tell who was really there, please take a picture of the log book and cache container to confirm the find Thanks Joe // JoGPS
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1365039167"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T10:09:20</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="483477">Highrod</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The 4th Geocache in our Aussies go Ape adventure.
What an incredible experience, we've been gearing up for this elusive cache for many years and it's finally here. We headed out in the rain and found the cache with our guide Gerson.
Cache is in great condition but on the damp side.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364627461"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T17:34:56</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1167453">Wandering_Weiands</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Special trip planned around finding the APE cache. We did it and made friends along the way. We are part of BGAA26.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364741649"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7387645">betzij</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On a geocaching adventure tour with a group of people from various US states and one from UK.  This adventure got started by one of the ND geocachers asking me if I could help them get a trip planned since they knew I had been on other geocaching adventure trips. I was supposed to come to Brazil 2 years ago but I broke my elbow and wrist just before the trip was to start so had to cancel.  

Of course, I contacted my friend at Geocaching Adventures, LLC to get the ball rolling.  A year later a group of 17  headed to Brazil to find the famous APE cache.   We met up in Sao Paulo the first day and rested a little the next day we were driven to the Intervales Park, getting in a little before dark.

The accommodations in the Park were like going to summer camp which was a fun experience for us.  We did a little night caching then off to bed.  The next morning we attended a CITO event and afterwards it was time to head off to find the cherished APE cache.  A local guide had cleared out the trail a few days before out arrival with a machete which made the hike a little easier.  We still had logs to get over, low hanging trees and vines, muddy tread in spot, but it was all worth it when we opened the container and signed our names to the log book.  

YIPPEE!!! We made it. 😍  Thanks for maintaining this "one of only 2" left of the APE caches. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364692578"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3605820">AdventuringRose</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">AdventuringRose's Brazil Great Ape Adventure – Day 4 🇧🇷🐒

Operation: A.P.E. Cache + Geotour Completion

After sharing a room with Bugs_77 and The Possum, it was time to get up. I woke up absolutely frozen. After hearing horror stories of ice-cold—or somehow even worse, lukewarm—showers, I decided cleanliness was a problem for Future Me and got dressed instead.

Which led me to my daily crisis.

The hiking shoes.

I hate my hiking shoes.

I spent a month and a half trying to break them in before this trip, but they were no match for my beloved Converse, which are, in my completely unbiased opinion, the most comfortable and fashionable shoes ever created. After yesterday's adventures, however, I reluctantly admitted the hiking shoes had one major advantage: traction. 

Plus, if I needed suitcase space later, I could always sacrifice them to the jungle gods.

Decision made. Hiking shoes on. Adventure mode activated.

A group of us—Tick_Magnet, The_Possum, Bugs_77, BetziJ, and ThewanderingWeiands—went caching before meeting up with everyone else to tackle the APE cache. 

Then it was jungle time.

Now, I knew we were hiking through the jungle today.

Or at least I thought I knew.

What I pictured was a nice trail through some trees.

What I got was a full-blown action movie where nature was actively trying to high-five me in the face.

I stayed behind Butterfly_77, who became my personal jungle navigation system, calling out helpful warnings like "over!" and "under!" whenever roots, vines, or branches appeared.

I was also extremely grateful for our guide Francis, who was ahead with the guide with the machete like we'd wandered into the wrong movie set.

Early in the hike, Francis casually showed us how ticks like to hide underneath bamboo leaves. I couldn’t believe how many ticks were on that little leaf!!

This information improved my day in absolutely no way and ensured I spent the next several hours convinced every leaf was plotting against me.

The trail was muddy enough to swallow my shoes whole, and for the first time in my life I was thankful for the hiking boots. I'd tied them so tightly that if the mud wanted one, it was going to have to take my entire leg too.

Along the way, Francis pointed out tapir tracks.

The jungle pointed out gravity.

I slipped.

I fell.

I tumbled.

In an act of pure instinct, I launched myself sideways so I wouldn't take out Butterfly_77 like the human bowling ball I’d suddenly become!

I immediately jumped up and began conducting a full medical assessment of my knee and foot, wondering if I'd just erased months of physical therapy in my one spectacular jungle maneuver.

The verdict would have to wait. I was overtaken with much adrenaline and sheer panic over who saw me pull that off?!

After that, I became so focused on where my feet were going that I completely stopped paying attention to everything above neck level.

This was a mistake.

I smashed my head into low-hanging branches at least four separate times.

After the first one, I told Butterfly_77, "You let me down!"

She replied, "I was busy going over and under!"

Fair enough. 😂🤣😂

By the second impact, I was considering adding "call chiropractor" to my post-trip to-do list.

At one point, someone behind me said, "I heard the thunk."

Not "I saw it."

Heard it.

That tells you everything you need to know.

Eventually we zeroed in on the cache area. 

Everyone searched while the guides patiently watched us wander around in increasingly creative circles.

Someone said, "It's huge! We should be able to see it."

I spotted a small trail leading farther into the jungle and asked Francis, "Can I go up there?"

Internally, I was remembering his earlier instructions I took to heart about about not wandering off alone because of jaguars and other large cats.

He smiled and said, "Of course you can go anywhere!"

Which felt suspiciously like something a guide says before the jungle decides to adopts you.

However my heart for adventure won. I headed up the trail and suddenly there it was!! I yelled:
"OHHH, I FOUND IT!"

The biggest geocache I have ever found.

Hidden in the jungle, surrounded by adventure, my friends, monkeys probably judging us from the trees, and a crowd of excited geocachers charging uphill toward it.

It honestly felt magical.

Once the initial free-for-all settled down, I got my chance to take all the photos I wanted and leave my Jack Skellington glow-in-the-dark trackable inside.

Brazil Day 4 Status: • thrilled!! • Slightly concussed (probably) 🌿🤕 • Fully adventuring 🌎 • Being monitored by monkeys and possibly jaguars 🐒👀



</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364756401"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T11:15:46</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1645252">Tick_Magnet</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I am enjoying my time in Brazil. So much fun Geocaching and exploring with my friends. This is probably the highlight of my geocache in career. A wonderful experience! Thank you so much for keeping this special geocache alive this. TFTFUN!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-7.262433" lon="72.368017"><time>2004-08-04T00:00:00</time><name>GCK6A1</name><desc>Diego Garcia B.I.O.T. by tweetdrivr</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCK6A1</url><urlname>Diego Garcia B.I.O.T.</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="160986" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Diego Garcia B.I.O.T.</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>tweetdrivr</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="202162">tweetdrivr</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="11" inc="1">May require wading</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>British Indian Ocean Territory</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>A walk on the beach!</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Walk on out to the beach at Cannon Point. When you hit the beach,
turn left (West) and walk along the beach to coordinates S 07
15.716 E 072 22.069 and look for a path into the trees on your
left...follow it to the cache coords. 
&lt;p&gt;Cache is an ammo can. It is near the designated mountain bike
path on your way to this one...this path also makes a nice hiking
trail. Follow it in either direction and you will end up back at
the road.&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1238299535"><groundspeak:date>2024-06-04T00:09:52</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21905715">Balayang</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The situation here has been reviewed again.

Sufficient time has elapsed since the issues were highlighted, and nothing has been done to restore it. 

Circumstances that prevent timely maintenance can arise, and ample opportunity for the Cache Owner to get in touch to request a time extension has been provided.

No request has been received from the Cache Owner, tweetdrivr,  for further time to restore the cache.

On this basis, it appears to have been abandoned by the Owner and, therefore, will be Archived.

Caches lost in this manner will not be Unarchived.

This area is now available for other interested players to utilise for cache placement if viable locations can be found.

 
[Balayang -Geoff](https://www.geocaching.com/email/?guid=35e8567e-6d62-483c-9e3d-c8ec0ffd25bd)
Volunteer Community Reviewer 
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1229356753"><groundspeak:date>2024-04-24T03:42:10</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21905715">Balayang</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">### Cache Maintenance Visit Required please.###
This geocache has been brought to my attention as needing an Owner Maintenance visit, as the logs indicate that it is most likely missing, or else some other problem exists with the cache. See the [GCHQ Health Score](https://www.geocaching.com/help/index.php?pg=kb.chapter&amp;id=38&amp;pgid=713) process.
I agree that it certainly seems necessary to have it checked by the Cache Owner. 

The cache owner needs to:

* Take action to restore the cache or address issues such as correcting the D/T rating.
* Re-enable the cache by posting an Enable log
* Post an Owner Maintenance log to advise what has been done and to clear any Needs Maintenance attribute which is present. 

Otherwise :
* Post a Note Log to request more time if necessary or provide other information.. 
   **Do not use an Owner Maintenance log for this. That is for use only **when you actually do something to repair the cache**. 

Alternatively:

* Archive the cache, and remove any remaining geo-litter from the site.

In the meantime, I've temporarily disabled the cache page to await owner action by tweetdrivr and to take it off the playing board to prevent further geocaching community inconvenience.
[Please see the maintenance section of the Geocache Hiding Guidelines.](https://www.geocaching.com/play/guidelines?expand=1#cachemaintenance)
**I will check back in 30 days** to see that action has been by the CO.
If nothing has happened, I will assume that the cache has been abandoned, and, unfortunately, I will need to Archive this cache. 
*Caches archived because of lack of maintenance/abandonment will not be unarchived.*

The Geocaching Community needs to have a degree of certainty that a cache is in good condition, waiting to be found, and the CO has a responsibility to maintain their caches.

Please see  [my profile page](https://www.geocaching.com/p/default.aspx?u=Balayang) for additional information.
Thank you
Balayang -Geoff
