Katolicka Policja</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1208166429"><groundspeak:date>2023-12-10T13:51:09</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="47474511">jwhelan1</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The walking and hiking trail near where it claims to be but the problem is because it is on an island the path that is mentioned is not identifiable because of new growth. and there is no GPS on the island so unless you bring a Sat GPS the coordinates don't really help.  so finding the coordinates is not simple.  The instructions need more clarity. 

I found the hiking trail and it is a very nice walk and hike but the easier way to get to it is with the following instruction. 

There's a main path that leads to cannon point that is big enough for a car. If you are at cannon point and start following the car path away from cannon point you will see a walking path on your right. It takes you down the path mentioned and should be able to get you near the cache. Goodluck finding it 

(There is a path on your left also but that will take you back to lodging.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1188749449"><groundspeak:date>2023-08-17T09:20:11</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="46959458">SuggestiveCarp</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Went out for a second time and did a more thorough search, but I still couldn't turn anything up.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="18.344483" lon="-64.570183"><time>2002-04-02T00:00:00</time><name>GC4876</name><desc>Eyrie by Obelix</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC4876</url><urlname>Eyrie</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="18550" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Eyrie</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Obelix</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="29415">Obelix</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>British Virgin Islands</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Start from Deadmans beach Peters island and follow your GPS.
You are looking for Two words when you find them e-mail me do not enter the words on your visitor log, even if encryped. You may log your visit after you get confirmation from Obelix.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description /><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Get real - this is too easy!</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1271729230"><groundspeak:date>2024-11-24T20:00:08</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3864609">CacheShadow</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache page has been Archived.

If the Cache Owner believes an Unarchive exception should be made:
- A request that includes the GC code of this cache can be made using the Send Email link on my profile page.
- The cache must be compliant with the current Guidelines.
- The request must be within 3 months of the Archive action.

CacheShadow - Community Volunteer Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1267320286"><groundspeak:date>2024-10-25T22:25:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3864609">CacheShadow</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache page has been Disabled as: 
- There appear to be issues with the cache and/or
- The Cache Owner has not posted a log in response to an earlier Geocaching HQ or Reviewer notification.

If the Cache Owner wishes to abandon the cache/free up space in the game they should:
- Use the Archive option on the cache page to retire the cache permanently from the website.
- Retrieve any placed containers/physical elements that may still be in place.

If the Cache Owner intends to keep the cache in the game, they need to:
- Post ongoing/regular status updates on the cache page using Write Note logs.
- Confirm when an in-person physical maintenance visit has occurred with an Owner Maintenance log.
- Use the Enable option to confirm when the cache is back in the game/ready to be found.

If a Write Note log from the cache owner is not posted on this cache page within 30 days, a Reviewer Archive action should be expected.

CacheShadow - Community Volunteer Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1212817961"><groundspeak:date>2024-01-17T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7225028">Coolman BZ</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We‘ll be back again! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1022714417"><groundspeak:date>2021-05-29T21:00:11</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3675695">Greatland Reviewer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Dear Cache Owner:

I'm checking up on caches that have had the "Needs Maintenance" attribute set in case you didn't see the "Needs Maintenance" log e-mail come in or you didn't notice the "Needs Maintenance" attribute that is currently displayed on your cache page.   In many situations, you may have already performed maintenance and the cache is all right.  If that's the case, you can clear the "Needs Maintenance" attribute (the white wrench in the red square) from your cache page by clicking on "Log geocache" and writing an "Owner Maintenance" log.   If you haven't checked on your cache since a cacher wrote a "Needs Maintenance" log, please do so soon so new visitors have a good experience finding your cache. 

Clearing the "Needs Maintenance" attribute when your cache is all right keeps your cache page accurate and will potentially bring more cachers to your hide since some cachers filter out caches that have that attribute set. 

No further Reviewer action will be taken on the cache UNLESS there are additional issues such as an extended string of DNF logs or a "Needs Archived" log. Groundspeak acknowledges that COVID-19 restrictions may preclude timely cache maintenance, so as long as a Cache Owner provides periodic updates via "Note Logs" written to the cache page, the cache will not get archived.

Cachers are reminded that the "Needs Maintenance" log should be used only if the cache is found and there are known maintenance issues. If the cache IS NOT found, the appropriate log is the "Didn't Find It" (DNF) log type. A cacher can't know if a cache needs maintenance if s/he hasn't actually seen the cache. 

Thanks for your help! 

Greatland Reviewer
Groundspeak Volunteer
My Profile: [http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=6354843d-6bec-4737-8db5-77907f57de8a](http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=6354843d-6bec-4737-8db5-77907f57de8a)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="910529849"><groundspeak:date>2020-02-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1040960">MikeSierra</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">At White Bay the road uphill is 
decorarted with a "private island" sign. We are on holiday and don't want any discussion with the residence guards. Sad, but this is a DNF for us.
Viele Gruesse,
Crew of Catamaran "Saphir"</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="4.918033" lon="114.983583"><time>2008-10-12T00:00:00</time><name>GC1H7VK</name><desc>Mar-Cat by Flaming J</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1H7VK</url><urlname>Mar-Cat</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1026400" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Mar-Cat</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Flaming J</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1146141">Anigma</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Brunei</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>It is situated in one of the many peaks of Bukit MarKucing(Kucing in malay means Cat).  Over here the view is marvelous with patches of garden and fruit orchards along the way.  Its best to hike after 4pm, then you can catch the sunset.  There are huts along the way where you can catch your breath or just simply have munchies and enjoy the cool breeze and the view.  This trail is not as busy as Bukit Shahbandar.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The cache is a small transparent container with blue lid.  Inside contains Paper, Pencil(for logging),Agensi Anti Dadah Kebangsaan(ADK) key chain, Year 2004 badge,Kenali Negara Kita badge, One box of REX Hotel Vietnam matches  and One box of Beverly Hotel matches.

Last checked March 2010.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>North East corner of the Hut</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1345292821"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-17T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3032475">jatmo</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Not hidden how I expected but the pictures narrowed it down to the exact spot. 
It's great to find the oldest cache in another country. Hopefully we can find a ride back to town on the first day of the Chinese New Year</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1345327491"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-17T09:47:42</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="164089">jtee</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">this cache was on our list to get so we took the bus downtown and heading to the clock when a lady asked if we needed help or a ride and she offered to take us to the trail head..she said it being a holiday that a grab could take awhile..so this worked out great for us and up we went in search of the oldest in Brunei..we searched everywhere and then saw a Pic that helped us out..the cache is now magnetic up on the inside of the roof..would never had known to look for that .but sooo glad we got signed in..back down at the road we tried to get a grab with not much luck but a car came by and offered us a ride back into town so it all worked out for getting this cache..thks for the fun </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1344292233"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54457797">Leaf891</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Stated the hike from the opposite end of the road unknowingly, passed by Bukit Muntah ( Throw up hill) rightfully named, encountered a snake in a tree trunk and had to find shelter halfway through the trail from the rain. TYFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1328274440"><groundspeak:date>2025-10-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7461642">Teamgeist1976</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Yes the oldest one :-)

Hello from Teamgeist1976! 🌍✈️

This time our caching adventure takes us far, far away – straight into Southeast Asia! We started our journey in the buzzing metropolis of Kuala Lumpur, where the Petronas Towers are shining like giant signal beacons for lost geocachers. From there we hopped over to the Sultanate of Brunei, just to make sure the Sultan knows what geocaching is all about 😉.

But the real jungle fun begins on Borneo (Malaysia):
🐒 Sandakan – hoping the proboscis monkeys don’t laugh too hard at our GPS skills.
🌊 Semporna – diving, caching, and trying not to get tangled in fishing nets.
🌳 Mulu Caves – because every real geocacher needs at least one bat-friend.
🏙 Kuching – city of cats, and we’re already wondering if they will help us find the caches or just stare at us suspiciously.
⛰ Kota Kinabalu – mountains, sea, and probably a few more DNFs than we’d like to admit
and furthermore destinations

Our mission:

Discover wildlife 🦎🐘🦜

Meet people 🤝

Explore cities 🏙

And, of course, add some smileys to our map 😁

We’re sure that somewhere between palm trees, satay stalls, and mosquito bites we’ll find a cache or two (or get lost trying). Either way: it’s all part of the adventure.

Thanks for keeping the geocaching spirit alive in this part of the world – greetings from Teamgeist1976 from Germany 🇩🇪.

TFTC and happy caching!
Da wir unsere Zeit lieber mit Rätsel und Suchen in freier Natur verbringen, das heißt wir sind lieber draußen beim Spielen :-), sind wir leider leider nicht immer der Lage lange Logs zu schreiben.
Unser Dank und Respekt haben alle Cacher und Cacherinnen, die sich nicht scheuen den großen Aufwand auf sich zu nehmen um mehr oder weniger verzwickte Rätsel, Verstecke und Dosen aus-zudenken. Jeder Cache ist die Zeit wert, die wir in ihn investieren und wir freuen uns über jede Do-se, die wir finden.
Wir haben ein tolles Hobby das wir hoffentlich noch lange am Leben halten können wenn jeder ein Stück zurück gibt was er bekommt.
Vielen Dank an alle!
Danke für den Cache :-) Thanks for that Cache :-) Merci pour la Cache :-) Dzięki za Cache :-) Grazie per questo Cache :-) Takk for at Cache :-) Obrigado por isso Cache :-) Gracias por el Cache :-) Díky za keš :-) Ačiū už tą talpyklą :-) Paldies par šo Cache :-) Aitäh selle eest Cache :-) Спасибо за то кэш :-) Kiitos, että Cache :-) Tack för att Cache :-) Tak for denne Cache :-) Hvala cache :-) Ευχαριστώ για τη μνήμη cache :-) 感謝您的高速緩存 :-) Önbellek için teşekkürler :-) Köszönjük, hogy a cache :-) Bedankt voor de cache :-) Graças para o cache :-) Dankon pro la kaŝmemorone :-) Dankä für de cäsch :-) მადლობა გეოქეშისთვის :-) նորհակալություն ջեոքեշի համար :-)
Happy Caching Mr. und Mrs. Teamgeist 1976 :-)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1305435564"><groundspeak:date>2025-06-17T23:50:24</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21558658">fahmi_bakar</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found this with matthewgibbs. Only have time to log today. TFTC. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="11.957383" lon="2.013367"><time>2009-01-07T00:00:00</time><name>GC1M1N7</name><desc>Parc W - Kabougou by el_daxo</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1M1N7</url><urlname>Parc W - Kabougou</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1109840" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Parc W - Kabougou</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>el_daxo</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="363933">el Daxo</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Micro</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="0">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="0">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="1">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="31" inc="1">Camping nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="43" inc="1">Livestock nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Burkina Faso</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description>This Cache is at the park entrance Kabougou and is intended as a reward for people driving all the way down to the National W Transborder Park http://www.parc-w.net/en/html/intro.html . It is a nice park but be advised that since the European Union stopped their financial engagement in July 2008 you can not buy any food or drinks in the park. This is a pity because the whole nice infrastructure is going down really fast. So get your things at latest at Diapaga. 

In the Park the main road are in good condition but for the other roads you need a 4 wheeler and a armed guide.

A local resident will assist with maintenance of the cache if necessary.  Details are on file with geocaching.com</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>filmbox- right wall</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1348758996"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-13T14:37:24</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6596893">pitfeder</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">17 Jahre ohne Found. Wahnsinn. 

Happy Caching wünscht 

Pitfeder</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="193484051"><groundspeak:date>2011-10-18T23:37:03</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="363933">el Daxo</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Parc W - Kabougou was transferred from Taddl to user el_daxo</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="61292491"><groundspeak:date>2009-01-25T06:35:30</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="481249">Fish Eagle</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Published</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-2.846333" lon="30.346133"><time>2011-11-14T00:00:00</time><name>GC383EA</name><desc>In the Wall - Muyinga by Stalex1411</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC383EA</url><urlname>In the Wall - Muyinga</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="2601098" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>In the Wall - Muyinga</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Stalex1411</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="3147741">Stalex1411</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Micro</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Burundi</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>As the first geocache to be placed in Burundi we hope that many of the expat community in the country will take up this great hobby.

Please note BYOP (bring your own pen!)

Enjoy, and beware of the many children/locals/muggles who will always be watching!</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Muyinga is home to beautiful scenery, a nearby hydro-electric dam and a gold mine industry set up by the Belgiums.

This cache was placed on a recent trip to visit the country where I grew up as well as to introduce my wife to the place I still call 'Home'</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Third hole in from the corner of the wall</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1124211885"><groundspeak:date>2022-09-06T10:16:43</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Due to no response from the CO after the request to maintain or replace the cache, I am archiving it to, stop it showing on the listings  and/or to create place for the geocaching community.

The [Geocache Maintenance guideline](http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) explains a CO's responsibility towards checking and maintaining the cache when problems are reported. 

Please note that if geocaches are archived by a reviewer or Geocaching HQ for lack of maintenance, they are not eligible for unarchival. This is explained in the [Help Center](http://support.groundspeak.com//index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=70)

If the CO feels that this cache has been archived in error please feel free to contact me within 30 days,  via email or message via my profile ,quoting the GC number concerned

Thank you for understanding

Knagur Green</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1099636099"><groundspeak:date>2022-05-28T01:23:05</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Needs Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="294500">rothkids</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This geocacher reported that this geocache should be archived. A community volunteer reviewer has been notified.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1099550323"><groundspeak:date>2022-05-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4703755">CSI Styria</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">rothkids logged a "found it" and then wrote that the geocache is no longer there [?] [?] [?]


strange!!

(I think, one "needs archieved" is enough [:D])</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1099424335"><groundspeak:date>2022-05-27T11:48:49</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings 

We have received a request to archive your cache page as the physical cache appears to be in need of maintenance and there has been no recent indication that timely maintenance may be forthcoming.

 I'm temporarily disabling it, to give you an opportunity to check on the cache, and take whatever action is necessary.

You are responsible for occasional visits to your cache to ensure it is in proper working order, especially when someone reports a problem with the cache (missing, damaged, wet, etc.) or posts a Needs Maintenance log. Temporarily disable your cache to let others know not to search for it until you have addressed the problem.

Please enable your cache by selecting 'enable' on the right hand side of the listing , once the cache has been replaced/repaired, or checked that it is still in situ.

The [Geocache Maintenance guideline](http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) explains a CO's responsibility towards checking and maintaining the cache when problems are reported. 

Caches that have been archived for lack of maintenance will not be unarchived. This is explained in the [Help Center](http://support.groundspeak.com//index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=70)

If you no longer wish to maintain the cache then the listing should be archived.

**Please respond to this situation in a timely manner (i.e., within 30 days) to prevent the cache from being archived for non-responsiveness. If you plan on repairing this cache,but cannot get to it within 30 days, please log a note to the cache page (not email) to let the community know**

Thank you for understanding 

Knagur Green
Groundspeak Volunteer Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1099636098"><groundspeak:date>2022-05-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="294500">rothkids</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Logging as a find, although did not locate container. Wall had been recently repaired and holes filled with mortar. Many curious people wondering why we were looking at a wall in the middle of nowhere.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="11.391733" lon="14.56335"><time>2003-07-26T00:00:00</time><name>GCGH6Q</name><desc>Wasa Park by SuperCesc</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCGH6Q</url><urlname>Wasa Park</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="82082" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Wasa Park</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>SuperCesc</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="81086">SuperCesc</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Cameroon</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>It's easy to arrive here.
It's in the entrance of Wasa National Park. In North of Cameroon.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>In our travel in Cameroon, we found a very interesting country. We went in the north of country, and we arrive just in Lake Chad.
In Wasa National Park, it's possible to see elephants, lions, and a lot of animals.
In the entrace of the parck, there is a "hotel", and a "bar" (I don't know if it's always open).
And in this bar, there are a poster with a drawing of all the animals that you can find there.
To arrive in this place you must take the North Principal Road of the coutry, from Maroua to the North.
Before to arrive at Wasa town, you must turn right. Just in the entrance of the park (N 11º23.495 ; E 14º33.795).
Now you are very near of the virtual-cache.
The questions to know if you really saw the panel are this:
1-How many animals are in the panel?
2-Wich is the first animal on each row?</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1297079530"><groundspeak:date>2025-05-07T23:17:52</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="52762504">LULU785</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">g</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1290833212"><groundspeak:date>2025-04-12T20:09:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="28556045">MirMia</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Accidentally put that I found</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1290832168"><groundspeak:date>2025-04-12T20:06:33</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="28556045">MirMia</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I loved this one so cool!! TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1287493845"><groundspeak:date>2025-03-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="745875">otti20</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">In Westafrika unterwegs um neue Länder zu entdecken. Dabei haben wir auch den" Wasa Park " gefunden.
Danke an SuperCesc fürs zeigen des schönen Ortes. Letzter Cache in Kamerun.
Gruss und Dank aus der Schweiz.
otti20
24. März 2025</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1287493910"><groundspeak:date>2025-03-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1126805">lutzenland</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Last cache in Camerun. Intesting Park area.

Tftc

lutzenland</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="44.588833" lon="-64.1725"><time>2000-06-28T00:00:00</time><name>GCBBA</name><desc>Geocache--Canada's 1st geocache by ken kane</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCBBA</url><urlname>Geocache--Canada's 1st geocache</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3002" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Geocache--Canada's 1st geocache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>ken kane</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="10664">eastriver</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="64" inc="0">Tree climbing required</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Canada</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Nova Scotia</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Due to highway twining construction this cache has been moved temporarily to near East River Provincial (picnic) Park (across the road from the Park).The new co-ordinates are as indicated above.                                                             
This Canada's first Geocache and is located about 30 minutes from Halifax on a major highway. It is not difficult, but is meant to attract people using one of our main routes in NS( Hwy # 103). It is only a few minutes walk from the highway and is in a LARGE ammo can. Take some fly dope !!! This cache was originaly named GC41 but was relisted as GCBBA when caches were taken out of the (GC.com) site admin account and given to individuals. On 24th June/06 a geostone giving the details and co-ordinates of GCBBA was unveiled at an Event at Graves Island Provincial Park. The geostone is near the Administration Building in Graves Island Park, which is about 7 Km west of GCBBA on Highway #3. A short drive, with easy access to the Park. Access to the Park is available year round. When the gate is closed just walk up the paved road. This geostone was built and designed by Wallace_River. The sale of "Canada's First Geocache" geocoin paid for the Event. If you come from outside Nova Scotia I would love to know where you come from. Many thanks to those who take the time to post their pics. Keep them coming. It was confirmed by Geocaching HQ that GCBBA was Canada's first Traditional Cache to reach 500 Favorite Points. Thank you to all those who helped reach that goal, and many thanks to those who continue to add their Favorite Points.


</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Big rock.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364983344"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T11:57:51</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54312679">t4teocaching</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A quick search along the way to the first camping trip of the season helped us find this one!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363473801"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="526318">ZSteve</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found this one with HonuHideout today.  We're in the area for a very brief visit and spent the day exploring geocaching style.  It was a beautiful day to be out and I really enjoyed walking around the area and seeing the sights while finding caches.  We didn't have time to find all of the caches that we wanted to during our time here, but maybe we'll get a chance to come back again some time to find some more.  This one has been on my list for a long time, so it was great to finally be able to find it today.  Favorite Point from me.  Thanks for the fun!





</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363338750"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="51000223">HonuHideout</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">So excited to have traveled from the cruise ship to get this highly sought after cache!  Took three TB’s, left three. Found it with ZSteve &amp; put green ink on the log! We’ve made our way to Canada via the cruise ship that left from Florida, USA for a fantastic 2026 geocaching trip. Any day is a great day when it includes Geocaching, right! Trying to keep up with my 100-day streak to meet a challenge.  TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364747077"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6174962">iicydiamonds</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thank you for maintaining this cache for so long! Although my travel companion is not a cacher, she thought that getting Canada's oldest sounded "really special", and agreed to a bit of a detour! And she was right, it was really special, even if I couldn't share the find with another actual cacher. My mom was still excited for me!

Left 3 TBs to continue their journeys!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362421139"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T07:02:57</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="335242">ScouterHerb &amp; MrsB</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">My caching name is ScouterHerb &amp; MrsB, although MrsB died in 2024. My daughter's were going to fly with  me to Nova Scotia to enable me to find GCBBA. However my arthritic legs are making it hard for me to find any cache let alone fly across the country for one. I will be 88 this summer. 

I did want to share the information I would have posted had I found it. 

I am from Sechelt, BC which is 4428 km West of GCBBA. A number of years ago I wondered how many Caches had been placed in the world in the first year of caching, May 3rd, 2000 to May 2nd, 2001. So, as a 10th Anniversary of Geocahing project, I decided to compile my own list, with a Canadian perspective. It turns out there were 2032 Caches placed in that period. Of those to date 1333 have been archived leaving 699 still available. You may view them on my web site at:   https://www.barge.ca/oldcachestotal.htm 60 of them were Canadian, of which 32 have been archived. 
GCBBA was of course the 1st placed in Nova Scotia,  the 1st placed in Canada and the 49th placed in the World. I have a list of all 699 still available at https://www.geocaching.com/plan/lists/BM7NXPA there are currently 8 of these disabled.
I would like to thank Ken Kane for keeping this one active and available. - Herb Barge

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="799270987"><groundspeak:date>2018-08-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I travel a lot for work.  I always try to sneak in a geocache or two (or 10) after work or by taking a later flight.  I haven’t been to Nova Scotia, so when the project came up in Halifax, I made some plans!  I was going to have TW (the wife) join me for a long weekend, but that didn’t work out, so I quickly switched to plan B.  I used Monday and Sunday as travel days and took a vacation day on Tuesday to explore Nova Scotia before my work and then on Friday evening high tailed it to New Brunswick followed by exploring Prince Edward Island on Saturday.  What a great trip it was!

My first stop of course was to get the oldest cache in Canada!  What a great spot.  I had never thought to use the middle of the exit ramp!  Brilliant!

Unfortunately, I should have done a bit more recon on the best path in, but I saw another car on the side of the ramp so I assumed they new more than I did and parked near by and went in from there.  We both took the hard way in and the easy way out.  He also scared the beans out of me as I was making my way to GZ.

Loved the giant container and the fun selfy sign.

Thanks for keeping this one going!

How could I not give it a favorite point?  Of course I did.

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="16.7522" lon="-24.758416666666665"><time>2008-01-17T00:00:00</time><name>GC18PPB</name><desc>I feel fine by supermo</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC18PPB</url><urlname>I feel fine</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="772564" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>I feel fine</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>supermo</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="227929">supermo</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Cabo Verde</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This cache was placed by the crew of the SY "I feel fine".</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This cache was placed by the crew of the SY "I feel fine" - Christoph, Denise, Johannes, Kurt, Mario, Pablo, Ralph and Ueli.
Original content:
- 10g of Tiger Balm
- Keyring with compass
- Keyring "Switzerland" with bottle opener
- 2 Pencils
- 1 Eurex Pen
- 1 Fishing bait
- 1 Lighter (Regionalgefaengnis Thun)</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Search for a removable stone.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1154462977"><groundspeak:date>2023-03-20T12:51:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9544212">Bitaro</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Olá supermo,
Esta geocache foi arquivada por falta de uma resposta atempada e/ou adequada perante uma situação de falta de manutenção.
Relembro a secção das [Linhas de Orientação](https://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) que regulam a manutenção das geocaches:
&gt; *O dono da geocache é responsável por visitas à localização física.*

&gt;*Você é responsável por visitas ocasionais à sua geocache para assegurar que está tudo em ordem para funcionar, especialmente quando alguém reporta um problema com a geocache (desaparecimento, estrago, humidade/infiltrações, etc.), ou faz um registo "Precisa de Manutenção". Desactive temporariamente a sua geocache para que os outros saibam que não devem procurar a geocache até que tenha resolvido o problema. É-lhe concedido um período razoável de tempo - **geralmente até 4 semanas** - dentro do qual deverá verificar o estado da sua geocache. Se a geocache não estiver a receber a manutenção necessária ou estiver temporariamente desactivada por um longo período de tempo, poderemos arquivar a página da geocache.*

**Se no local existe algum recipiente por favor recolha-o a fim de evitar que se torne lixo (geolitter).**

Uma vez que se trata de um caso de falta de manutenção a sua geocache não poderá ser desarquivada. Caso submeta uma nova será tido em conta este arquivamento por falta de manutenção.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1145265393"><groundspeak:date>2023-01-15T20:06:27</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9544212">Bitaro</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Olá supermo,

Pelo teor dos últimos registos, parece necessária a intervenção do owner para verificar o estado da geocache.
Até lá, ficará temporariamente inactiva.

Por favor leia atentamente as [Linhas de Orientação](https://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) que regulam a manutenção das geocaches:
&gt; *O dono da geocache é responsável por visitas à localização física.*

&gt;*Você é responsável por visitas ocasionais à sua geocache para assegurar que está tudo em ordem para funcionar, especialmente quando alguém reporta um problema com a geocache (desaparecimento, estrago, humidade/infiltrações, etc.), ou faz um registo "Precisa de Manutenção". Desactive temporariamente a sua geocache para que os outros saibam que não devem procurar a geocache até que tenha resolvido o problema. É-lhe concedido um período razoável de tempo - **geralmente até 4 semanas** - dentro do qual deverá verificar o estado da sua geocache. Se a geocache não estiver a receber a manutenção necessária ou estiver temporariamente desactivada por um longo período de tempo, poderemos arquivar a página da geocache.*

Esta designação serve para geocaches que estão com alguma questão pendente ou um problema temporário por resolver.
Como owner, tem ao dispor, pelo menos, quatro soluções possíveis:

1. **Efectuar a manutenção necessária e reactivar a geocache**, dentro do prazo estabelecido pelas Linhas de Orientação
2. **Colocar uma nota na geocache com o plano de manutenção**, caso esta não possa ocorrer num curto espaço de tempo. Nessa nota deve constar:
  * o prazo em que pretende efectuar a manutenção,
  * o argumento pelo qual o prazo indicado abaixo terá de ser ultrapassado para que fique novamente activa;
3. Caso não consiga assegurar a manutenção da mesma, pode **considerar o processo de [adopção](https://www.geocaching.com/adopt/)** por um geocacher local;
4. **Arquivar a geocache** se não tiver disponibilidade para assegurar o estado pleno da mesma. Por favor, tenha em consideração que nesta opção é necessário remover a geocache ou os conteúdos da mesma para evitar que se tornem lixo (*geolitter*).

Assim, caso não seja feita manutenção ou indicado um motivo válido pelo qual a geocache deva estar desactivada além do tempo previsto pelas Linhas de Orientação, a mesma será arquivada num **prazo de 60 dias**.
Relembro que não é possível desarquivar uma geocache que seja arquivada por falta de manutenção.


Obrigado pela colaboração
**Bitaro**
Community Volunteer Reviewer

[Centro de Ajuda](https://www.geocaching.com/help)
[Linhas Orientação](https://www.geocaching.com/play/guidelines)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1143942197"><groundspeak:date>2023-01-06T17:24:20</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Needs Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="43958675">Salaman2</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Tento hráč ohlásil, že by uvedená keška měla být archivována. Informace byla předána místně příslušnému reviewerovi.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1143942195"><groundspeak:date>2023-01-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="43958675">Salaman2</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Its about 10 years and no cache here. I think the cache is lost.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="188264389"><groundspeak:date>2011-09-09T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4429090">Foxmetz</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Géocache de ouf!!!!!!!

FTF!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="19.37905" lon="-81.407567"><time>2001-11-22T00:00:00</time><name>GC2978</name><desc>TO HELL AND BACK by NCFLYERS - The Double J's of Fortuna, CA</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC2978</url><urlname>TO HELL AND BACK</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="10616" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>TO HELL AND BACK</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>NCFLYERS - The Double J's of Fortuna, CA</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="7209">ncflyers</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="1">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="0">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="1">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="29" inc="1">Telephone nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Cayman Islands</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This is a virtual cache located on the island of Grand Cayman, British West Indies.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This is one of those sites that does not involve hiking. In fact, the coordinates are to one of two different parking lots. If your receiver has brought you to the hottest post office in the world, &lt;b&gt;&lt;font color="#FF0000"&gt;HELL&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;, you have found it! Take a picture with your camera. Remember, there is no tupperware or ammo can hidden here! Bring a postcard to mail to yourself if you want to receive a special souvenir postmark. &lt;b&gt;&lt;font color="#FF0000"&gt;HELL&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;, we've never seen anything like this. Go to the back of the post office, there is a small passageway that goes through to the back. &lt;font color="#0000FF"&gt;&lt;b&gt;In your post of this find, you no longer have to post a description of what you see at the find; however&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;, &lt;font color="#FF0000"&gt;&lt;b&gt;you MUST TAKE A PHOTO OF YOURSELF OR YOURSELVES AT HELL AND POST IT WITH YOUR GEOCACHING ENTRY, or, for those that do not have the means to post a picture, send a post card (or letter if you wish) from you in Hell with the HELL postmark to:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="#FF0000"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Groundspeak HQ, 837 N 34TH ST STE 300, SEATTLE, WA, 98103-8965&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
Geocaching.com has mandated us to beef up our requirements or close down this geocache. Thank you for your time.
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="#0000FF"&gt;&lt;font color="#FF0000"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font color="#0000FF"&gt;"Edison Medicine": Anything that brightens your day is a good thing!&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font color="#0000FF"&gt;NCFLYERS – The Double J’s of Fortuna, CA&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt; &lt;img src="http://www.geocaching.com/images/icons/icon_smile_wink.gif" border="0" align="middle" /&gt; &lt;img src="http://www.geocaching.com/images/icons/icon_smile_wink.gif" border="0" align="middle" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Hope you enjoyed your trip to HELL and back. We sure did. Have a Great Geocaching Day!NCFLYERS – The Double J’s of Fortuna, CA.
</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364592670"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T09:11:09</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="32625060">JoeRVandal</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it with geobarbie9!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364592101"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T09:09:08</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="32622427">geobarbie9</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found with Joervandal. What an unusual place</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360272570"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-10T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7539208">PIXIP</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks! 🇮🇱</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357836636"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-28T16:38:52</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6561776">Mouetstyle</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Forgot the photo...</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357834273"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6561776">Mouetstyle</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Pour cette 1ère cache de notre séjour sur Cayman, mon choix se porte sur l'ancienne de l'île. Pas grand monde vers 10h00 du matin, le magasin est fermé, nous y reviendrons pour la cache physique. L'endroit est très surprenant, la nature est belle.  Merci à l'owner de me donner l'opportunité de visiter le lieu. 
For our first geocache of our stay on Cayman, I chose the oldest one on the island. There weren't many people around at 10:00 AM, the shop was closed, so we'll come back for the physical cache. The place is very surprising, thank you to the owner for giving me the opportunity to visit.
TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="481856143"><groundspeak:date>2015-03-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Mixed feeling on all of this HELL business.  Not that Hell isn't a nice place to visit, but I sure wouldn't want to live there!

Got there and back on a Sunday bus schedule.  It all worked out but  we were a bit worried for a while.  I really like the bus system on Grand Cayman.

Thanks for the Virtual Hide! 

I'm also taking a bunch of travel bugs to Hell!

Cheers!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="12.119767" lon="15.025667"><time>2009-05-13T00:00:00</time><name>GC1REHX</name><desc>GO TCHAD GO by AERO30, adopted by merdian </desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1REHX</url><urlname>GO TCHAD GO</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1241394" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>GO TCHAD GO</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>AERO30, adopted by merdian </groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1049026">merdian</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="1">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="1">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="1">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="29" inc="1">Telephone nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Chad</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>FIRST CACHE OF TCHAD - la TCHADIENNE
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The cache is easy to find, placed inside the NOVOTEL garden (now Hotel Irrisor, Hotel La Tchadienne) to avoid risk with local people who always look at tourists. The box is near the carpark left of the hotel entrance. Access is free. Be careful to be discret!
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Magnetic key box very close to the third rain downpipe (counting from the south = first downpipe)</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1287493971"><groundspeak:date>2025-03-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="745875">otti20</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">In Westafrika unterwegs um neue Länder zu entdecken. Dabei haben wir auch den" GO TCHAD GO " gefunden.
Danke an AERO30, adopted by merdian fürs zeigen des schönen Ortes.
Gruss und Dank aus der Schweiz.
otti20
25. März 2025</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1287493325"><groundspeak:date>2025-03-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1126805">lutzenland</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On our tour on Africa otti20 and me arrived in Tchad und could find this (new?) Box.

Tftc

lutzenland</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1277879770"><groundspeak:date>2025-01-19T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10369208">Karlusia</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nice time in Tchad, and of course some geocaching around.
Nice place and hotel that you can walk around
Happy Geocaching

🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟HAPPY GEOCACHING🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫⭐✨🌟🌟✨⭐💫</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1336022027"><groundspeak:date>2025-01-10T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2022811">nocybe1810</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It's always great traveling to hot and sunny countries when it's coldish at home... [:D]
So, this January 2025, a little group of 15 geocachers wants to discover some interesting new countries in Africa. On our trip, we visit (or pass through) Egypt, Chad, Congo, Cameroon, Equatorial Guinea, Gabon, and Sao Tome and Principe. Of course, the goal is to find geocaches in all these countries. But they are not that frequent here, so we have also time for excursions and sightseeing.
We had nice insights into the local life, met friendly people and had a lot of fun.

On our second day, we arrive in N'Djamena. Well, Mrs. Brummelbären always says "In Africa the clock is ticking differently", so we patiently wait for the hotel shuttle picking us up... Which never happens. The policeman responsible for the security is helpful and tries to call the hotel for us, but phones also work differently in Africa. We end up in taking taxis. [:D]
Once checked in at the hotel, we leave immediately to discover the city driving around by taxi, of course guided by the few available geocaches. But we also have time to visit a local craft market, the place in front of the president's palace and the river's shore close to our hotel.
The day ends with a lovely event, where we meet a nice geocacher from Poland and her boyfriend who is living here. 

To save space in the logbooks, we sign usually as team "CR-CA25".
Thanks to all owners for contributing to a perfect GC journey.

Merci beaucoup pour cette cache! 👍👍👍
#28.312 Greetings from sunny Nice 💙🤍❤️
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1279416125"><groundspeak:date>2025-01-10T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4427880">TEmLy11</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Endlich sollte es mit Gleichgesinnten oder wie Andere auch sagen würden Gleichverrückten, wobei ich verrückt in diesem Fall als Neid also der höchsten Form der Anerkennung verstanden habe, nach Afrika gehen.
Dabei ging es über Ägypten, den Tschad, Camerun, die Republik Congo, Gabun, Äquatorialguinea, Sao Tome e Pricipe und Portugal wieder zurück nach Deutschland.
Hier waren Brummelbären, btjg, Ci_Ti, Darmstädter, mao_gc, Höfi1, jowo2003, Kleinzschachwitzer, Landmaus, nocybe1810,ralf_de, stellarissa, tinyredfox, Virtualboy und meine Wenigkeit anwesend, wobei wir auch zwischenzeitlich mit CR-CA25 geloggt haben, um die bereitliegenden Logbücher ein wenig zu schonen.
Insgesamt war es ein anstrengendes, aufregendes Abenteuer, welches mit dieser tollen Gruppe aber auch einfach nur riesigen Spaß gemacht hat. Ich werde mich immer wieder freuen, wenn ich den einen oder die andere aus der Gruppe wiedersehen oder vielleicht sogar noch die eine oder andere gemeinsame Reise machen darf.
Damit unser wunderschönstes gemeinsames Hobby nicht zu kurz kam, haben wir versucht möglich zu machen und zu besuchen, was nur eben möglich war.
TFTC - TEmLy11

Translation with translate.google.de:
Finally, we were going to Africa with like-minded people or, as others would say, like-crazy people, whereby I understood crazy in this case as envy, the highest form of recognition.
The trip went via Egypt, Chad, Cameroon, the Republic of Congo, Gabon, Equatorial Guinea, Sao Tome e Pricipe and Portugal back to Germany.
Brummelbären, btjg, Ci_Ti, Darmstädter, mao_gc, Höfi1, jowo2003, Kleinzschachwitzer, Landmaus, nocybe1810,ralf_de, ​​stellarissa, tinyredfox, Virtualboy and yours truly were there, and we also logged with CR-CA25 in the meantime to save the logbooks that were ready.
All in all, it was an exhausting, exciting adventure, but also just great fun with this great group. I will always be happy when I see one or the other member of the group again or maybe even go on one or two trips together.
So that our most wonderful shared hobby was not neglected, we tried to make it possible and visit as many as possible.
TFTC - TEmLy11</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="30.7348" lon="104.14356666666667"><time>2001-10-02T00:00:00</time><name>GC201F</name><desc>Berry Virtual Cache by Savoy</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC201F</url><urlname>Berry Virtual Cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="8223" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Berry Virtual Cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Savoy</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="18222">Savoy</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Not chosen</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>China</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Alt=529m The only reason this is a 'two' is because you have to get to china!</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>I decided to place my first China geocache as a ‘virtual’ cache. Once I have my letter translated into Chinese you can look forward to see a few more ‘traditional’ caches in our area.
&lt;P&gt;
If you are in the close, you are most likely headed for this destination away. Head to the location the safest way possible (which leaves all Chinese taxies out of the picture!). Once there look for the most obvious landmark and email me with the proof of your visit (I promise you won’t have to scratch your head long for that one.) You’ll get via email a certificate (suitable-for-framing of course) noting your accomplishment. PLEASE (as I have noticed is the case with most virtual geocaches) DON’T leave a log entry stating your answer.
&lt;P&gt;
Enjoy! 
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Sorry, no spoilers here... if you really need help, feel free to email me. </groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363701683"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2351150">MTKEus</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#30738

Another highlight of my trip were these cute pandas.

Thanks for showing and for this vc
I deleted the obvious thing in the first photo to not spoiler.

Best regards
MTKEus

In: Fp

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362388724"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T09:26:05</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="443411">luke_</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thank you for the virtual cache! Visiting from Canada. Sent over the requirement. TFTVC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361026602"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-15T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="34960285">cadi63</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Bei einer China Rundreise darf dieses Highlight nicht fehlen</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360788388"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-14T11:05:13</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5060899">Cassow11ry</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">From Beijing I travel to Chengdu for the pandas…  I was glad to see a cache here!!   

Thanks for cache.. sending China lots of love from Australia!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360512307"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-12T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8366191">samdoggy0901</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Last day of our China tour. Great place to finish up. Lots of pandas out today. TFTC. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-10.559883" lon="105.646017"><time>2009-06-05T00:00:00</time><name>GC1TAXW</name><desc>The Christmas Train by daysix</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1TAXW</url><urlname>The Christmas Train</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1267681" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>The Christmas Train</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>daysix</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="815956">daysix</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Christmas Island</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>An easy cache accessible by 2WD vehicle</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The first cache on Christmas Island; near the location of the original phosphate mining town at South point.

Most of the town was destroyed when the mine expanded the population move to settlement at the other end of the Island.

There are several Chinese temples on the way to visit and a round trip should take less than an hour.

The cache is maintained by Linda Cash of the Christmas Island Tourism Association, who is the editor of “the essential Christmas Island travel guide” and along with her husband Phil is a fantastic ambassador for the Island, many thanks Linda and Phil for as fantastic time.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Down the stairs and to the left</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1284176542"><groundspeak:date>2025-03-08T12:18:13</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21905715">Balayang</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">
The situation here has been reviewed again.

Sufficient time has elapsed since the issues were highlighted, and nothing has been done to restore it. 
Circumstances that prevent timely maintenance can arise, and ample opportunity for the Cache Owner to get in touch to request a time extension has been provided.
No request has been received from the Cache Owner, daysix,  for further time to restore the cache.
** It appears to have been abandoned by the Owner and, therefore, will be Archived.**
**Caches lost in this manner will not be Unarchived.**
This area is now available for other interested players to utilise for cache placement if viable locations can be found.
 
[Balayang -Geoff](https://www.geocaching.com/email/?guid=35e8567e-6d62-483c-9e3d-c8ec0ffd25bd)
Volunteer Community Reviewer 
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1279140438"><groundspeak:date>2025-01-30T13:46:14</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21905715">Balayang</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">### Cache Maintenance Visit Required please.###
This geocache has been brought to my attention as needing an Owner Maintenance visit, as the logs indicate that it is most likely missing, or else some other problem exists with the cache. See the [GCHQ Health Score](https://www.geocaching.com/help/index.php?pg=kb.chapter&amp;id=38&amp;pgid=713) process.
It certainly needs to be checked by the Cache Owner. 

The cache owner needs to:

* Take action to restore the cache or address issues such as correcting the D/T rating, or the posted coordinates.
* Re-enable the cache by posting an Enable log
* Post an Owner Maintenance log to advise what has been done and to clear any Needs Maintenance attribute that is present. 

Otherwise :
* Post a Note Log to request more time if necessary or provide other information.
   **Do not use an Owner Maintenance log for this. That is for use only **when you actually do something to repair the cache**. 

Alternatively:

* Archive the cache and remove any remaining geo-litter from the site.

In the meantime, I've temporarily disabled the cache page to await owner action by daysix and to take it off the playing board to prevent further inconvenience to our Geocaching Community.

[Please see the maintenance section of the Geocache Hiding Guidelines.](https://www.geocaching.com/play/guidelines?expand=1#cachemaintenance)

**I will check back in 30 days** to see that action has been taken by the CO.
If nothing has happened, I will conclude that the cache has been abandoned, and, unfortunately, I will need to Archive this cache. 
*Caches archived because of lack of maintenance/abandonment will not be unarchived.*

The Geocaching Community needs to have a degree of certainty that a cache is in good condition and waiting to be found, and the CO has a responsibility to maintain their caches.

Please see  [my profile page](https://www.geocaching.com/p/default.aspx?u=Balayang) for additional information.
Thank you
Balayang -Geoff
Community Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1277287345"><groundspeak:date>2025-01-12T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="488247">tronador</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nope.  Nada. The old settlement around the station is really interesting with its history boards. Amazing how quickly nature reclaims everything.
I couldn't find the cache anywhere unless it's rolled out of its hidey hole and is now buried beneath so much new growth. You'd need a brush cutter to clear all that. As mentioned this needs some TLC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1274333521"><groundspeak:date>2024-12-24T14:50:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="35017487">Zumbaio</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This geocacher reported that the cache might be missing.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1274333520"><groundspeak:date>2024-12-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="35017487">Zumbaio</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Did not find it. 
Came there with our local guide, and even with his help, we could not find it. It might need an update or maintenance.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-21.2122" lon="-159.790717"><time>2009-02-10T00:00:00</time><name>GC1NEQ4</name><desc>Rarotonga Cook Islands - Canuck Cache by dmcl</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1NEQ4</url><urlname>Rarotonga Cook Islands - Canuck Cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1152183" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Rarotonga Cook Islands - Canuck Cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>dmcl</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="921360">dmcl</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="33" inc="1">Motorcycles</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Cook Islands</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;h2&gt;Rarotonga - Cook Islands - Canuck Cache&lt;/h2&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;h3&gt;Getting there:&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://wikitravel.org/en/Rarotonga"&gt;Rarotonga&lt;/a&gt; is the main island in the Cook Islands. All visitors will enter the country here, unless you arrive by boat. We have visited these islands several times over the years and keep returning because of the people and climate. The island is an outdoor tropical greenhouse filled with beautiful flowers and the people have an extremely easy going, relaxed lifestyle. The Cook Islands are a wonderful getaway from the fast paced, hectic lifestyle found in so many other countries.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;About the cache:&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is easy to get to on Uruau Drive. You can walk or drive right to GZ. I always rent a scooter when I visit Rarotonga, to give me the flexibility for travel around the small island. The only drawback with the scooter is that you are limited to a maximum of 2 passengers and it does rain in Rarotonga. The cache is hidden along the road which leads to the cross island trek - but you do not need to hike to get to the cache. If you do the trek, you can find the cache along the way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;March 2018 Update Note:&lt;/b&gt;Someone has done some earthwork and pushed dirt into the area used to access the cache. It is now more of a challenge but still accessible - best to have decent shoes on.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Cross island trek:&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Start waypoint north end: S21 12.348 W159 47.105&lt;br /&gt;
End waypoint south end: S21 15.786 W159 47.729&lt;br /&gt;
Total distance with side branch to the Needle: about 9 km.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is hidden on Uruau Drive, which is the first part of the cross island trek for those hiking from north to south (which is the recommended direction). The trek is a fairly rigorous, steep walk which can be done independently or with the service of a local guide. It takes about 3.5 to 4 hours to complete. Most hikers catch a bus to the harbor and get out at the intersection of the main road and Uruau Drive. Just tell the bus driver you want to do the cross island trek and he will drop you off at the right spot. I set a waypoint at the north end of the trek (See above), which marks the beginning of the hike.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You begin the hike on a paved road, which heads inland and climbs slowly up a narrow valley. You will cross over the inland road and soon arrive at the cache, which is exactly 1km from the start of the trek. The lower part of the valley is farmed and makes for a beautiful walk. Along the way you will pass: the power station for the island, small farms with taro patches and grazing goats and pigs. The paved road ends at a bed and breakfast near a small parking lot.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Just read the signs and the trail is obvious. Here, the paved road turns into a narrow dirt road that winds slowly upward through the jungle and ends in an open area near the public water intake on the Avatiu Stream . At the end of the open area you will get to the trail which follows the Avatiu Stream for a short distance. The trail then crosses the stream and you will come to a huge boulder. Stay just to the right of the boulder and the path begins a sharp ascent up a 'staircase' of tree roots. As you climb you are surrounded by dense jungle, with the odd vantage point showing views back to the harbor and forward to the rocky needle at the top of the climb.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As you approach the rocky pinnacle called Te Rua Manga or "The Needle", you will reach a fork in the trail at S21 14.308 W159 47.280. Going to the right will take you on a short 10 min climb up to the Needle at 413m and S21 14.344 W159 47.327. The trail ends here and there are great vistas to the north and south sides of the island. It is well worth the time to go up to Te Rua Manga.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When you head down and return to the main trail, follow the other fork - which will take you down to the south side of the island along Papua Stream. Along the way you will reach another fork in the trail. The left branch follows the traditional route and is the easier hike. If you stay to the right following the white power casing pipe, you will end up walking along a very steep-sided ridge that ends with an extremely treacherous, loose rock slope, that drops down to Papua Stream. I would definitely recommend that you follow the traditional route, unless you are an experienced hiker wearing good hiking boots.This was the third time I have done the cross island trek, and this was the only time I took a wrong turn and ended up going down to Papua Sream on my 'butt'.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The trail along Papua Stream parallels the stream and crosses it in several places. The ferns are gigantic and tower over your head. In some sections the trail is hard to follow, so take your time and watch for signs of foot traffic. The difficult section of the hike ends at Wigmore Waterfall at S21 15.228 W159 47.255. This is a perfect spot to rest and take a dip in the pool to refresh the body and soothe the feet - which are likely to need it by this point. The trail from Wigmore's Waterfall to the end on the south side is on a good road that runs through farmland of banana, papaya and vegetables. Near the end you will see the abandoned Sheraton/Hilton complex which has been left unfinished for many years. As soon as you reach the main road you have completed toe trek. Congratulations!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;PLEASE HELP:&lt;/b&gt; My long time , local volunteer, maintenance person has left the island. Until I can return and find another helper, I can only rely on your support with keeping this cache in good order. Given the extreme distance from my Canadian home, I would ask any fellow geocachers help me maintain the hide for all of those who may follow. If it appears to be in need of any maintenance - could you please fix it as best you can. I believe it may need another log book. Thank you, for your support.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Update:&lt;/b&gt; There has been recent earthworks that make the last few meters to the cache more difficult. What was once easy is now a scramble. Flip flops not recommended.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Underfoot then overhead</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364762039"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="521242">bushbabe</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Oh dear - I was sure I was in exactly the right spot as the app had me at 1m! When I checked the hint and went under and found a rock in what I was SURE should've been the right spot and a bit of trash below that looked like it could've been a cache container, I assumed it was missing. It was the only feasible spot within 5m of the GZ so.... since I happened to have an appropriate container with me, I set up a replacement... My offline data list being several weeks old, I didn't see the last log til now! Oops! I thought another Canuck replacing the Canuck cache was too appropriate! I will try to get back there to remove it before departure, but not sure it'll be possible. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363821746"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="658035">capperz</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Last cache of the day snd was getting slippery in my jandals!
Tried the first under but nothing found initially so I tried the next gap. Nothing found there so retraced my steps and headed down, then to up the far side to the host. Soon spotted the cache and added my name.

First full day on the island after arriving yesterday. An overcast morning soon morphed into a rainy rest of the day meaning some time was available for a modest exploration. 
I enjoyed visiting a couple of Earthcaches, and a handful of trad caches. Another interesting resting place to visit, poles apart from my recent Fiji experience.
Thanks to all COs for their hides and Vince is for sites and sights.
Kia Ora from NZ</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1353997963"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-07T14:16:23</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6653370">RDip</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">An older cache but with fewer problems than some other Cook Island caches. I had to go further inside than I hoped. TftC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1353997994"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-07T09:56:13</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6653370">RDip</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Despite is age, this was one of the Cook Islands caches that was in place and the hint was still current. Still, I had to go in further and muddier than I hoped. TftC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1348711453"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-12T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6921477">lolar</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Great to find the oldest cache of the Cook Islands! TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="9.992983" lon="-83.0246"><time>2002-06-14T00:00:00</time><name>GC6CCA</name><desc>Christopher Columbus's 4th and Final Voyage by -Team Family Affair</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC6CCA</url><urlname>Christopher Columbus's 4th and Final Voyage</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="27850" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Christopher Columbus's 4th and Final Voyage</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>-Team Family Affair</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="22241">Team Family Affair</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Costa Rica</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p class="MsoNormal" style="mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;"&gt;This is the 25&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; geocache from Team Family Affair. We created this cache while on a 12 day Caribbean cruise. This virtual cache is located at Parque Vargas (Vargas Park) in the port town Puerto Limon, Costa Rica. The park is located right along the seawall, just a 5-minute walk from the pier. The park is filled with monuments, beautiful tropical trees and lots of flowers. Don’t forget to look up, as you will be able to enjoy watching the birds and perhaps see a sloth hanging in one of the trees.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the park near the seawall is a monument to Christopher Columbus who first visited this village in June 1502. This was Columbus's forth and final voyage across the ocean to the New World 500 years ago, as Columbus and his crew were searching for the eastern coast of Asia. They had no idea how big the world really was! Unfortunately Columbus died just a few years later in 1506, never completely realizing what He and his crew had discovered.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="MsoNormal" style="mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;"&gt;To log this cache as a find you must:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Find the monument, take a selfie picture of yourself and your team with the monument in the background and post it to your “found log” on this geocache page.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li style="list-style:none;"&gt;We hope you enjoy this cache as much as we did creating it!&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;-Team Family Affair&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1362563093"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4808311">Finitus</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Heute kurz die Stadt und das Denkmal besucht. Aber irgendwie hatten wir uns hier mehr erhofft. 
TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358434803"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="194815">pinatl</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This is my first trip to Costa Rica, from Pacific coast to Caribbean coast. It's a beautiful country, with a lot of wildlife and also very friendly people.
It was an excellent trip, and I didn't want to leave the country without finding a few caches...
I attach my picture in front of the monument, as requested. TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357860563"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-28T22:17:07</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="688679">Sitarra</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Visitando Limón en un crucero.  Vine al parque antes de irme a mi excursión en este bello pueblo. TFTVC </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1356475145"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-21T14:16:07</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1894421">McDonald5</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC!  Stopped on our way off the ship.  I bet this park was beautiful when it first opened.  Lots of birds squawking in the trees!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355820538"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-18T10:51:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="48543761">benhardhasbum</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#317 (en el atlántico costarricenses 🤩)

On a trip to Puerto Viejo, after years of not visiting this province of Costa Rica.

Lo mejor de Limón es su gente !

TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="43.5787" lon="16.3507"><time>2001-10-25T00:00:00</time><name>GC2499</name><desc>Saint Ivan by Ivan Ramljak</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC2499</url><urlname>Saint Ivan</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="9369" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Saint Ivan</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Ivan Ramljak</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="26255">boar</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Croatia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Altitude is approx 630 mt. You can easily walk all the way up and down to the cache. Terrain is typically rocky as all seaside Dinaric alps are.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Surprise and funny details.
&lt;p&gt;The coordinates are originaly taken in this form&lt;br /&gt;
N 40.5787 E 016.3507&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>When you come on to the coordinates, it's not there it's 5 meters down the rocks. In the corner behind the sq ft rock plate by the east looking rock! it's 1,5 litre, white plastic container</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364836333"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="24454174">AtalanKaarlo</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Last day in Split area on this trip and I decided to go for the oldest in Croatia. It was a rocky path and sun was shining hot, but luckily there was some cooling winds from the sea. The views of course were magnificent and I found all the caches I planned to.

This was of course the main target of the day. Once I got to the chapel there was some renovation ongoing and a bunch of workers at site. I used all my croatian skills and greeted them and then went for the cache. Luckily nothing too difficult climbing required and the container was easily found. The book however is totally soaked and wet and needs desperately a new logbook. Thanks for the hike and greetings from Finland 🙂 

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363125748"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T13:44:22</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="22617132">miekes1</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Gevonden 😀</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361216746"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-15T15:48:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7394303">Xiefehl_en_Mozique</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Vanaf 7 mei reizen we door de Balkan. Deze vakantie staat in het teken van vieren, geocachen en genieten van al het moois dat de Balkan te bieden heeft.
**Dag 9:** Vandaag bleef het ondanks de slechte weersvoorspellingen droog. In de ochtend brachten we een bezoek aan Trogir en in de middag maakten we de wandeling naar de oudste geocache van Kroatië (Saint Ivan - GC2499).

Starting May 7, we will be traveling through the Balkans. This holiday is all about celebrating, geocaching, and enjoying all the beauty the Balkans have to offer.
**Day 9** Today it remained dry despite the bad weather forecasts. In the morning we visited Trogir, and in the afternoon we hiked to the oldest geocache in Croatia (Saint Ivan - GC2499).

*We really enjoyed the trail although it was not always an easy walk. We spotted 3 horses and saw a lot of butterflies and beautiful flowers. After a walk of 75 minutes we reached the place were we had to search the cache. We were excited to find it. The book is wet, so we took a picture! Thanks for keeping this oldie! FAVO!*

boar TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363303715"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6296406">shevijs</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for the cache and greetings from Latvia! Found together with UdrsLga on our 5 week Eurotrip visiting 20 countries^^

It was amazing to find this one, +FP</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358129308"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10360346">BigMcKs</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks to Ivan Ramljak for placing Saint Ivan.

The quest for today was to find Croatia's oldest, a Wherigo, a letterbox cache, and any others that were on my trail. I was delighted to be able to sign the logs of all the caches I searched for.

This involved a long hike in the beautiful hills. It was a wonderful day for hiking. Very windy on the exposed parts but lots of shelter in other parts.

Thanks to all the COs. Apologies for a generic log, but I was trying to save my battery power on the hills.   I will drop some favourite points along the way.

Favourite point. I wasn't sure what was needed from reading the hint but soon the penny dropped and I negotiated the path to the cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="23.143833" lon="-82.37935"><time>2002-05-18T00:00:00</time><name>GC5B6F</name><desc>Cuba Libre by CaveDiver</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC5B6F</url><urlname>Cuba Libre</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="23407" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cuba Libre</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>CaveDiver</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="33338">CaveDiver</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Micro</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="53" inc="1">Park and grab</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="59" inc="1">Food nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="1">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="64" inc="0">Tree climbing required</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Cuba</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Visiting Havana Cuba? Then stop by this well-known hotel and see if you can get my cache!
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Our first visit to Cuba, and we were excited to find that no one has ever placed a cache there! It was somewhat difficult to find a "traditional site" for the cache, since we were in Havana, but I hope you like the one we selected.
&lt;p&gt;The cache is a fairly straightforward one in terms of terrain... but its going to be difficult to retrieve it without being observed. I strongly suggest going shortly before nightfall - pick a time that will give you sufficient light, but (hopefully) make you just a little less visible to the tourists.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My technique was to approach the site, sit down and pretend to take a few photos of the scenery. The cache will require some slight movement of a few rocks, but nothing too onerous.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I'm going to put extremely explicit directions in the hint, in the hopes of cutting down on searching time that may expose the cache to unwanted attention. Frankly, even if it disappears after the first "find" I'll still be happy to have gotten one in Cuba!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is a large, obvious object at these coordinates:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;N 23° 08.638&lt;br /&gt;
W 082° 22.780&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I use this object as a landmark in my hint... just in case the coordinates are off (I had to do this QUICKLY you understand).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The hint will give you step-by-step instructions... you'd find it even if you didn't have a GPS with you.&lt;/p&gt;
2022 update - folks, my wife and I established this cache a long, long time ago. I'm in the US and getting to Cuba is a bit challenging these days. If anyone can maintain/update the cache I'd be very very grateful. Also, if anyone would like to post or send me photos I'd be very very happy to see them! :)
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Remember, I said this hint is extremely explicit!  The cache is located near the Hotel National - it is a very inexpensive cab ride from Old Havana.  The object referenced above is a large cannon set into the ground.  The cannon is the first one you'll come to when you visit this area.  With the mouth of the cannon at your back you will be facing the ocean.  The cache is located in front of you and to the right.  There is a long trench running along the edge of the cliff; this is a battlement designed to allow troops to move even if they were being shelled from the water.  You must be on the seaward side of this trench , but above it at ground level (don't fall off!).  Your landmark is a 'cut' in the seaward side of the trench - it looks like a little cubbyhole in the trench wall.  On top of the trench (at ground level) there is a small stone wall in front of the trench 'cubbyhole'.  If you sit on that little wall with your back to the hotel and your front to the ocean, the cache will be on your left hand side, literally within reach.  Look down into the pile of rocks.

Use your best judgement, of course, but if you think you've been busted feel free to take the cache with you.  It won't be the end of the world!</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1343160499"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6493866">resqcat</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Visiting from Canada! TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1342616419"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-22T05:00:32</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="48283392">Distrekzy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Lo estuvimos buscando como por 40 mins hasta que nos dimos cuenta de que había una imagen con una flecha que literalmente señalaba el lugar jajaja</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1342151897"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-17T22:15:45</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="53606085">juliasmelo</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Still there! Tftc!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1341779121"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-09T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="919700">muhujan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found with Janne, Triin and Mai. Greetings from Estonia!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1325291437"><groundspeak:date>2025-09-20T16:27:59</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="51591924">TheFerners</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">They renovated that area, I guess the cache is gone.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="12.091717" lon="-68.87765"><time>2004-10-11T00:00:00</time><name>GCKT6P</name><desc>Pittig Ding by Guus Geluk</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCKT6P</url><urlname>Pittig Ding</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="179142" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Pittig Ding</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Guus Geluk</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="191161">Guus Geluk</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Curaçao</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Nice walk through an old plantation or over an old saltpond</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Park you car at either location 12°05.833N 68°52.552W (just past
Caribbean Cargo to the south-west) or at 12°04.909N 68°52.396W (Jan
Thiel Area) and walk to the cache. You can follow the paths untill
you are appr. 150m from the cache. 
&lt;p&gt;The cache now contains:&lt;br /&gt;
Golfball&lt;br /&gt;
Kids Toyball&lt;br /&gt;
Noseflute&lt;br /&gt;
Pen&lt;br /&gt;
Memo Recorder&lt;br /&gt;
Travelbug BOB.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="1"&gt;Small note on cache maintenance: We live in
Curacao and walk almost every 2 weeks in the area where we posted
this cache, so maintenance is no problem at all for us.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>You will find the cache on the dike next to the saltpond. It is under a green tree. You will need to be at the right spot to be able to find it as the cache is hidden under leaves. If you are more that 4 meters away you will not be able to find it. Stand besides the dike on the saltpond side and you will be able to reach under the tree to get it.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1358440623"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-01T22:42:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="51540838">ElineTeddy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Bedankt voor de cach 😀</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358440557"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="51487082">Jootje365</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Deze vakantie brengen we door op het zonnige Curaçao ☀️. Wat een heerlijk eiland! Vandaag willen de kids graag de zonsondergang boven de zoutvlaktes bewonderen, dus we maken aan het einde van de middag een leuke wandeling 👟 naar de spierwitte zoutvlaktes. En zeker bij zonsondergang stellen ze niet teleur, het levert mooie fotos op 📷!  Onderweg passeren we ook deze cache, dus natuurlijk ga ik samen met ElineTeddy 🐻 daar even naar op zoek 🔎. De cache is snel gevonden en we hebben onze naam op het logrolletje genoteerd 📝. Thanks for the cache 😀!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357384035"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-26T10:14:15</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="51607254">deSantpoorters</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Tftc... We hebben een heerlijke wandelingen zi rond de zoutpannen </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354355319"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-10T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5105270">Zascandiles</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">El primer caché de Curaçao es nuestro primer objetivo en la isla. Tras alquilar un vehículo, nos dirigimos al parquin indicado en un caché cercano. Avanzamos por un bosque que bien podría ser mediterráneo hasta la Zona Cero,  donde localizamos el caché sin problemas. 

Punto favorito 

Muchas gracias Guus Geluk por el caché y por mostrarnos este lugar.

Puedes seguir nuestras aventuras en Instagram: @geozascandiles

https://www.instagram.com/geozascandiles?igsh=dzlxemZ1ZDZhN2d0</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355056419"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-07T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1444973">nikonman0521</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">8:36 am. - Nice find while on a stop over from the Cruise ship Regal Princess.  We had a vehicle all day and this was one we found.  The salt pond appeared dried up but it was a nice hike to the cache.  SL TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="34.8867" lon="32.7433"><time>2002-04-01T00:00:00</time><name>GC47F2</name><desc>Cyprus 1 - Lake View by The Hornet</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC47F2</url><urlname>Cyprus 1 - Lake View</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="18418" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cyprus 1 - Lake View</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>The Hornet</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="372325">FelixDilbert</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Cyprus</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>A virtual cache accessible by car although a 4WD would be better.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This is one of four virtual caches we noted in our recent visit to Cyprus. They all have something in common, once you have found them all and have worked out the common factor e-mail me and I'll send you a star!
&lt;P&gt;
You can drive most of the way to this one up a mountain road (be prepared for a drive through a river) followed by a short walk. The view is magnificent. You will pass a well known tourist spot, Kelefos Bridge, on the way. 
&lt;P&gt;
The cache is a man made object and stands on a headland a short walk from the road.
&lt;P&gt;
To verify your find e-mail me the number on the cache.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The cache is a cairn overlooking the Danzos Dam near Kelefos Bridge.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1362158701"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10102634">PaLaRunCa</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Cyprus' first (according to the alphabetical gc code)!!! 🇨🇾 One of the 4 oldest on the island for sure anyway! 

This one makes Cyprus our 56th 'oldest gc' country!! 🌍

As with so many oldies, this virtual brought me to a wonderful place. Lovely walk over the gorgeous old bridge and such a nice view on this hidden valley!

Also the common factor between the 4 first virtuals became clear... :)
Favo+!!! Of course. ❤️🇨🇾❤️

On this very spot, I got the first picture from something happening at home, just nice to remember and link this to geocache location. And of, course also still enjoying the day after... 💙🖤🇧🇾 What an evening it was!

-------

A week off work, and because it’s always fun to colour in another country on the map, I decided to head to Cyprus for a three-day short trip. 🇨🇾

Paphos became my base for exploring the island’s three different regions: mainly the Greek part, but also the Turkish side with a short “border” crossing in the capital city of Nicosia, as well as the British territory around Akrotiri.

As usual, the oldest cache in the country was the main goal of my trip, but in Cyprus that actually meant four different hides sharing the exact same placement date. I managed to visit and complete all four oldest caches on the very same day, literally geocaching from sunrise to sunset. The final one brought me to a beach location where I arrived only two minutes before sunset, just in time to enjoy a truly stunning view over the sea. Now that’s what I call perfect timing. 😄

Of course I couldn’t resist picking up a few challenges and extremities along the way, as well as all possible icons. Besides the oldest caches, I was also happy to track down several other oldies scattered across the island. The journey also brought me to Mount Olimbos, the highest point of the island, located in the stunning Troodos Mountains, where the panoramic views were simply phenomenal.

I walked the beautiful Persephone Trail in the Troodos Mountains, explored part of the Aphrodite &amp; Adonis Trail, and even visited the legendary birthplace of Aphrodite according to Greek mythology. It was quite special to encounter these famous Greek gods and legends once again in the very landscapes where their stories were born.

Along the way, I discovered charming local villages, beautiful Byzantine churches, impressive Orthodox monasteries, and even some picturesque old Venetian bridges hidden in the mountains. One of the Byzantine churches dated all the way back to 1178 and still contained its original frescoes and painted depictions of holy figures, which was absolutely remarkable to see. I also explored an abandoned hospital somewhere along the route. I simply love discovering lost places like that. Cyprus constantly surprised me with the diversity of landscapes and history packed into such a relatively small island.

The island’s wildlife also added plenty of memorable wildlife encounters to the adventure: colourful hoopoes, a black whip snake crossing the trail, countless lizards both small and large, including the impressive Cypriot agama, just to name a few.

Mountains, nature, rugged coastlines, steep cliffs, ancient ruins, a fascinating history, and the world’s only still-divided capital city… Cyprus truly has so much to offer. From a geocaching perspective as well, this trip lacked absolutely nothing! I even managed to score an FTF here!! The many kilometres on foot also turned out to be perfect preparation for an even bigger mountain adventure still waiting somewhere on the horizon. 😉

Thank you, Cyprus, for letting me discover your beauty and diversity. And of course, a big thank you to all the COs for guiding me to wonderful places and providing so much geocaching fun along the way! It was quite a short trip, but I definitely made the most of every single moment.

With this adventure, Cyprus proudly became: 
• my 83rd geocaching country 🌍
• the 56th country where I found the oldest cache
• the 40th country where I completed a challenge cache
• the 27th country where I managed to score an FTF

Ευχαριστώ όλους τους κατόχους της cache που με καθοδηγούν σε υπέροχα μέρη και μου προσφέρουν τόση διασκέδαση geocaching στην πορεία!

Tftc The Hornet!

Discovering our world one box at a time! 🌍 #36163

Rating when found: D1.0/T2.0

Feel free to discover the trackable on our gc profile! 🐒🦍</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360561669"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-09T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1282916">cdrw</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Another return after many years, the plan was simple, but busy and it worked out great. We managed to visit nature and its wonderful corners, we saw a inland canyon, amazing cliffs and caves by the sea. We visited the highest local hills again, enjoyed swimming on several beaches and tasted local specialties. The weather cooperated, we walked a lot of steps, found a few caches along and we still have a lot left to see for next time. Thank you. 😉

TFTV!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358385436"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="813667">pudupudu.net</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for full moon cache. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357665617"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3713037">geosackboy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Wir machen gerade Urlaub auf der schönen Insel Zypern. Das Wetter der letzten Wochen lässt die Insel in saftigen Grün erscheinen. Das ist wunderschön und ganz anders als beim letzten Besuch im August.
In dieser Jahreszeit macht auch das Erkunden der Strände und Berge mehr Freude. Die Temperaturen sind genau richtig, um aktiven Urlaub zu machen.
Hier kamen wir auch vorbei und haben den schönen Ort genossen.

The reply has been sent.

Vielen Dank für den schönen Cache sagt geosackboy</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357032969"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-25T16:16:46</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="46387787">denali3108</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Done😀</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="49.587183" lon="18.119717"><time>2001-06-01T00:00:00</time><name>GCE50</name><desc>Tex-Czech by Kenneth, McKena and Ethan</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCE50</url><urlname>Tex-Czech</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3664" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Tex-Czech</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Kenneth, McKena and Ethan</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="3380187">schvabM</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Czechia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Moravskoslezský kraj</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Look in the park.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The cache is located in the National Park in Stramberk.  Take the main trail about half way up to the caves and then you will need to take a side trail.  Half way up this trail there is a large tree on your left with an "X" marked on the back.  Go left at the tree about 20 yards and you will see a couple of large rocks with trees above them.  The cache is placed below the left side of the rock.  We forgot to place the instructions in the cache so we would appreciate it if the first person to locate the cache would add an instruction sheet in both English and Czech.  Good Luck.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364946809"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="31211576">Sydd84</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Během eventu k 25. výročí založení keše jsem se stavil vypustit do světa nový TB a přidal jednoho krtka. Žádný jiný TB v keši nebyl. Krabička i logbook jsou v pořádku.

# protahuji šest osobních geocestovatelů🏷</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364580952"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T14:33:24</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="55231813">Smoulinka111</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Díky za kešku✌️</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364580876"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T14:32:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="30917721">GeoPat3</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">díky , nalezeno 🤌</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364903323"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="28308696">Pajda</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Dzięki dla właściciela 👌

Coroczna samochodowo-rowerowa eskapada turystyczna, czyli tygodniowy zlot kolarski. W tym roku Ustroń 😀 Według listy  uczestników ponad 500 rowerów 🚴‍♂️🚴‍♂️🚴‍♂️🚴‍♂️🚴‍♂️ Jak dla mnie to również zawsze okazja do mniejszego lub większego skrytkobrania 🙃 Nowe miejsca, nowe powiaty, kolejna porcja frajdy 😁 Drugi dzień, czyli niedziela. Prognoza pogody wyglądała bardzo obiecująco, więc postanowiłem pojechać samotnie do Czech 🚙 Moim pierwszym celem była Ostrava. Oczywiście zabrałem ze sobą rower i po mieście przemieszczałem się wyłącznie na dwóch kołach 🚴‍♂️ Niespiesznie kręciłem sobie przeplatając fizyczne skrytki z labami. Dużo słońca i minimalny niedzielny ruch sprzyjały spokojnemu zwiedzaniu miasta 👌 Spędziłem tu wiele fajnych godzin i bardzo mi się podobało 🙂 Na deser zostawiłem sobie prawdziwą perłę, ponieważ czekał na mnie malowniczy Stramberk i najstarszy kesz w Czechach 🔥 Tutaj zaliczyłem wspaniały spacer 😊 Miejsce zdecydowanie godne polecenia 👌 W międzyczasie stawałem też w kilku ciekawych miejscowościach jak Staříč, Příbor czy Kopřivnice, gdzie również można było zobaczyć coś interesującego i znaleźć świetne skrytki 🙂 Oczywiście to wszystko to tylko malutki ułamek tego co jest tu do zobaczenia, ale cieszę się i z tego, bo to był na pewno udany dzień, który będę wspominał bardzo miło 😀
FAV 😀</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364767547"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2075671">sedakh</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Dlouho předlouho unikala mrška.. Tímto směrem z Brna moc často nejezdíme a tak to trvalo nějakých 15 let, co ji mám v hledáčku, než došlo na odlov. Přes víkend jsme s Kristalkas byli u Jablunkova a tak se vyloženě nabízelo si na zpáteční cestě udělal malou zajížďku. Hlavní důvod byla samozřejmě tato cache, ale velmi příjemně překvapila i lokalita. Byl jsem v Šipce a na Kotouči poprvé a je tady moc krásně.

Co se týče krabičky samotné je v pořádku a hezky schovaná. Na první pohled jsem se nechal nachytat, myslel jsem že tam není i s ohledem na historický listing..ale kristalkas hned hlasí, že tam je..[:D]

Takže díky moc za tuto legendu, za její udržování a přeju jí dalších 25 let života. [8D]</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-10.616583" lon="26.310083"><time>2012-07-22T00:00:00</time><name>GC3RRMY</name><desc>Fun in Fungurume by Afrikaaner Bob</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC3RRMY</url><urlname>Fun in Fungurume</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3098140" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Fun in Fungurume</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Afrikaaner Bob</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="6194841">Afrikaaner Bob</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Micro</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="53" inc="1">Park and grab</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Democratic Republic of the Congo</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This is a little micro-sized geocache placed in Fungurume, DRC.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Fungurume is one of the many copper towns located in the Africa Copper Belt extending from Lubumbashi to Kolwezi along the N39.  Take a moment to marvel at the green-rock mountains that are around the valley full of malachite. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The geocache container is a small metal tin magnetically stuck on a bank marquee.  This is a high-traffic area (cars, lorries, and people) so be discrete.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Happy Hunting!
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1133933483"><groundspeak:date>2022-10-26T00:37:54</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6194841">Afrikaaner Bob</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Die geocache word vermis en is sedert 2017. Alle vondse sedertdien is leuens.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1132440615"><groundspeak:date>2022-10-18T01:20:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="32302318">cassandrak724</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1129873365"><groundspeak:date>2022-10-05T18:44:42</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="43297537">Eetupro1234719</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Ewewewew</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1118504805"><groundspeak:date>2022-08-14T20:56:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="42717080">Thered2317</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Bello</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1116758228"><groundspeak:date>2022-08-08T02:35:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="42530888">jayke7575</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="55.754067" lon="12.442567"><time>2000-09-30T00:00:00</time><name>GC6A</name><desc>Kippers in the Jungle (Denmark's first) by Klaus Alexander Seistrup adopted by Lysthoej</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC6A</url><urlname>Kippers in the Jungle (Denmark's first)</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="106" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Kippers in the Jungle (Denmark's first)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Klaus Alexander Seistrup adopted by Lysthoej</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1218236">lysthoej</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="55" inc="1">Short hike (&lt;1 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Denmark</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Region Hovedstaden</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Location: Smørmosen, Herlev, Copenhagen, Denmark
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;***** Opdatering 1 august 2009 ******&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;"Cachen er overdraget til Team Lysthoej, da Klaus ikke længere havde mulighed for at vedligeholde cachen.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Vi synes det er vigtigt at Danmarks første cache består i mange år frem i tiden og vil gøre vores bedste for at vedligeholde den. Så vidt det er muligt er der ikke ændret noget på den orginale tekst eller den måde som cachen er beskrevet på denne side.&lt;br /&gt;
Denne cache er udlagt som nr. 87 i hele verden.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;God fornøjelse med at finde Danmarks første cache."&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;u&gt;&lt;b&gt;Orginal tekst:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I received my Garmin eTrex a couple of days ago. Today was sunny and very warm for the season,&lt;br /&gt;
so I decided this was a fine day to create the first geocache in Denmark. :-)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The stash is located under the root of a fallen tree in Smørmosen in the outskirts of Copenhagen. This is an easy 2, but you will have to get down on your knees to actually see the stash which is a semi-transparent plastic box with a blue lid and the words "GPS Stash" written on all sides, holding (in addition to the log book and a Biro):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A tin of kippers (best before New Year 2004)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Red diode lights for your bicycle (or if you're jogging). Batteries and an arm strap included.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;An "Impossible Puzzle" from Binary Arts.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The canopy was pretty dense and the best accuracy I could obtain was 12 metres, I'm sorry. But I made quite a few readings and have taken the average, so you should be able to make it anyway.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I used to "play jungle" in that area when I was a kid, but I haven't seen the location for more than 25 years and I was very surprised how much it still looked the same even today. The noise from the nearby highway has increased by several orders of magnitude, though.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Enjoy!&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>by tree</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364970788"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T15:36:41</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="32173258">Mumla25</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found the first cache stil alive.
Thank you for placing the cache. 
Greetings from Holland
2x TB out. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364956410"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T13:41:04</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="19448223">Leixoni</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On a road trip from 🇫🇮 to 🇸🇪 🇩🇰 🇩🇪 🇳🇱 🇧🇪 🇱🇺
Seeing history, scenery and meeting cool people, and of course caching too. Had quite a few mosquitoes bothering me at this historical cache, but the weather and envuronment were pleasant. Thank you for the cache and greetings from Finland!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364996223"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1276645">zoekbaars</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We are very pleased to find this cache and to be able to log this old one. Of course we leave our favorit-point behind. Og derfor vil vi også gerne sige: Mange tak og på gensyn næste gang</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1365033069"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18188074">stiertje70</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Vandaag zijn we toch in de buurt dus waarom ook niet de oudste cache van Denemarken doen.
Hij wordt in goede staat gevonden al begin het logboek al aardig vol te raken.
Bedankt voor de cache en het instant houden van dit oldje.
Bedankt voor de cache. (3x TB - IN}</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364898133"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="24662188">Quickelinchen</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Für unseren Sommerurlaub 2026 ist eine kleine Rundreise durch Deutschland, Dänemark und Schweden geplant.
Neben dem obligatorischen Sightseeing stehen einige ausgewählte Caches auf der To-Do-Liste, neue Landkreise wollen erkundet und weitere Caches für die Statistik besucht werden. 
Hierfür wurde im Vorfeld ordentlich gerätselt, Routen geplant und Tools eingepackt. 


Nach Hannover, Hamburg und Fehmarn ging es weiter über die Fähre Puttgarden - Rødby bis nach Kopenhagen. 

"Kippers in the Jungle" stand diesmal auch auf unserer To-Do-Liste, konnte von uns gefunden und das Logbuch signiert werden.
Vielen Dank für diesen Oldie!

Vielen Dank fürs Herlocken, Legen und Pflegen!


*Randnotiz: Bei Platzmangel, auf großen Runden, auf schlecht beschreibbarem Material, wenn der Stempel zu groß oder unpassend ist, oder auch einfach nur mal so tragen wir uns gerne mit unserem Kürzel "Quix ツ" ein.
Nicht immer stehen wir chronologisch an letzter Stelle im Logbuch, wir nutzen auch Lücken und andere freie Stellen.*</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="11.60375" lon="42.413967"><time>2005-06-14T00:00:00</time><name>GCPAFJ</name><desc>Lac Assal, Really Deep by Aradilla</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCPAFJ</url><urlname>Lac Assal, Really Deep</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Earthcache</type><groundspeak:cache id="254375" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Lac Assal, Really Deep</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Aradilla</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="169564">Aradilla</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Earthcache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="1">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="36" inc="0">Snowmobiles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="23" inc="1">Dangerous area</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Djibouti</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This is the first Earthcache in Africa! Additionally it is currently the oldest active Earthcache in Africa! Besides being one of the really hot places in the World you should approach this location with a 4 WD. The "roads" of typical African condition. But what makes this point really outstanding is the elevation!
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The Lac Assal in Djibouti is located at the deepest point in Africa with an altitude of approximately 155 m below sea level. &lt;br /&gt; That makes this point the second deepest point on the surface of the Earth after the Dead Sea.&lt;br /&gt; The Lac Assal is the lake with the highest salinity worldwide. It has a salt concentration of approx. 34.8 % which is 4 percent higher as the salt content of the Dead Sea.&lt;br /&gt; The lake receives it water from subterranean springs which are fed from water of the Indian Ocean. Furthermore the salt content is increased by the high evaporation rate at this place (lots of sunshine and hot climate). The lake is situated within the African rift valley where the initial stage of the separation of continents can be observed. It is like a rubber band that you tear apart at its ends it will become thinner in the middle and at one time it will break. Here at the Assal Lake the stage where the middle becomes thinner is present and being thin the hot molten rocks situated below the earth’s crust have it much easier to get to the surface what causes the volcanic activity in this region.&lt;br /&gt; Here comes a more scientific explanation: The East African rift system is a divergent plate boundary created through the rifting and separation of the African and Arabian tectonic plates that began around 35 million years ago in the north, and by the ongoing separation of East Africa from the rest of Africa along the East African Rift, which began about 15 million years ago. It has reached locally the stage of continental rift, with attenuation (thinning) of the continental crust and lithospheric mantle. High surface heat flow (proportional to the temperature gradient) and volcanism testify that the asthenosphere is rising underneath the lithosphere.&lt;br /&gt; In the near future (well by means of geologist! You do not have to hurry as you have at least a couple of million years time for your visit!) the mountains separating the Indian ocean and the Assal Lake will be torn apart and the whole area flooded.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; 
&lt;b&gt;Your task: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Once you visit this place you have to perform a little experiment that need a bit of preparation from your side. You have to collect a water sample (use a 1 liter bottle of any kind / if you use a different volume correct your weight measurement so that it is equal to what 1 l would have had) and take it to the place you are living (or the hotel). There let the water evaporate and state the weight of the salt you received from your water sample in your email to me. Of course you should provide photographic evidence for your experiment! Even so it seems obvious, transfer the water from the bottle into a pot of some sort to evaporate the water otherwise it will take ages (alternatively you can heat the water as well). Furthermore as a proof of your visit to the Assal lake please post a photographic evidence that shows you, your GPS with the coordinates and your height readable and the bottle of water you collected for your experiment. Logs with different approaches or not complete photographic evidence might be approved as long as they were discussed with me via email. But generally speaking: No experiment, no email, no photo (of you at Lac Assal and of the result of the experiment!) = No Log! You HAVE to do ALL Three! You do not have to go exactly to this position everything close to the lake and with a negative altitude will be fine! Faked Photographs will lead to the deletion of your Log! You can provide the answers (and log the cache) either in english or german, (that might help some tourists). PLEASE do sent your email address along so that I can answer! If you do NOT send your EMAIL along I will NOT ANSWER! Free counters
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Please tick the box send my email address as otherwise I will not answer.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1340011904"><groundspeak:date>2025-12-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6275751">Jidec</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Un belle découverte que le lac Assal et ses sources chaudes. Nous avons apprécié notre visite, le mois de décembre permettant d'échapper aux  fortes chaleurs, mais pas à la pluie qui nous surprendra sur la route du retour.
L'échantillon est collecté sur place puis ramené en France pour la suite de l'expérience. 
Merci Aradilla pour cette Earthcache originale. 
Son altitude et son ancienneté augmente également son intérêt pour les chasseurs de challenges.
Un PF
 </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1335585691"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-11T18:07:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8506681">Riba14</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">😎😎

On today’s trip we stopped at the places previously agreed with the guide.

All perfect places for a geocache. 

Thank you for bringing me here

Says Riba14 🙋‍♀️
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1334920693"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-11T12:07:03</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6535652">SteLaSyXL</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Wie wir dieses Experiment lieben 🥰 In unserem Vorübergehenden zuhause auf St. Helena haben wir es durchgeführt und die Antwort an den Owner gesendet.
***
How we love this experiment 🥰 In our temporary home on St. Helena we carried it out and sent the answer to the owner.
***
Hier waren wir bei Lac Assal, Really Deep mit der grösse Andere von Aradilla den wir suchen und finden durften.

Vielen Dank und 
Grüsse vom Baselbieter🇨🇭 aus dem Fricktal
Sagt SteLaSyXL

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1356871300"><groundspeak:date>2025-10-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="419386">Rost-Nielsen</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">While on a business-trip from Mogadishu, Somalia to Djibouti my colleagues and I decided to visit the famous Lac Assal on a half days cartrip from tha main city.
Upon arrival at the lake we took a good time to walk around and explore the lake as well as the surroundings. We had a very nice walk and especially the green hot springs were very beautiful to look at. The water in them were VERY hot, almost scolding!
Now when I finally had made it to Lac Assal I had to collect all the answers for this Earth Cache including a bottle of lakewater in order to conduct the described experiment.
I sent the result together with other info to CO who then replied with permission to log this very fine Earth Cache.
Thanks to CO for making this cache and thereby bringing me to this very interesting place.
TFTC Team Rost-Nielsen
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1275021127"><groundspeak:date>2024-12-28T13:20:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3149955">pingu_k</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We’ve been on a trip to Djibouti and found a guide to bring us to Lac Assal and some other places. It had been very interesting and learned a lot. I took the opportunity that we stopped here and had a bottle ready. Back in the hotel i executed the experiment and retrieved some salt. Documentation was sent to the owner and permission to log was given. 

Thanks Aradilla for leading us here, teaching new stuff and getting the opportunity to explore. TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="15.397483" lon="-61.312217"><time>2009-05-29T00:00:00</time><name>GC1T0RW</name><desc>Emerald Pool by Sorensen0</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1T0RW</url><urlname>Emerald Pool</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Earthcache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1257947" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Emerald Pool</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Sorensen0</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="402342">ZerØ</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Earthcache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Dominica</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>On the Volcanic Island of Dominica in the heart of the rain forest in Morne Trois Pitons National Park. Dominica is one of the filming sites for Pirates of the Caribbean movies and is an incredible location.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Emerald Pool is a popular tourist destination whether one travels to the island by cruise ship or otherwise. Several tours are shuttled to the site or it is easy to have a taxi take you there independently. Entrance into the park is US$5.00 and is a short hike to the falls. It is rumored that if you swim in the Emerald Pool is will take 10 years off of your life (I mean to say, it will ADD 10 years to your life haha...thanks to dcachfinder for pointing out that was worded backwards.) Dominica is an island born of volcanic origins and is shown by many different types of geologic formations all over the island and rain forest. There is a lot of flora and fauna and different species of animal life in the rain forest as well. The water of emerald pool runs through a volcanic canyon and over into a grotto. There is a cave that is behind the falls and one can walk behind the falls without getting wet if you prefer. Lava can be dynamic and can create many unusual types of formations, particularly caves.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/gs-geo-images/98a26d3d-560c-4681-b1e5-fb09548db6de.jpg" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Dominica lies at the center of the Lesser Antilles Island arc, where the islands of the Active Arc (see Lesser Antilles Arcs map on this website) are large and complex comprising many coalesced stratovolcanoes. The island has an area of 750 sq.kmWhereas all the other volcanic islands of the Lesser Antilles have only one active volcano, Dominica has nine and yet there has been no major magmatic eruption since Columbus visited the island and as a result it has today the best and most extensively preserved tropical rainforests. The youngest dated volcanic deposits on the island are associated with the Morne Patates dome on the flanks of the large active Plat Pays Volcano that comprises the southwestern end of the island. This was a Pelean eruption (similar to the eruptions of Mt. Pelee on Martinique in 1902 and 1929) and radiocarbon ages from the block and ash deposits suggest it occurred about 500 years ago. In addition there have been two steam explosions (phreatic activity) in the Valley of Desolation in 1880 and 1997. Frequent seismic swarms and vigorous and widespread geothermal activity today characterize the island. In fact it is the most worrying of all the Caribbean volcanic areas and there is a general feeling that it (like Montserrat pre-1995) is long overdue for an eruption. What is of particular concern is that the capital Roseau and most of the islands infrastructure lie on a pyroclastic flow fan derived from the Wotten Waven caldera situated on the eastern outskirts of the capital. The pyroclastic deposits of the Roseau area abound with ignimbrites (pumiceous pyroclastic flows), surge and airfall deposits with radiocaron ages ranging from 38,000 to 1000 years B.C. (from Wikipedia) There are numerous types of lava caves, the most common and most extensive being lava tubes. But not all lava caves are lava tubes. Other types of lava caves include the following classifications: * Volcanic rift or fissure caves, which form along volcanic rift zones and eruptive fissures, or in fractures associated with volcanic activity. These are tectonic in formation, caused by “stress in lava during and after solidification.” They may also be the site of fissure eruptions, and the walls covered with spatter. Notable rift caves include Crystal Ice Cave, formed in Idaho’s Great Rift (and now part of Craters of the Moon National Monument and Preserve). Caves in the Great Rift are known up to 800 feet deep. * Inflationary caves tend to be small chambers which form when lava under pressure pushes up surface rock from below and then drains back down. One surface expression of this is the tumulus, a fractured hillock of lava which is often hollow. In some cases volcanic gases may exert pressure on solid or semi-solid lava and form what is basically a bubble of thin rock. Rarely, the latter may be big enough to qualify as a cave. * Lava mold caves, which form when lava flows around trees or even large dead animals. The engulfed material eventually burns or decays away, but ends up leaving a hollow space with the original shape. Usually these are not very large but can get somewhat complex where groups of fallen logs were touching, and may then form caves that go in several directions where the resulting voids intersect. Such caves are known from Washington (USA), near Ape Cave, and from most notably from Japan in the Yoshida-tanai area. Elephant mold caves are known from the Nyiragongo volcano in Africa, and one in the shape of a Tertiary-age Rhinoceros is known from Blue Lake, Washington (USA). * Open vertical volcanic conduits are voids open to the surface which remain after magma has erupted. They tend to be narrower near the top and bell out below, requiring a roped descent for exploration. The deepest known example is Thrinukagigur in Iceland at 204m deep. * Pit craters form when magma that doesn’t quite reach the surface drains to form a void, and the ground above it slumps. These huge open-air pits with their sheer walls are analogous to some of the large shafts formed by solution, and typically require a roped descent for exploration. While most have no extension beyond the visible floor, others may have entrances into adjacent (now empty) magma chambers, such as was seen when the crater of Mauna Ulu in Hawai`i Volcanoes National Park was explored by a team of Swiss cavers. In Na One, a pit crater on Hualalai Volcano in Hawaii, a narrow opening at the bottom of an 130m-deep pit crater leads into an open vertical volcanic conduit, with a total depth of 268 m.&lt;br /&gt;
Logging Requirements:&lt;br /&gt;
1. Name what kind of cave the falls runs over.&lt;br /&gt;
2. photo of yourself at the falls to verify location.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1360770316"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-13T13:15:26</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="43612912">gadpet</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Heute einen Ausflug zum Emerald Pool gemacht. Schöner Rundgang hier. Die Frage konnte gut beantwortet werden.

TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355089081"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-13T16:41:27</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8264741">Stieb05</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Yes.... Yes.... zusammen mit Stieb01 auf AIDA-Tour. Auf dieser tollen Insel hier konnten wir auch stoppen und diesen EC besuchen. Die Antwort ist soeben per Mailraus. 
Gerne bleibt ein FP auf dieser Insel für diesen ältesten Cache zurück. 


Vielen Dank an ZerØ für den neuen Smiley auf der Karte

DFDC sagt Stieb05 

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355081753"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-13T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8297463">Stieb01</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Wow, FB bleibt hier...
Gemeinsam mit Stieb05 ging es mit der AIDA auf kleine Urlaubs- und Cachertour. 
Dabei konnte der ein oder andere interessante Cache in Dominica besucht und das Logbuch erfolgreich signiert werden. Dieser Alte Earth-Cache in super schöner und interessanter Location war auch dabei und grüßt nun als Smiley auf unserer Cacherkarte. 
Viele Grüße von Stieb01 aus RLP und unserem schönen Naheland, den besten Dank an den netten Owner fürs Legen, Hegen und Pflegen dieses Caches.

Wow, FB stays here...
Together with Stieb05, the AIDA went on a small holiday and cacher tour.
One or the other interesting cache in Dominica could be visited and the logbook successfully signed. This multi-cache in a super nice and interesting location was also there and now greets as a smiley face on our cacher map.
Many greetings from Stieb01 from RLP and our beautiful Naheland, the best thanks to the nice Owner for laying, cherishing and maintaining this cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1352402197"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-02T08:37:41</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4928724">nyboholm</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">First time at a rainforrest, the Emerald pool eas amazing.

Tftc</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1352144958"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5105270">Zascandiles</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Qué ilusión encontrar este EarthCache, además siendo nuestro primer caché en Dominica. Llegamos justo cuando estaba lloviendo, lo que hizo que el entorno se sintiera todavía más selvático y espectacular. Aun así, no dudamos en aprovechar el momento y nos bañamos en Emerald Pool, una experiencia increíble en un lugar realmente precioso.

Punto favorito 

Muchas gracias ZerØ por el caché y por mostrarnos este lugar.

Puedes seguir nuestras aventuras en Instagram: @geozascandiles

https://www.instagram.com/geozascandiles?igsh=dzlxemZ1ZDZhN2d0</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="19.7966" lon="-70.692133"><time>2003-04-21T00:00:00</time><name>GCG1CM</name><desc>A Walk in the Park by dgreno</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCG1CM</url><urlname>A Walk in the Park</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="66889" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>A Walk in the Park</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>dgreno</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="35197">dgreno</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="1">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="64" inc="0">Tree climbing required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="10" inc="0">Difficult climb</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Dominican Republic</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This virtual cache in the Dominican Republic town of Puerto Plata is associated with a famous movie.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This stop is a stop on almost any tourist agenda on the northern coast of the Dominican Republic. It's worth a half-hour of your time and the approximately $3US admission fee. Although not officially associated with a very famous movie, they do their best to give you the impression that they are! To log this cache, visit this spot and email me with the full name of this place (in English or Spanish) and the movie that comes to mind.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1362468807"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T11:25:08</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10460458">SerenitySearchers</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Here on a Princess cruise.
Here is a photo of our princess with mode of travel in background.

Thanks for the Fun and Thanks for the Cache!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362468640"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T11:24:16</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="26841591">GigglyGirly</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nice and easy found 

Thanks for the cache and for helping to make my journey fun!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362181585"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-19T14:06:03</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8449271">JaBob69</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Visiting from PA. Tftc. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358725859"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-02T17:21:51</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1099448">jjsj</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Great place!  Answers sent.  Thanks for sharing </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357611788"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4945014">E-Taler</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">From April 24th to May 3rd, 2026, I went on a cruise to the Caribbean. The trip started in Miami and went to the Dominican Republic, the British and US Virgin Islands, and finally to the Bahamas. Traditional caches, EarthCaches, virtual caches, and mystery caches were found along the way. 

TFTC says the E-Taler.


In der Zeit vom 24.04-03.05.26 ging es auf eine Kreuzfahrt in die Kabrik.Der Start war in Miami und ging in die Dom.Republik auf die Britischen u. US Jungferninseln und zum Abschluss noch auf die Bahamas. Hier konnten Tradis, EC ,virtuelle Caches und Mysteries gefunden werden .

TFTC sagt der E-Taler</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-8.520533" lon="125.608467"><time>2007-03-19T00:00:00</time><name>GC127RK</name><desc>Cristo Rei by Team Bungarra</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC127RK</url><urlname>Cristo Rei</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Multi-cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="579473" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cristo Rei</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Team Bungarra</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="243252">Team Bungarra</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Multi-cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Timor-Leste</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>* Check Travel Warning/Advisory information regarding East Timor
*</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Cristo Rei (Christ the King) is a statue at Cape Fatucama,
approximately 6 km east of Dili. At 27 metres (88.6 feet) high, it
is believed to be the second largest statue of Christ in the world,
second only to the ‘Christ the Redeemer’ statue at Rio de Janeiro
in Brazil.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
To reach the statue, visitors climb a long flight of steps. Along
the way up to the statue, you will pass 15 Stations of the Cross.
There are a number of places along the stairway where you will also
enjoy the panorama West towards Dili, or along the coast to the
East.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
When you reach the statue and have admired the view, count the
number of bent columns supporting the globe on which Jesus is
standing. Add this number to the decimal portion of your given
South coordinate in order to locate the cache.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The cache is a small plastic container hidden beneath rocks in a
sheltered location. Watch for ‘Muggles’ as the location is well
patronised.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Remember to check Travel Warning/Advisory information regarding
East Timor.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>John Nineteen gives a short version of the Passion.  For a more accurate final cache location, add the verse number that first indicates the location of the crucifixion to the decimal portion of the East coordinate.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="666545731"><groundspeak:date>2017-02-24T03:54:31</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="243252">Team Bungarra</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Finally have to archive this cache.  Unable to revisit myself and no volunteers to take it over.

The Redeemer will have to entice another follower to take up the cause!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="666546206"><groundspeak:date>2017-02-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="243252">Team Bungarra</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Cache Archived. :(</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="665435506"><groundspeak:date>2017-02-18T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3675695">Greatland Reviewer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hello:

The cache has been temporarily disabled for at least a month.  If you have plans to replace this cache in the near future please let the geocaching community know by placing a note on the cache page and perform the necessary cache maintenance. If you have decided not to replace the cache please archive the listing.   

If there is no response within thirty days, I may archive the cache to free up the space for another cacher.

Thank you.

Greatland Reviewer
Groundspeak Volunteer
My Profile: [http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=6354843d-6bec-4737-8db5-77907f57de8a](http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=6354843d-6bec-4737-8db5-77907f57de8a)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="662278311"><groundspeak:date>2017-01-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8828096">Shrëk</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Any chance that this will be back online soon?  I will be on a cruise that visits Dili in early March and would be good to be able to get this one.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="648887654"><groundspeak:date>2016-11-02T03:05:32</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="243252">Team Bungarra</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Sorry but have to disable until I can physically check the condition of the cache.

Cheers,
Bungarra</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-0.002217" lon="-78.45535"><time>2002-09-25T00:00:00</time><name>GC934A</name><desc>The Fake Equator by Steve (Licorice)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC934A</url><urlname>The Fake Equator</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="37706" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>The Fake Equator</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Steve (Licorice)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="28262">Licorice</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="1">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="26" inc="1">Public transportation nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Ecuador</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Located north of Quito, at the Mitad del Mundo (Middle of the World) monument
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;img src="http://www.geckobeach.com/GPS/licorice21.jpg" width="240" height="180" align="right" /&gt;Any visit to the capital of Ecuador would not be complete without a visit to the equator, just north of Quito. The Ecuadorian government has build a tourist monument called the "Mitad del Mundo" at the equator to commemorate the French and Spanish scientific expedition that measured the equator's location between 1736 and 1744. At this monument there is a yellow line painted on the ground to indicate the equator and one of the favourite tourist activities is to straddle the yellow line and think of yourself with one foot on each of the northern and southern hemispheres. Most people also visit the museum and leave with the satisfaction of standing on the equator.
&lt;p&gt;But wait, pull out that handy-dandy GPS unit of yours and place it on the yellow line just to verify the accuracy of the line and you'll note that your GPS is definitely NOT on the equator -- what gives? When the French-Spanish survey was completed in 1744, the place where the yellow line sits today is where the equator was, but due to annual planetary variations the equator is now located north of the yellow line.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Onto the virtual cache: To qualify a find for this cache, you'll need to do two things: First take a picture of your GPS on the yellow line with the coordinates showing or a picture of yourself holding your GPS infront of the obelisk with the yellow line clearly present and upload it with your find. Second to satisfy yourself, find the location of the REAL equator and draw your own line on the ground and either place your GPS ontop of that line or stand on the line and hold your GPS and take a picture showing 0° latitude and upload it with your find as well.&lt;br /&gt;
Bonus question: how many metres or feet is the real equator from the yellow line?&lt;br clear="all" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>To get to Mitad del Mundo you can either take a taxi from Quito (about US$10) or catch a public bus for much less and avoid paying the toll just north of Quito.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364918402"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T22:24:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="843116">jaypost</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A perfect day taking my students here. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364238741"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T15:06:05</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1185612">MI3sprouts</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">At the end of the day, we ended up coming to the very significant spot for our first cache in Ecuador. Had a great day touring around Quito.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361241852"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-15T17:29:34</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3523587">Pappies</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Enjoyed balanced the egg and enjoyed my time in Ecuador in general. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359666968"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-07T17:22:32</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3305852">Team Søskendeweekend</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We are on holiday in Ecuador. Our first time in South America and first time in Ecuador. What a fantastic place. First we visited the sun museum and afterwards Mitad del mundo. spectacular. Greetings from Denmark.

Jonathan, Christian og Else 😊 🌞 🇩🇰 

#3377</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358661082"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-02T12:47:50</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5922204">thornies</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Loved coming to the real equator today and the entertaining tour. Sadly not an egg balancing champion but learnt a lot. It’s busy today as it is a holiday weekend so many people are visiting the “fake” one. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="29.49495" lon="30.523516666666666"><time>2002-01-19T00:00:00</time><name>GC336F</name><desc>Fox 01 by atorrigi</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC336F</url><urlname>Fox 01</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="13167" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Fox 01</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>atorrigi</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="32880">atorrigi</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Egypt</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This cache is for those that roam the desert like a fox! It is in a location overlooking the northwestern shoreline of Birket Qarun. It can be reached on a typical day trip from Cairo. </groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>For the most direct access to Fox 01, enter the Fayoum area north of the lake. A 4x4 is not required to reach this cache, yet most people that travel this region do travel by 4x4, as the road is rough in some areas. It can also be accessed offtrack by 4x4 from the western edge of the Fayoum by traveling north from the village of Qarun.
&lt;P&gt;
To reach the cache location you may follow the numerous fox tracks up the escarpment. The cache is hidden in a very nice lookout location with 360 degree views of the North Fayoum area. The cache is well hidden within the rock formations near the entrance of a fox den.
&lt;P&gt;
The cache is located in a Ziploc brand Tupperware style plastic container named 'Fox 01'. 
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Elevation is important to note while searching for this cache. It is located above 61 m and is hidden in a hole covered with rocks just above the edge of an abandoned fox den.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1357645670"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-03T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18030217">JellyCZ</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">well, the childhood dreams became reality and I witnessed the ancient wonders of Egypt.
drove 4135 km in rental car, from Alexandria to Abu Simbel and back. in 10 days, with a muggle friend. 
this was one of the highlights, probably because we drove there after sunset. I really hoped we could reach the place with our 2WD rental car, and indeed it was possible, quite easily. the hill with the cache is steep but short, soon we found an empty fox den, presumably the original spot. we continued up the hill and found a shaft, it looked like a man-made one. there must be a pyramid buried here. :) next to the shaft I found the cache, a replacement from February. very cool. then we spent a few more minutes here, enjoying the serene night atmosphere.
tftc and greetings from Zlín!
+fp</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1346926004"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-01T16:39:03</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8792259">lineus</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We came here as part our Egyptian circumnavigation on the motorcycles and climbed to this rock formation with great pleasure. The view is stunning, TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1346925631"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-01T16:38:12</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54634474">sklip</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thank you. We were very interested. This is a very beautiful place.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1346714231"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="872840">superfelix</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Today we visted Fayoum during our Egypt vacation. Of course we had to stop for this geocache before driving deeper into the National Park dessert.

Wow, what a climb up to the fox dens. We are so lucky that we found the new "box" after a little searching. Coming down again to the 4x4 was also not so easy.

#20267
شكرًا</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1346379961"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="14911796">Michel19799Gaby</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Schnell und gut gefunden </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="13.92655" lon="-89.49266666666666"><time>2003-05-01T00:00:00</time><name>GCG7N5</name><desc>El Jordan by Lucrecia, Ana, Simon, Andreas</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCG7N5</url><urlname>El Jordan</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="72919" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>El Jordan</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Lucrecia, Ana, Simon, Andreas</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="102942">Polyglott</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>El Salvador</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Located on the El Jordan Finca (private but accesible), nice walk.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>On private land but owner has given permission to civilized geochachers. Find a ravine close to coordinates, reception is not 100%.  Container is large coffee-tin wrapped in black plastic bag. Contents:
Frog, Whistle, Quetzal coin, Expo 2000 pin, Matches, Corona pin, Airplane, Bullet, Bear, Rubber Ball, Koala, Cork, Spoon, Ball Bearing, Sunflower, Chopsticks, Moist Towel, Butterfly Watch, Parrot Watch, Q-Tip, Condom, Bucket, German Flag, Empty Cigaretes, Despensa Park Card, 3 The Pub Passes, Logbook, Pencil 
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Once in ravine, you will need to climb about 6-7 meters (20 feet) on the left side of the waterfall, about 15-20 meters away (45-60 feet) from it.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="762326667"><groundspeak:date>2018-04-25T08:09:03</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1778438">GeoCrater</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I am regretfully archiving this cache since there's been no response from nor action by the cache owner within the time frame requested in the last reviewer note.

GeoCrater
Geocaching.com Community Volunteer Reviewer


Lamento archivar este caché lamentablemente, ya que el propietario del caché no ha respondido ni ha actuado dentro del marco de tiempo solicitado en la última nota del revisor.

GeoCrater
Geocaching.com Community Volunteer Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="758867680"><groundspeak:date>2018-04-11T07:53:06</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1778438">GeoCrater</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">If it is not possible for the cache owner to repair / replace - this cache should be archived rather than disabled.  Should the cache not be replaced within the next two weeks, this cache may be archived by the reviewer.

GeoCrater
Volunteer Reviewer for Geocaching.com

Si no es posible que el propietario de la memoria caché lo repare / reemplace, este caché debe archivarse en lugar de deshabilitarse. Si el caché no se reemplaza dentro de las próximas dos semanas, este caché puede ser archivado por el revisor.

GeoCrater
Revisor voluntario de Geocaching.com</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="750756230"><groundspeak:date>2018-03-11T19:44:37</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="102942">Polyglott</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Lost and not possible to mantain</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="750173403"><groundspeak:date>2018-03-09T22:33:42</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1626673">Trebbi</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I found a broken box, I´m not sure if this was the rest of the Geocache?
You should check it to be sure if it is there or not.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="750172864"><groundspeak:date>2018-02-18T14:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1626673">Trebbi</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false"># 37614

During a six weeks stay in Guatelama I planed a trip to Panama.
At the end of my time here I got a rental car for 10 days and started driving to Panama. 
I had a nice time, met some other travelers and could see some nice places AND of course I could find some Geocaches.
Some strops during the trip: San Salvador, San Lorenzo, Managua, Volcan Masaya, Granada, San Jose, Buenos Aires,  Palmar Sur, Uvita, Sixaola, Puerto Limon, Santa Elena, Leon, Tegucigalpa, San Pedro Sula, Tikal, San Ignacio Belize, and finally Guatemala!
What a pitty that I could not enter Panama with this car, so I have to come back for one more trip around Panama.
I had a great time during the trip here in central America and of course in Antigua. Thanks to everyone who placed some Caches here!

Thanks to Polyglott for placing and maintaining the Cache.
Danke an Polyglott fürs Legen und Pflegen der Dose.


T rebbi
F ound
T his
C ache


Geloggt mit GSAK 8.7.0.0</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="3.757517" lon="8.7835"><time>2012-03-20T00:00:00</time><name>GC3FHKP</name><desc>El primer ecuatoguineano by CACHE ALLIANCE</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC3FHKP</url><urlname>El primer ecuatoguineano</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="2823256" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>El primer ecuatoguineano</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>CACHE ALLIANCE</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="3175685">CACHE ALLIANCE</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Equatorial Guinea</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;b&gt;&lt;big&gt;Equatorial Guineas first geocache!&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/b&gt;
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;big&gt;You are looking for a very tiny black nano cache, conveniently hidden at the Sofitel across from the old cathedral.&lt;br /&gt;
It is accessible from the street, no need to enter the hotel.&lt;br /&gt;
Be aware of muggles at the hotel and muggles at the plaza in front of the church.&lt;/big&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="1"&gt;Small note on cache maintenance: We are here frequently and regularly on business, so maintenance should not be a problem.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/center&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Below the German flag at hip height in the right corner of the black iron fence.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="913112420"><groundspeak:date>2020-03-12T18:35:13</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Due to no response from the CO after the request to maintain or replace the cache, I am archiving it to, stop it showing on the listings  and/or to create place for the geocaching community.

The [Geocache Maintenance guideline](http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) explains a CO's responsibility towards checking and maintaining the cache when problems are reported. 

Please note that if geocaches are archived by a reviewer or Geocaching HQ for lack of maintenance, they are not eligible for unarchival. This is explained in the [Help Center](http://support.groundspeak.com//index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=70)

If the CO feels that this cache has been archived in error please feel free to contact me within 30 days,  via email or message via my profile ,quoting the GC number concerned

Thank you for understanding

Knagur Green
Groundspeak Volunteer Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="902794986"><groundspeak:date>2020-01-10T19:05:46</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The cache appears to be in need of owner intervention. I'm temporarily disabling it, to give the owner an opportunity to check on the cache, and take whatever action is necessary. 

Please enable your cache by selecting enable on the right hand side of the listing , once the cache has been replaced/repaired, or checked that it is still in situ.

The [Geocache Maintenance guideline](http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) explains a CO's responsibility towards checking and maintaining the cache when problems are reported. Caches that have been archived for lack of maintenance will not be unarchived. This is explained in the [Help Center](http://support.groundspeak.com//index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=70)

**Please respond to this situation in a timely manner (i.e., within 30 days) to prevent the cache from being archived for non-responsiveness. If you plan on repairing this cache,but cannot get to it within 30 days, please log a note to the cache page (not email) to let the community know**

Knagur Green
Groundspeak Volunteer Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="902658038"><groundspeak:date>2020-01-09T12:30:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Needs Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1049026">merdian</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Dieser Geocacher hat gemeldet, dass der Geocache archiviert werden sollte. Ein Reviewer wurde benachrichtigt.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="902658037"><groundspeak:date>2020-01-09T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1049026">merdian</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The hotel is removed and there is now just only a construction site. So no cache anymore unfortunately.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="885131091"><groundspeak:date>2019-09-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3968299">Kesj-Sjeng</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Log by "Chris2009786" is a bogus log! PLEASE DELETE... This is an obvious TROLL. He logged many different geocaches all over the world in only 1 day, including my cache in Monrovia, Liberia. He was never there...</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="15.7789833333333" lon="39.7952833333333"><time>2005-11-19T00:00:00</time><name>GCRCNC</name><desc>Dur Ghella Cache by Alpenglow Expat</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCRCNC</url><urlname>Dur Ghella Cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="316059" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Dur Ghella Cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Alpenglow Expat</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="481248">Alpenglow Expat</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="4" inc="1">Boat required</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>4</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Eritrea</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Dur Ghella Island, Dahlak Archipelago, Eritrea.  First geocache in Eritrea!! You'll need a boat to get to this cache, thus the difficulty rating.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The geocache is a plastic box covered by a pile of stones beneath one of two trees that are closer to one another than most of the island's sparse trees.  The island is small enough that you can reasonably get to the geocache from any convenient landing point, but the northeast side is probably most convenient.

Cache contents:
Ceasar's Palace pen
Logbook
1 Egyptian Pound
20 Thai Baht
1 Ethiopian Birr
Pendant featuring a famous Thai Buddhist monk
American/Eritrean flags pin
2 Eritrean hair pins
1 sapphire ring (I think it's fake, but pretty)

Info about the area:  The Dahlak Archipelago is one of the untouched jewels of the Red Sea.  With practically no tourist development and indeed very little habitation or even fishing traffic, the islands in this sprawling cluster of lonely sand bars and uplifted coral beds are the archetypal desert islands.  The snorkeling is fantastic, with reefs untrodden by the tourist hordes that have trampled other tropical reefs to little more than gravel.  Some of the islands offer great diving along deep walls as well.  During Eritrea's long history of conflict, the islands have been used as bases by several powers and signs of past conflict can be seen on Dur Ghella as exploded shell casings.  The Eritrean military stills uses some of the islands as bases, others as prisons, which limits the islands travelers can get permission to visit.  A current rumor has it that the US military maintains an anti-terrorism base here, though with frosty relations between the Eritreans and the US, this seems unlikely.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1296381549"><groundspeak:date>2025-05-04T18:24:28</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="481248">Alpenglow Expat</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**Found by @after8 with photos.** It's still there! After almost 20 years! I believe this is the first legitimate find of this cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1296183904"><groundspeak:date>2025-04-29T12:34:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8847997">after8</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache was the goal of my geocaching in Eritrea. I was so eager to make it here! Now I have found 150% of the local caches. Too bad such a beautiful country has so few findings. Anyway under a scorching sun we walked here from the other (SouthEast) side of the island where we had docked. Try to come in the cooler months: I think walking 2kms in August would be tough. While I was checking the roots of the wrong twin tree, my muggle friend FOUND THE ORIGINAL (topless) TUPPERWARE! I added my new white box containing some Eritrean swags and I happily signed the new logbook protected in a waterproof vial. I covered with the original hiding stones. I am very happy for the finding which awards me a very rare (FTF) !
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1291667474"><groundspeak:date>2025-04-16T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="481248">Alpenglow Expat</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">User after8 is planning to visit the island in late April and will perform maintenance. I will re-enable once that is complete. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1287487392"><groundspeak:date>2025-03-25T13:16:09</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">There seems to be a problem with your cache. Please check and maintain the cache and enable once it up and running and ready to be found . Normal maintenance time apply</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1286490597"><groundspeak:date>2025-03-20T21:07:34</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Needs Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="47629887">ForAfrica</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Today on my tour, I decided to try this remote and hard-to-reach cache. Unfortunately, as I mentioned, there's no cache anywhere nearby. I haven't found anything here except trash. Therefore, this cache should be archived.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="58.01725" lon="25.8812"><time>2001-02-10T00:00:00</time><name>GC263</name><desc>HE-stash / HE-aare by Enn and Hannes Veenpere</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC263</url><urlname>HE-stash / HE-aare</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="611" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>HE-stash / HE-aare</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Enn and Hannes Veenpere</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="2324">enn</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="55" inc="1">Short hike (&lt;1 km)</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Estonia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Helme village, near historical sights, inside an tree-trunk. Probably the first stash in Estonia.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;Peaks tõenäoliselt olema Eestis esimene selle mängu käigus peidetud aare.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Peitsid 10.02.01 Enn ja Hannes Veenpere.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Koordinaadid olid peitmise ajal: N 58° 01'02.2'' E 25° 52'51.5'' Nüüdseks aja jooksul veidi muutunud. Asukoha määrasime Garmin eTrexiga (sätingud WGS84 LAT/LON hddd°mm'ss.s'')&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Lähedal mälestis ja allikas. Muidu ka huvitav ja looduslikult ilus koht. Puutüvi. Aare ei saanud esimese korra puhul just eriti keerulisse kohta.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Parkige oma auto lihtsalt näiteks 58° 00'57.6'' ja 25° 52'48.2'', jalutage veidi kenas looduses ja peaksitegi varsti leidma.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Aardesse sai algselt pandud logiraamat ja pliiatseid, tutvustavad kirjad, väike telefonimärkmik, hot'i serveri sümboolikaga pastakas, metallist visiitkaartide karp, autojuhilubade kaaned, pakk nätsu. Kõik see oli pakitud suuremat sorti Nescafe purki ja keeratud musta kilekotti. Hiljem on ümbris ja sisu muutunud. Täname kõiki kes aegade jooksul on aidanud aardel heas seisus püsida.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364905881"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T16:13:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8401820">Lulybelle</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A trip around the Baltics with BigMcKs, Greeenbug, mattia_p, MacaroniSnr, Icklelego and TheSwerve, signing as Baltic Bashers. Of course we had a wish list of caches to put a shape on our few days.  We’ve been blessed with great weather and lovely caches, thank you to all the COs for making our trip so memorable 

After a morning walk to pick up a few caches we had missed around Tallinn we went back to the airport to pick up cars for the rest of the trip, then it was off to Riga with a few stops on the way

Of course this was on the list being the oldest in Estonia and what a great cache too with a lovely walk to it. FP and TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1365018723"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T16:08:34</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1032462">theswerve</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">20/05/2026 @ 16:08

Day 3 of a trip taking in Estonia-Finland-Latvia and Lithuania with a group of 7 cachers from Ireland 🇮🇪..

Day 1..Potter around Tallinn and attend a an event later…👍
Day 2…Trip across the sea to Finland..👍
Day 3…drive from Tallinn to Riga..
This was high on the list of caches to get on this trip,,,Found without bother…Nice to see these old caches surviving..TFTC

Logged on iPhone via Cachly </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363710073"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T16:08:32</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2884288">Mac Aroni Senior</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On tour with the Irish cachers again. 

We had a busy trip visiting 4 countries - for me it was 5 as I had spent a week in Denmark and arrived straight from Copenhagen. 

Thanks to all COs for placing and maintaining all the the caches. FPs are awarded randomly in appreciation of all the work gone into making them all. 

Caches signed as Baltic Bashers or BB and answers sent for the group when we get WiFi. 

TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363314865"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15322489">mattia_p</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Irish are on the road again.
Group of 7 (signing logs as Baltic Bashers); myself, Icklelego, Lulybelle, Greenbug, BigMcKs, MacAroni Senior, theswerve, took off from Dublin with a plan to visit Tallin, Helsinki, Riga,  Panevėžys (here for caches as well as 5km Park Run) and everything in between.
We had fabulous time meeeting local cachers, sampling local food and beer, visiting amazing places and having tones of laughs. We got over 150+ caches across 4 countries. Renting cars was essential to move around freely to get what we could in 6 days of travels. FP distributed accordingly. 
Thank you to all CO for placing and manatining all the caches.

TFTC! 😁</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362300113"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10360346">BigMcKs</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks to Enn and Hannes Veenpere for placing HE-stash / HE-aare.

Delighted to visit Estonia, Lithuania &amp; Latvia on a Baltics Dash tour - Baltic Bashers - Greeenbug, Lulybelle, the Swerve, Mac Aroni Senior, mattia_p, icklelego and BigMcKs. Including a short trip to Finland. Sightseeing and geocaching.  Thanks to all the geocache owners. I will drop some favourite points along the way. Lots of great caches to find. Answers for earthcaches  and virtuals will be sent when we have wifi. 

Favourite point for Estonia' oldest.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="13.602416666666667" lon="40.66158333333333"><time>2002-12-06T00:00:00</time><name>GCB5D7</name><desc>Erta Ale Volcano by Klammeraffe</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCB5D7</url><urlname>Erta Ale Volcano</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="46551" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Erta Ale Volcano</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Klammeraffe</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="25787">Klammeraffe</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Large</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Ethiopia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;H1&gt;Erta Ale Volcano Geocache&lt;/H1&gt;
&lt;P&gt;Inside the Danakil desert, the 600-meter shield volcano Erta Ale has a crater with a lava lake.&lt;BR&gt;
In December 2002, the &lt;a href="http://home.wtal.de/c_weber/"&gt;VEI Expedition&lt;/A&gt; reached the place and stayed for five days.&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;/P&gt;</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;H2&gt;Ethiopia's first Geocache!&lt;/H2&gt;
&lt;P&gt;Erta Ale volcano geocache is Ethiopia's first geocache!&lt;BR&gt;
Not made for the comfort-seeking tourist, you need to get into the world's hottest desert, travel among armed Afar nomad people who are at gunpoint with the ethiopian army and master volcanic territory.&lt;/P&gt;
Erta Ale (the Fuming or Devil's Mountain) lies in the north-east end of The Rift Valley segment that runs across Ethiopia and Djibouti to the Red Sea.  The summit lava lake sits at an elevation of about 500 m, while the base of the volcano rests 75 m below sea level.  Erta Ale and its neighbours have grown from the most low lying part of the Great Rift Valley on land.&lt;br&gt;  
One hundred kilometres away the rift has been flooded to create the Red Sea.  After rifting has started 20 million years ago, the crust of the continent eventually split between modern Ethiopia and Arabia, allowing a new crust to from upwelling lava.  What is happening now at the Red Sea is possibly what happened between the American and Afro-European continents when the Atlantic first developed 2000 million years ago.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;P&gt;
Erta Ale is a shield volcano, part of the East African rift system.  In its vast summit caldera there are two pit craters.  The smaller crater (140m dia and 60-90m deep) now has an active lava lake.  Even now, after the end of the war, the Erta Ale range remains one of the most inaccessible places on earth.  There are no roads and temperatures are extremely high. The tribe living there, the Afar people, are proud and strong warriors, often hostile to foreigners.&lt;P&gt;Getting to Erta Ale is not easy - just to reach the volcano is a test of endurance.  The volcano is situated at the bottom of the Danakil Depression, generally considered to be one of the most inhospitable regions on earth, a valley floor 130 m below sea level.  The climatic conditions are terrible, with record temperatures 56°C in the shade, but with no shade to be found there.&lt;br&gt;
The lava lake is permanently stirred by fountains of lava and the skin that covers it in some cooler spots makes it seem alive.  The lava of Erta Ale is basaltic, which remains molten at 1100°C.  The lava lake has a surface area of 4 000 sq m, so the thermal radiation is intense.  To lean over the crater without protection is out of the question.  Just to have a quick look, one must position gloved hands in front of the face.  Aluminium, fire-proof clothing Nomex is a must.  To protect the eyes, a sheet of polished gold must be used; it is only few microns thick and so see-through.&lt;br&gt;
With this armour one can at last approach the edge and take some time to admire the view.  The surface of the lake is covered in a layer of cooler lava, floating on the molten core like the skin on milk.  The lake is moving - a current ripples the lava and makes the skin undulate. This current originates in a fountain spraying molten lava brewed by the high temperature gas that it emits.  The skin is black in the shade, and as brilliant as silver in the sun.  The fountain is scarlet, becoming orange as its temperature rises.  The flow of the lava tears the skin into a huge panels separated by fissures through which lava shows red.  Bubbles of gas regularly break the surface of the lake, popping the elastic skin with spurts and incandescent jets.  A real volcanologic adventure!
&lt;/P&gt;
&lt;H2&gt;Location&lt;/H2&gt;
&lt;P&gt;The cache is inside a lava tunnel in safe distance to the pit crater, covered with pieces of broken lava tunnel ceiling.&lt;/P&gt;

&lt;H2&gt;Contents&lt;/H2&gt;
&lt;P&gt;The cache contains 2 canisters with 20 liters of treated water, a shovel, a large plastic tarp and several small items useful in a desert camp&lt;/P&gt;

&lt;H2&gt;More Volcano Geocaches&lt;/H2&gt;
&lt;P&gt;A list of more &lt;A href="http://www.klammeraffe.org/~fritsch/geo/vulkan/"&gt;volcano geocaches&lt;/A&gt; is available.&lt;/P&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>&lt;P&gt;Look at the western caldera wall close to a huge rock fall.&lt;/P&gt;</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1351766891"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4229727">Adamantan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Wow - what a a place for a cache!
I was looking at the coordinates (N 13° 36.211 E 040° 39.630) presented by DoloSteph and Otterlin, but I just found broken pieces that might have been a box for some time.
And since Hayli Gubbi broke out just 3 days before we came here I was not surprised that the box was gone. Therefore I have already prepared a replacement container for this cache including a new log book.

We came here with a group from Germany heading for Dallol. 
The journey started in Harar. We visited the city and got aquainted with the local food and som of the traditions. We visited the biggest Kat-market in the world in Aweday and headed West for Doho Lodge (nicely located at a hot spring with a lake) a little north of the Awash National Park. 
The following day we visited the Awash Falls and after that we hit the road and went North up to Semera, where we stayed the night.
Next day we visited a few hot springs in that area and then started our camping tour. First night at the Afambo Lake, second stay at the Afdera Lake and on the third day we reached Erta Ale Base Camp directly at the cell tower.
We went up to the vulcano soon after we reached the camp and stayed until the sun set. 
And on the next day we came back to see the sunrise. 
It is a marvelous experience to be here.
Thank you for placing this cache here!
TFTC Adamantan &amp; Adamantine</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1332919763"><groundspeak:date>2025-10-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2955856">mennerke</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Leuk dat je tijd neemt voor het plaatsen en onderhouden van deze cache!🙂

Merci pour la cache!👍
Merci d'avoir pris le temps de placer et d'entretenir cette cache !😁

Danke für diesen Cache!👍
Vielen Dank, dass Sie sich die Zeit genommen haben, diesen Cache zu platzieren und zu pflegen!😉

Thanks for the cache!👍
Thank you for taking the time to place and maintain this cache!😎</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1303700201"><groundspeak:date>2025-06-09T01:13:35</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="31923418">rusteelevrai</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Make me dream thanks </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1283959382"><groundspeak:date>2025-03-04T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10640187">DoloSteph</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">NEW COORDINATES: N 13° 36.211 E 40° 39.630

***Erta Ale Volcano*** : la boîte avait déjà disparu. Les pierres avaient bougé. Je replace un tube au même endroit qu'Ortellin. Le lieu est splendide et c'est mon premier volcan en activité. Je favorise le site 💙.

Merci Klammeraffe pour la pose de cette cache.

Mes objets voyageurs ne font que transiter par ce point et continuent leur voyage.

Trouvailles : 14321 

