Photo of the log in the log book 😊</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1321090294"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-15T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1726506">RxGal</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Two years ago Scouting4Ever and I signed on for a cruise at the invitation of a local geocacher, AndrewsDK. We invited PeachofWA and Skyhawker. PNW_Navigator and PNWcarrots joined next, then HTBob and 27 Jacks, and then DM&amp;K. 

We went on this trip to see the rich history, beautiful architecture and elegant culture of Europe, but also to find the oldest geocache in each area. Eight of us were all in when PNW_Navigator proclaimed he was going to find Iceland’s oldest, GC7AD7!

Some of us were working on difficult challenges, prompting a side-trip of three couples to plot a course from London across the Channel on Eurostar to Brussels, where we overnighted, rented a car and met up with a geocacher from the Netherlands who cheerfully and courageously drove us from Brussels through France, Luxemburg, Germany, the Netherlands and back to Brussels in time to catch the last train back to London, where we signed the final log of the day to meet the Challenge of finding 6 countries in a single day.

But back to this story, finding the oldest cache in Iceland. Research was done. Logs were read. Seabeck Tribe was consulted for travel tips, currency needs and where to buy food. Equipment for a variety of conditions was readied. (There were “Be prepared” Scouters in this group!) Cars, two for safety, were rented, both 4WD-high-clearance vehicles rated for the F-roads (translation: unpaved, unimproved, often heading off across lava fields) of Iceland. Additional gasoline in jerry cans was discussed but determined not to be necessary, given the fuel tanks and capacity of the cars we had rented. The terrain, temperature, windspeed, and whether the roads were open was researched, with route meticulously calculated and plotted by our resident expert, Skyhawker, down to the last route number, gas station and drop of gas. We departed from our ship in Reykjavik to pick up our rental cars in Keflavik, where we would return the cars and fly home. Lead drivers were Scouting4Ever in the Land Cruiser, followed by PNW_Navigator in the Jeep Wrangler. Both are Jeep owners with off-road experience, as are all the other couples in the intrepid group of eight. We stopped at the last gas station before heading into the wilderness. The Jeep was a hybrid requiring unleaded, but the Toyota was a diesel, and we got the last $4 worth of diesel in their tanks. The tank was just filled yesterday, we were told, so perhaps it was a clogged line from the tank to the pump….they would let the petrol supplier know.  A decision had to be made whether to proceed without a full tank of gas. After much deliberation and calculation, and gladness for having topped off the tank at the previous station, a plan was made. We would go with the Jeep as far as we could, but at 340km remaining, we would have to turn back and hope the ‘last gas station” had worked out the diesel fuel problem. Otherwise, the Jeep would travel on to the next closest, find fuel and bring it back to the Land Cruiser. Scouting4Ever kept his eye on the gas levels as we continued our journey.

The drivers’ offroad experience turned out to be useful, but the first big, wide river crossing had us all stop to eyeball the waves whipped up by the high winds playing against the river current. As we studied our approach options, a tall camper made its way across the river toward us, showing us the way. We crossed many rivers on the way to the cache, and returned over those same rivers, but two were noteworthy for being challenging. The second challenging river found us again eyeballing the wide river for an approach into deep, swift currents with waves whipped up by the 45mph winds. As we calculated our approach, a park ranger appeared on the other side in his 4WD high clearance truck, then plunged in and showed us which route to take, hopping from island to island, first upsteam then across. From there it was across gray, moon-like lava fields (yes, U.S. astronauts did train here) as we went up, and up, and up. We finally reached GZ to find that the wind was so strong it was difficult to open car doors, difficult to walk, painful with the black sand blasting into our faces, around our glasses into our eyes, and stinging any exposed surface of skin. Every time we picked up a foot to walk forward, we were pushed back. Leaning into the wind, the geocachers began their search. HTBob was the one who yelled, “Found it!”, and the log was brought back to the cars to sign, out of the wind, and to photograph our signatures. After a quick snack to recover, the cachers returned the cache to its hiding place, and we mounted up to head back across those rivers towards the gas station. Thankfully, the tanks had been refilled, both cars were filled up, and we were on the way back to our lodging for the night. It was a 15-hour drive, round trip.

Thank you for some of the best scenery we've ever seen, a grand adventure, the oldest cache in Iceland, and an experience that will last for a lifetime of tellings! 

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="21.8650833333333" lon="77.9615166666667"><time>2004-03-09T00:00:00</time><name>GCJ120</name><desc>Balajipuram by neeljana</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCJ120</url><urlname>Balajipuram</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="126141" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Balajipuram</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>neeljana</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="201724">neeljana</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>India</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Cache located in Betul District of state Madhya Pradesh, about halfway between the major cities of Nagpur and Bhopal right off the National Highway 69.  Short walk from highway over small stream bridge.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This cache is concealed in a clear Rubber-maid style plastic container with a Blue "Balajipuram" (Indian figure)paper insert on the inside.  Look for text on flagpole</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Find small temple and bamboo flagpole in front, look down</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1151721186"><groundspeak:date>2023-03-04T04:05:15</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="115500">Crow T Robot</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache has been reported missing but players continue to log finds on it.  It appears that the local maintainer is no longer able to care for this cache.  Please submit a new listing if this issue is resolved.  Thank you.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1149963512"><groundspeak:date>2023-02-20T15:50:44</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25094385">arsalan4788</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">بلای جان تبریک ب خودم </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1149961976"><groundspeak:date>2023-02-20T15:38:28</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25094385">arsalan4788</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">🌺😍😍😍</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1149961948"><groundspeak:date>2023-02-20T15:38:05</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25094385">arsalan4788</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">درود درود فقط</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1118117205"><groundspeak:date>2022-08-13T21:55:41</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="42666335">Shaunak2395</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">:)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-8.357567" lon="115.69455"><time>2001-07-24T00:00:00</time><name>GC1488</name><desc>Indonesia One - Bali by Champurrado, SunnyRac, and Made Sheila</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1488</url><urlname>Indonesia One - Bali</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="5256" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Indonesia One - Bali</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Champurrado, SunnyRac, and Made Sheila</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="4849">SunnyRac</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Indonesia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This cache will lead you to one of the more remote tourist areas of Bali. This is a gorgeous place to relax and see the sunset, and a great area to spend some time. Visitors will be rewarded with cliff side ocean views. Bring your swimsuit.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The loot is stashed just past Good Karma and before Reincarnation.
&lt;p&gt;It seems that most of the terrain in Bali is used for living, farming, or grazing. This trek will take you along a hilly shore to lived-on land. Although this area is touristed it offers a nice antidote to the bustle of Ubud and Kuta. The drive to this site from Kuta will take you through some of the most beautiful rice terraces in Bali. Bring a camera.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is easy to find, but hard to reach without some transport. We recommend attempting this cache only if you plan on staying overnight in the area, as it is about three hours from Kuta. If you do stay and enjoy snorkeling/scuba, check out the sunken World War II vessel nearby-a huge ship with plenty of fish stowaways.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When you reach the cache coordinates, proceed through a passage that carries you up between two small bales* (*see clues). You will find the cache where they accept cash. Tell the gatekeeper that you are there for the geocache. The first person to reach the cache will be treated to a refreshment by the gatekeeper.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is in a plastic box with all sorts of supplies for the weary traveller. Chapstick, earplugs (for those pesky rooster call mornings), playing cards (one pack is from the Pajarito Springs cache in New Mexico, USA), a small flashlight, etc. There are also three handmade clay beads that say "peace" in three languages. These are from the Burning Man Festival 1999 in Nevada, USA.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is not a commercial cache, but is found on commercial land. We placed it here to keep it from being overturned in a rice padi or discovered by a wandering dog. However, few will be disappointed by the remoteness and beauty of the area. It is also a treat to meet the kindly gatekeepers. We look forward to hearing about your adventure.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The cache is on the East coast of Bali, South of Amed, in an area called Selang.  It is best accessed with a car or driver, as the walk can be long, depending on your starting location.   If you are really looking for a hike, there are plenty of trekking ops in the area.  If you are staying overnight, we heard about a sunrise hike to Gunung Seraya.

The cache is on the inland side of the main coastal road.  Look for the sign that says "Blue Moon Villa, Komang John Cafe".  Enter here.  The rest is easy.  Komang John makes a mean Arak Saint John...and his brother Komang Bijang grills a tasty daily catch.  The food here is simple, but divine, and will leave you with plenty of extra rupia to buy silly trinkets for the cache.  

By the way, the pool is stunning.  Ask Komang John if you can take a dip.

*Bale - an open-sided structure
</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1362087493"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-19T16:05:37</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="14779984">Tinade</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">At the end of Bali we get this Cache. We are happy 😀😃🙂</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360534342"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-12T17:27:40</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="40661467">Hottiemonster</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found my first grocache in bali. Nice to sit down and have a drink and watch the ocean.
Staying in amed for a week
Tftc</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360365394"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-11T11:03:06</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4118159">66st</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Vielen Dank für den Cache.😁</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1356795374"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-24T14:45:05</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="12987206">Axax53</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found while in amed, had to get this old one! Very nice place! :)

TFTC! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1356363577"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-21T15:14:42</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="35558510">Thamora</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Stayed in the hotel and just saw by accident that here is the first cache ever created in Indonesia! 🤩

The staff in the hotel is super friendly and they were very supportive also when my mother felt sick - so I think the cache is in good hands to stay there another 25 years 😉
Tftc!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="34.1743" lon="53.68175"><time>2005-02-22T00:00:00</time><name>GCMXZB</name><desc>Genie Bottle by aliparsa</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCMXZB</url><urlname>Genie Bottle</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="212549" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Genie Bottle</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>aliparsa</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="346238">aliparsa</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Iran</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>A plastic bottle containing small items burried in the center of Rig-e Jeen, a less-explored area in the central desert of Iran.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>A ball-point pen with UPS marking and some Berkeley addresses

A glass test tube (in which there's a note about us in Persian)

A pair of bolts and nuts (3/8 24 threads/inch)

A plastic strap

A 250 RLS coin

A 100 RLS coin

Two 12 mm washers

An H green pencile

A magnifying lens

A surgical blade (strile)

A geneine M151 strap guide

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1222712402"><groundspeak:date>2022-10-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1857257">peretpintor</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Trobat en el meu viatge en moto de Catalunya a Iran.
MGPC !

Found on my motorbike trip from Catalonia to Iran.
TFTC !
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="570435828"><groundspeak:date>2016-01-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="14126318">trash88</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">tftc</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="281711560"><groundspeak:date>2012-11-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6665966">hr_haddadzadeh</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">:D it was so fun..! we did it with iran deserts group.. and we added our bottle of secrets as well.....!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="284393292"><groundspeak:date>2012-11-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4223775">kbabazadeh</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Add another bottle to the point for second time...</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="175071350"><groundspeak:date>2011-07-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="960510">Heid</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">?? Is this available ?
or what is there to believe ?
suspect one !</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="30.9626" lon="46.102867"><time>2003-09-18T00:00:00</time><name>GCGXJB</name><desc>Ziggurat of Ur by bridwell adopted by H2Nut</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCGXJB</url><urlname>Ziggurat of Ur</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="93013" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Ziggurat of Ur</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>bridwell adopted by H2Nut</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="213301">H2Nut</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Micro</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Iraq</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Come see the Ziggurat of Ur, also known as the Ur of the Chaldees
Ziggurat at Tall al Muqayyar</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This is a rare opportunity to see buildings and ruins that date
from 4,000-2,000 BC. Sir Leonard Wooley first excavated this site
in 1922-1934. Records establish this site as the ancient capital of
Sumeria. Ur of the Chaldees is also considered as Abraham’s
birthplace, the common patriarch of the Jewish, Christian and
Muslim faiths. 
&lt;p&gt;Cache is in a large pill bottle.&lt;br&gt;
 Contents include:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Iraqi currency&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Postage stamps&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;$10 phone card&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;110/220 volt adapter&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Safety pin&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Dog tag chain&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Plastic hook&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Paper/Pencil for logs&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please follow the: &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocreed.info"&gt;&lt;img src=
'http://img.groundspeak.com/user/thumb/755ffac7-79cb-4810-aceb-2ca82b8c3a90.jpg'
     border="0" align="middle"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Within the base of a utility pole on the south side of the Ziggurat.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1344547284"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-10T16:54:28</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="37122439">Rico6284</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Agreed with previous comments, now is all fenced and cache is not accessible</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359277220"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7366439">Rezi73</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Zusammen mit Kleinzschachwitzer habe ich mich auf eine ganz besondere Reise begeben: Von Frankfurt ging es über Istanbul zunächst nach Kuwait City und schließlich weiter in den Irak. Schon die Route war ein kleines Abenteuer für sich, aber vor Ort wurde es noch beeindruckender.

Wir durften tief in die faszinierende Geschichte der Menschheit eintauchen, alte Kulturen hautnah erleben und viele unvergessliche Eindrücke sammeln. Es ist schon etwas Besonderes, an Orten zu stehen, an denen Geschichte geschrieben wurde – Momente, die einem lange im Gedächtnis bleiben.

Natürlich kam auch unser gemeinsames Hobby nicht zu kurz: Unterwegs konnten wir einige spannende Geocaches entdecken, die diese Reise zusätzlich bereichert haben. Gerade an so außergewöhnlichen Orten zu cachen, macht für mich einen ganz besonderen Reiz aus.

Ein herzliches Dankeschön an alle Cacheowner fürs Legen und Pflegen der Dosen. Ohne eure Mühe, Kreativität und Zeit wäre dieses wunderbare Hobby in dieser Form gar nicht möglich!

Viele liebe Grüße aus dem schönen Sachsen in Deutschland
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1345373626"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4435272">Kleinzschachwitzer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**Kuwait** 🇰🇼 and **Iraq** 🇮🇶 – between desert, world history and lots of smileys 🙂 ... 😎

From January 30 to February 14, [@Rezi73](https://coord.info/PR8D260), a muggle friend and I went on a very special tour: **Kuwait** 🇰🇼 and **Iraq** 🇮🇶 – two countries that are not everyday geocaching destinations, but which welcomed us with open arms, great hospitality and impressive history.

Our journey began in **Kuwait City**, where modernity and tradition stand side by side. A glittering skyline 🌇, wide promenades along the **Arabian Gulf**, and traditional souks filled with the scent of spices 🌶️ and coffee ☕ – an exciting contrast. Of course, we didn't miss the opportunity to search for some geocaches 🛢 here as well. Between the dhow harbor and the skyscrapers, we were able to log the first smileys 🙂 of our trip.

We continued across the border into **Iraq** 🇮🇶 – a country steeped in history, whose cultural significance is almost impossible to put into words. In **Basra**, we felt the pulse of the south, shaped by the confluence of the **Euphrates** and **Tigris** rivers. The people we met were curious and warm, and conversations often arose spontaneously – whether over tea 🫖 at the roadside or while looking at our GPS 🛰️ devices together.

An absolute highlight was our visit to **Ur,** one of the most important cities of **Sumerian** civilization. Standing among the remains of the **ziggurat** and knowing that history was written here over 4,000 years ago was a spine-tingling moment. Here, too, we were able to log a few geocaches 🛢 – modern treasure hunters meet ancient world 🌍 history.

**Babylon** was no less impressive. Walking through the reconstructed **Ishtar Gate** and following in the footsteps 👣 of **Nebuchadnezzar II** made history tangible. The massive walls 🧱, the remains of the palaces, and the view over the ancient city gave us an idea of the importance this place once had for the entire region. Hosting an event 📒 between myths of world wonders 🏛️ and archaeological sites was a very special moment of our trip.

In **Baghdad**, we immersed ourselves in the stories of 1001 Nights. The **Tigris**, old book 📜 markets, mosques 🕌 and bustling streets – a city full of contrasts, between past and present. We were particularly impressed by the warmth of the people. Despite language barriers, we were always welcomed, photographed 📷 or invited for tea 🫖.

Another highlight was **Erbil** with its historic citadel ⛫ – one of the oldest permanently inhabited places in the world 🌍. From above, we had a sweeping view of the city, while below us, history became visible layer by layer. Of course, we couldn't miss out on finding a geocache 🛢 here either.

Along the way, we experienced vast desert 🐪 landscapes, fertile river valleys, modern cities, and millennia-old ruins. This trip showed us once again how connecting our hobby is: even in regions that many only know from the news, there are small geocaches that tell stories and lead us to special places.

Favorite point awarded for showing this great place ... 🙂

"Thanks for the cache" says ***Kleinzschachwitzer*** from Germany</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1333001164"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-03T14:03:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3382126">dejdy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We visited Zigurrat of Ur during our trip to federal Iraq. The site is accessible, but only from the front, there is barbed wire on the sides, so it is not possible to get to the actual cache location. I hope photolog is OK with the owner, but I think that none of the recent founders actually got to the cache itself. Anyway, thanks for the cache in an amazing place!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1333001325"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-03T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3543281">_dam</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found with dejdy, picture as proof in his log.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="53.192017" lon="-6.084183"><time>2000-06-03T00:00:00</time><name>GC43</name><desc>Europe's First by Donnacha (Orginal CO Chris O'Byrne)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC43</url><urlname>Europe's First</urlname><sym>Geocache Found</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="67" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Europe's First</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Donnacha (Orginal CO Chris O'Byrne)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="61401">Donnacha</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="26" inc="1">Public transportation nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Ireland</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Leinster</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description> &lt;div align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/gs-geo-images/e10e72b1-b325-45c3-9590-15a8d5da0ca0.gif" usemap="#image-maps-2017-01-05-162806" alt name="Image-Maps-Com-image-maps-2017-01-05-162806" width="500" height="206" border="0" /&gt;&lt;map name="image-maps-2017-01-05-162806"&gt;
&lt;area alt="GCI" title="GCI" href="Http://www.geocachingireland.com" shape="rect" coords="0,0,207,206" target="_blank" style="outline:none;" /&gt;
&lt;area alt="FBP" title="FBP" href="https://www.facebook.com/geocachingireland" shape="rect" coords="221,92,361,117" target="_blank" style="outline:none;" /&gt;
&lt;area alt="FBG" title="FBG" href="http://facebook.geocachingireland.com" shape="rect" coords="213,117,451,142" target="_blank" style="outline:none;" /&gt;
&lt;/map&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;font color="#ff0000"&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;b&gt;Temporary Relocation&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;font color="#ff0000"&gt;Due to a rockfall on the Cliff Walk a gate has
been installed preventing access to GZ. This leads me to believe
it may be sometime before the walk is reopened again. I have
decided to temporarily move the cache until the walk is reopened.
This has resulted in the cache now being more difficult to access
as you must now climb up part of Bray Head. This was unavoidable
due to the terrain and other caches within proximity.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div align="left"&gt;Bray Head, County Wicklow, Ireland. The first geocache in Europe, placed on 3rd June 2000 - just one month after the demise of selective availability.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When selective availability was turned off, and the geocaching
game took off, I decided to hide a cache near where I was living
in Bray, Co. Wicklow. I was delighted to see that I manged to
place the cache before anyone else in Europe placed one.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And so all was well, until 15 June 2003, when I went to visit the
cache and found it to be gone! Disheartened, I found it too
difficult to replace the cache.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Enter &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=614db9bd-d00e-4480-9a64-accd6b48f410"&gt;Donnacha&lt;/a&gt;
who, on 31 May 2004, placed a replacement cache within eyeshot of
the original location. The coordinates listed above refer to the
coordinates of the replacement cache - the original cache was at
53d 11.477' N, 6d 04.804' W, hidden under stones where the two
walls meet. You can view photos &lt;a href="http://imgcdn.geocaching.com/cache/large/e53cdf18-69a3-49ca-9fe0-4a10bf555447.jpg"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;
and &lt;a href="http://imgcdn.geocaching.com/cache/large/fa6b1519-e0fa-4908-8707-9700deac0f6c.jpg"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.
If you are visiting the replacement, do say hello to the original
location!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And so the cache lives again! Enjoy!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As you make your way towards the cache, look left and you will
see Lord Meath's Lodge.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The railway company owned the walkway up to Lord Meath’s Lodge.
They kept the gate closed and charged a penny for entry each day
except Friday. The estate house was Killruddery House, which is
now open to the public. A dirt road was also constructed around
the top of Bray Head for guests, and this was also open to the
public. The cliff walk was closed each Friday when it was reserved
for Lord Meath’s own use. The steps above the toll house led to
the estate and the stones for the cottage and the toll gate were
collected from the immediate area with the exception of granite
and red brick which were brought to the site.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;a href="http://info.flagcounter.com/t4Gq"&gt;&lt;img src="http://s07.flagcounter.com/count/t4Gq/bg_FFFFFF/txt_000000/border_CCCCCC/columns_4/maxflags_20/viewers_0/labels_0/pageviews_0/flags_0/percent_0/" alt="Flag Counter" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/center&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Base of rock, covered by some stones.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1365016525"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T16:51:52</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9224274">Team Chaenaan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A few days left in our Ireland vacation. So time to find Europe:s oldest. Quite a hike to get to ground zero through butned landscape. But we found it! Thanks for the cache.  #11695</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364967415"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10527167">Cindyv88</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Op citytrip in Dublin. Met als hoofddoel deze cache vinden. En dat is gelukt. Tftc</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364948031"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6195595">R.R.83</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Irl:
Bhí cuairt a thabhairt ar an gcéad gheocache san Eoraip ar mo liosta mianta le fada an lá. I mbliana d’éirigh liom mo theaghlach a chur ina luí ar thuras gearr a dhéanamh. Go gairid roimh ár dteacht, díghníomhaíodh an taisce mar gheall ar thine foraoise, ach ar ámharaí an tsaoil, athghníomhaíodh é ceithre lá roimh ár n-imeacht. Mar sin inniu, ghlac mé an chéad traein amach as Baile Átha Cliath i dtreo GC43. Nach mór an t-ádh gur fhág an duine a fuair é romham leid luachmhar do na cúpla méadar deireanacha ina log. Mar sin lean mé an príomhchonair go dtí díreach faoi bhun Bhré Cheann Bhré agus as sin chuaigh mé díreach chuig an taisce. Is rud maith é gur mhair an bosca armlóin an tine foraoise gan dochar...

Eng:
Visiting Europe's first geocache had been on my wish list for a long time. This year I managed to convince my family to take a short trip. Shortly before our arrival, the cache was deactivated due to a forest fire, but fortunately, it was reactivated four days before our departure. So today, I took the first train out of Dublin towards GC43. How lucky that the person who found it before me left a valuable tip for the last few meters in their log. So I followed the main path to just below Brayhead and from there went directly to the cache. It's a good thing the ammo box survived the forest fire unscathed...

De:
Europas ersten Geocache zu Besuchen stand schon lange auf meiner Wunschliste. Dieses Jahr konnte ich die Familie von einem Kurztrip überzeugen. Kurz vor unseren Anreise wurde der Cache dann wegen eines Waldbrandes deaktiviert, aber glücklicherweise 4 Tage vor unsere Abreise wieder aktiviert. Heute dann mal früh mit dem ersten Zug raus aus Dublin Richtung GC43. Wie gut, dass mein Vorfinder eine wertvollen Tipp für die letzten Meter in seinem Log hinterlassen hat. So ging es entlang des Hauptweges bis knapp unterhalb zum Brayhead und von da ab direkt zur Dose. Wie gut das die Ammobox den Waldbrand gut überstanden hat...

TFTC R.R.83</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364800459"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:41:08</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="61401">Donnacha</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Fire is now out.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364903763"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="30839564">bükkfa</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Auch wir stehen jetzt im Logbuch des ersten europäischen Caches! 
Wir raten aber jedem dringend den Hauptweg bis knapp unterhalb zum Brayhead hochzugehen und dann wieder runter zur Dose.
Wir sind leider falsch abgebogen und haben uns  den Weg durch den verbrannten Ginster gebahnt.
Keine gute Idee..
Tftc!

We are now also in the logbook of the first European cache!
But we strongly advise everyone to go up the main route just below the Brayhead and then back down to the can.
Unfortunately, we turned wrong and made our way through the burnt ginster.
Not a good idea.
Greetings from Germany!
Tftc!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="894308792"><groundspeak:date>2019-08-15T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2089726">travelingGeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">How in the world, did I forget to log this one!?!

Probably because I wanted to write some epic log!  Alas that didn't happen!

Glad I realized I forgot to log it so I am now.  

Attaching photo for proof!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="54.144133" lon="-4.4727"><time>2002-05-20T00:00:00</time><name>GC5A4C</name><desc>Manx by ThePuzzler adopted by twoofnine</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC5A4C</url><urlname>Manx</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="23116" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Manx</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>ThePuzzler adopted by twoofnine</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="4752089">twoofnine</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Isle of Man</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;It is our privilege to be the adoptive owners of this, the first and oldest geocache, on the Isle of Man.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The original wording can be found below but perhaps a few words of clarification are now required.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache has not been moved, but the original co-ordinates were for a reference point from which to begin your search. As this point, an "X" marked on a wall, has faded over time, the new co-ords are for the cache itself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is parking on the road adjacent to the approach to the cache. As there is some tree cover, please give your GPS device time to settle.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please note that D/T ratings for old caches such as this were added retrospectively and may not exactly match what would be expected today. Perhaps D1.5/T3 might be more realistic.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Many thanks to "ThePuzzler" for starting the hobby of geocaching on the Isle of Man.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Here is the original description:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cache placed in a hurry as only had 5 mins before the ferry left. So first finder please relocate to a more suitable location.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Have listed this cache in Ireland and UK as IOM has visitors from both countries.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is the first cache for Isle of Man.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Covered in stick-o-flage, in crook of multi-trunk tree. Access up the bank is behind the parking sign.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364025072"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T15:08:14</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="44312783">stockerh</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it thank you x</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364476011"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4354420">mefromhere</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Today we went to Douglas by bus to get the steam train to Port Erin to visit the town. 
Back in Douglas we also visited some caches nearby.
This one was part of our todays tour.
Thanks to the over for this cache. 

28. Mai 2026</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362583945"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T09:34:50</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18887505">khanks79</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it 😀</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362540916"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7583636">samager</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We zijn aangekomen op Island of Men en willen zeker een paar caches doen. We maken een wandelrondje en kunnen zo een serie adventure cachea doen, een aantal tradies en multies. Ook bezoeken we nog een earthcache en een virtual.

Dit is een van de caches die we vandaag hebben gelogd/bezocht.

TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362381149"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8907503">PETER_LV</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Today we flied from Dublin to Douglas .

After visit the highiest hill on Isle of Man, we were a little bit walking in Douglas.

This one we found without problem.
Thank you for taking care of this 24 year old cache.

Greetings from Slovakia. 

TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="32.17005" lon="34.803433"><time>2002-04-14T00:00:00</time><name>GC4CEC</name><desc>20 Years (Isreal) by GekoTeam</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC4CEC</url><urlname>20 Years (Isreal)</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="19692" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>20 Years (Isreal)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>GekoTeam</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="8790">GekoTeam</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Israel</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>What are we and how many of us are there.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>To confirm the cash please email us at: gekoteam@gmail.com &lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;Don't post your answer here, even if encrypted.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Why 20 years?&lt;br /&gt;The last time I stood here was 20 years ago when this was just starting to be a hi-tec area. It has is grown!&lt;br /&gt;Now it is with the whole GekoTeam.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Just relaxing on the grass.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1347216468"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4471472">Just75</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I really like virtual caches.
They are usually not very demanding, you don't have to spend hours and hours there, you don't have to drive dozens of kilometers, and yet you will see and remember places that you would never have known without these caches.
Thank you very much and I will give you a point.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1336557653"><groundspeak:date>2025-12-01T16:49:26</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="46087147">Itayker22</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Woah, what a special cache! Had to re-read the publishing date to make sure I saw it correctly, haha. Amazing that it's here for so long! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1340503238"><groundspeak:date>2025-10-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8765631">3_Dragons</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A short walk to this place to check how many of what there are in order to answer the question.

TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1315580401"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-06T11:24:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5797551">Mkuutomasi</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Wow, an old virtual cache! This is too nice! Nowadays the virtual caches are common, but I can remember the times when they were rare as webcam caches. :-)
I am currently working in Israel. My hotel is in Herzliya. 
Thank you!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1305823905"><groundspeak:date>2025-06-05T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1097464">Fógl</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#13861
Dnes mi končí dovolená v Izraeli, a tak se cestou z Haify na letiště v Tel Avivu ještě zastavuji u této virtuálky. Děkuji za cache a posílám pozdrav z České republiky :-)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="46.521633" lon="11.3613"><time>2001-05-15T00:00:00</time><name>GC17B3</name><desc>Bergwind -ZF218 by GeoFaex adopted by ZerminigerFour</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC17B3</url><urlname>Bergwind -ZF218</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="6067" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Bergwind -ZF218</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>GeoFaex adopted by ZerminigerFour</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="6441689">ZerminigerFour</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="0">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="10" inc="1">Difficult climb</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Italy</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Trentino–Alto Adige</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Box covered with stones, not buried. Very beautiful area.

Bergwind, meanwhile the oldest active geocache in Italy</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;div&gt;Bergwind, a Historic Geocache - Classed as 'Ancient' (2001)&lt;br /&gt; &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=789d2dc7-4541-4eac-9768-f48fe340a738"&gt;&lt;img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/gs-geo-images/153835b6-a9c1-4fa3-b37b-89352d8de2a9.jpg" /&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/log/1d14c1b3-0d95-4f34-b00e-b587239f1e84.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Read more about The Historic Geocaches' &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=789d2dc7-4541-4eac-9768-f48fe340a738"&gt;campaign&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a name="campaign"&gt;&lt;img class="gclh_vip" title="Add campaign to VIP-List" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you find a good place to park your vehicle, the find is easy. If you hike to the cache from the next city, it might be more difficult. The area is perfect for motorbiking, mountainbiking, hiking ... or just watching beautiful landscapes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Update 20.07.2019&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="tlid-translation translation" lang="en"&gt;&lt;span class title&gt;-The coordinates had to be moved due to the closure of the old road.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span title&gt;They adapted the conduct of the road in Val Sarentino and built a new tunnel.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="tlid-translation translation" lang="en"&gt;&lt;span title&gt;- Le coordinate dovevano essere spostate a causa della chiusura della strada vecchia.&lt;br /&gt;
Hanno adattato la condotta della strada in Val Sarentino e hanno costruito una nuova galleria.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="tlid-translation translation" lang="en"&gt;&lt;span title&gt;- &lt;span class="tlid-translation translation" lang="de"&gt;&lt;span class title&gt;Die Koordinaten mussten aufgrund der Sperrung der alten Straße verschoben werden.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Sie haben die Straßenführung im Sarntal angepasst und einen neuen Tunnel gebaut.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Spoiler</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364811682"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4599481">lterSchwede46</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Auf dem Heimweg vom ersten Mega in Italien machten wir für diesen Methusalem natürlich einen Umweg. 

Ich wusste ja von Vorloggern schon so in etwa, was mich hier erwarten würde, bin dann aber doch mit ziemlich weichen Knien wieder auf die Straße zurück. 

Danke für die mehr als 25 Jahre!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364924973"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21302979">Zuiderkruis63</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">******** Mei 2026 ********

Wat een fantastische dag tijdens het Pizza Event hij was kort even mijn naam op de pizza 🍕☀️

Na een gezellige start ging de route verder naar Bergwind-ZF218. Wat was het daar prachtig! De uitzichten waren indrukwekkend en met het schitterende weer was het puur genieten.

Daarna door naar de EarthCache PORPHYR in Bozen. Altijd bijzonder om onderweg iets te leren over de geologie van een gebied, en deze locatie maakte dat extra interessant. Vervolgens bezocht ik de traditionele cache bij Schloss Runkelstein. Wat een schitterende plek! De combinatie van geschiedenis, cultuur en het prachtige decor maakte dit absoluut een hoogtepunt van de dag. Hiervoor laat ik graag een FAVO achter. ⭐

Ook Burg Ried stond op het programma. Wederom een prachtige locatie waar ik volop heb genoten van de omgeving en de bijzondere sfeer. Ook hier verdient de cache een FAVO. ⭐

De wegen waren vandaag behoorlijk druk, maar dat kon de pret absoluut niet drukken. Van de ene mooie locatie naar de andere rijden, genieten van het prachtige weer, de indrukwekkende landschappen en de mooie caches maakte deze dag meer dan geslaagd.

Uiteindelijk doorgereden naar mijn overnachting in Sterzing, met een grote glimlach terugkijkend op een geweldige dag vol mooie ervaringen.

Dank aan alle CO's voor het leggen en onderhouden van deze caches. Jullie laten ons genieten van prachtige plekken die we anders misschien nooit hadden ontdekt 🌻



What a fantastic day during the Pizza Event! 🍕☀️

After a great start at the event, I continued my journey to Bergwind-ZF218. What a beautiful location! The views were stunning, and with the wonderful weather, it was an absolute pleasure to be there.

Next was the EarthCache PORPHYR in Bozen. I always enjoy learning something new about the geology of an area, and this location made the experience even more interesting. After that, I visited the traditional cache at Schloss Runkelstein. What an amazing place! The combination of history, culture, and the beautiful surroundings made this one of the highlights of the day. A well-deserved FAVO goes here. ⭐

Burg Ried was also on today's itinerary. Once again, a beautiful location where I thoroughly enjoyed the scenery and unique atmosphere. This cache also earns a FAVO. ⭐

The roads were quite busy today, but that certainly did not spoil the fun. Traveling from one beautiful location to another, enjoying the fantastic weather, impressive landscapes, and wonderful caches made this a truly memorable day.

I finally arrived at my overnight stop in Sterzing with a big smile, looking back on a day filled with great experiences.

Many thanks to all the cache owners for placing and maintaining these caches. Thanks to your efforts, we get to discover beautiful places that we might otherwise never have found!🌻

FP awarded where mentioned. ⭐</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364664970"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="26007775">MoHa_PL</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">31 maja 2026. 
Po pierwszym Mega we Włoszech wracając do domu, zaplanowaliśmy zalogować kilka ciekawych keszy.
Ten był jednym z nich.
TFTC. 

After our first Mega in Italy, on our way home, we planned to log a few interesting caches.
This was one of them.
TFTC.


