Track for Infos - HAEX3W</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364998126"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="16551910">Mokušiak</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Veve99 and I have been planning a trip to Italy for a long time and took the opportunity to combine it with a visit to the first Italian MEGA event. The weather forecast was promising 🌞 with temperatures around 30°C.

Thursday: At midday, we got in the car 🚗 and set off. Through Austria, a short stretch through Germany, and then back through Austria. Along the way, we logged a few geocaches and stopped in Kufstein in the evening, where we spent the night. We ended a rather tiring day of travel with a delicious dinner 🍗🍲🍺 😃.

Friday: We continued on towards Italy. We stopped at carefully selected geocaches, highly rated geocaches, geocaches with interesting D/T combinations, and old geocaches (we even found the oldest Italian one!). We visited other beautiful places, some with geocaches and some without. Furthermore, we ended a pleasant but also tiring day with dinner, this time at a well-known fast-food chain 🍔🍲🍺 😃.

Saturday: We headed to the venue of the MEGA event. We enjoyed the pleasant atmosphere of the well-organized event. We met some friends and also knew new ones. In the afternoon, we explored the surrounding area with geocaching. We visited more beautiful places, some with caches and some without. We went to Varese, visiting the Sacro Monte, hiked through the forest to the southernmost Swiss geocache, made a stop in Como, and then continued on to our accommodation. In the evening, we couldn't resist a classic Italian dinner 🍕🍺 😃.

Sunday: Before starting our journey home, we went to the CITO event. The location was perfectly chosen. There really was a lot to clean up. On the way back, we stopped in Brescia and then in Spiazzi to visit the Santuario Madonna della Corona. After that, we only made brief stops at rest areas for drive-in caches.

Many thanks 👏 to all the cache owners who invited us to so many beautiful locations and set up and maintained the caches.

---
📝 S veve99 sme si už dlhšie plánovali výlet do Talianska a tak sme využili príležitosť spojiť ho s návštevou prvého talianskeho MEGAeventu. Predpoveď počasia bola sľubná 🌞 s teplotami okolo 30°C. 

Štvrtok: na poludnie sadáme do 🚗 a vyrážame. Cez Rakúsko, kúsok cez Nemecko a opäť Rakúsko. Cestou logujeme pár keší a večer si robíme zastávku aj s prespaním v Kufsteine. Celkom náročný cestovný deň končíme dobrou večerou 🍗🍲🍺 😃.

Piatok: pokračujeme smer Taliansko. Zastavujeme sa na starostlivo vytipovaných keškách, vysoko hodnotených, zaujímavých D/T kombináciou, starých (aj najstaršiu taliansku sme našli). Navštevujeme ďalšie pekné miesta s keškami aj bez nich. Príjemný, ale tiež náročný deň sme zakončili večerou, tentoraz takou fastfoodovou 🍔🍲🍺 😃.

Sobota: presunuli sme sa do dejiska MEGA eventu. Užívame si príjemnú atmosféru dobre zorganizovanej akcie. Stretáme známe tváre, ale aj spoznávame nové. Neskôr poobede sme sa vybrali keškovať do širšieho okolia. Opäť navštevujeme pekné miesta s keškami aj bez nich. Navštívili sme Varese. Prešli sme sa lesom k najjužnejšej švajčiarskej keške, odtiaľ sme si urobili zastávku v Como a pokračovali na ubytovanie. Večer sme neodolali klasickej talianskej večeri 🍕🍺 😃.

Nedeľa: predtým ako sme vyrazili na spiatočnú cestu sme sa vybrali na CITO. Lokalita pre tento účel vynikajúco vybratá. Veru, bolo čo upratovať. Na spiatočnej ceste sme sa zastavili v Brescia a v Spiazzi s návštevou Santuario Madonna della Corona. Potom už nasledovali iba krátke zastávky na drive-in kešky na odpočívadlách.

Vďaka 👏 všetkým ownerom za pozvanie na mnohé krásne miesta, zakladanie a starostlivosť o kešky.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="5.25415" lon="-3.617967"><time>2013-01-06T00:00:00</time><name>GC43ZMR</name><desc> first cache's in ivoiry coast by mathstev</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC43ZMR</url><urlname> first cache's in ivoiry coast</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3401811" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name> first cache's in ivoiry coast</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>mathstev</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1344679">mathstev</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Côte d'Ivoire</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>La cache se situe à quelques dizaines de mêtres de la statue de la vierge marie au bord d'une parcelle d'evéas
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p style="margin:0cm 14.2pt 0pt;text-align:justify;line-height:14pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="color:rgb(51, 51, 51);font-family:Verdana;font-size:10pt;"&gt;A l'entrée de Bonoua, sur la colline d'Impérié, est érigé un grand Sanctuaire dédié à la Vierge Marie, Notre-Dame de la Garde, en souvenir de son apparition à Gênes (Italie) en 1490.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="margin:0cm 14.2pt 0pt;text-align:justify;line-height:14pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="color:rgb(51, 51, 51);font-family:Verdana;font-size:10pt;"&gt;Une dévotion très chère à don Orione, dont les dépouilles réposent aux pieds du sanctuaire dédié à la Vierge du même titre, qu'il fit construire à Tortona par ses séminaristes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="margin:0cm 14.2pt 0pt;text-align:justify;line-height:14pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="color:rgb(51, 51, 51);font-family:Verdana;font-size:10pt;"&gt;Une statue de huit mètres (œuvre du sculpteur Donkor) est sur place depuis 2002, et beaucoup de pèlerins sont déjà venus, même de loin, pour prier la Vierge et implorer sa protection.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="margin:0cm 14.2pt 0pt;text-align:justify;line-height:14pt;"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="margin:0cm 14.2pt 0pt;text-align:justify;line-height:14pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="color:rgb(51, 51, 51);font-family:Verdana;font-size:10pt;"&gt;La construction du Sanctuaire a commencé en 2004 : un sanctuaire moderne, capable de 1000 places.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="margin:0cm 14.2pt 0pt;text-align:justify;line-height:14pt;"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="margin:0cm 14.2pt 0pt;text-align:justify;line-height:14pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="color:rgb(51, 51, 51);font-family:Verdana;font-size:10pt;"&gt;Le 6 décembre 2009, Mons Paul Dakoury-Tabley, evêque de Grand Bassam, a béni le nouveau sanctuaire, à la présence de prêtres, religieux et religieuses de la Congrégation de don Orione et du diocèse.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="margin:0cm 14.2pt 0pt;text-align:justify;line-height:14pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="color:rgb(51, 51, 51);font-family:Verdana;font-size:10pt;"&gt;A l’occasion le P. Flavio Peloso, Directeur Général de la Congrégation de don Orione, a fait don au sanctuaire d’une précieuse relique de la croix de Jésus.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="margin:0cm 14.2pt 0pt;text-align:justify;line-height:14pt;"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign="top&amp;amp;amp;quot;"&gt;
&lt;div align="middle"&gt; &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Al'angle du mur</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1341056139"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-05T00:24:28</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54415032">MIKADEMADRID</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Trouvée en bon état. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1333527451"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-08T07:59:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54196179">Dave34109</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Trouvée en bon état. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1332685992"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-01T19:03:08</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="52295742">majosika</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">🤑</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1282806886"><groundspeak:date>2025-02-26T22:44:02</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25092969">svente86</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Vor 2 Wochen mit Frötschi gefunden</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1281279380"><groundspeak:date>2025-02-15T21:19:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="50963567">froetschi73</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nice place.
Thank you.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="18.470783" lon="-77.314467"><time>2002-02-07T00:00:00</time><name>GC3A2B</name><desc>Sea Rose Villa Cache by Kat</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC3A2B</url><urlname>Sea Rose Villa Cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="14891" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Sea Rose Villa Cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Kat</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1937">Kat</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="65" inc="1">Yard (private residence)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Jamaica</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>The hard part is just getting there.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The cache is on our property, Sea Rose Villa, in Jamaica. The cache contains some cards, stickers, a croaky, tire patch kit, a knife, travel bug duck, Geocoin #053. Dave the caretaker is aware of the Geocache game and maybe waiting for you to show up with your GPS. I grabbed the travel bug from Snoqualimie Pass two days before I left. What a great contrast, from 8 feet of snow to 86 degrees.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Under some rocks, around a small tree, in the SE corner of the lot.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="802068302"><groundspeak:date>2018-09-09T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4716665">Der_Holzmichel</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Heute, am fünften Tag unserer Reise nach " Jamaica ", bei hochsommerlichen Temperaturen, während unserer abenteuerlichen " Inselrundfahrt ", hier, in diesem herrlichen Gebiet der Karibik, einen Zwischenstopp eingelegt und eine " größere Cachertour " unternommen.

So wollten wir auch sehr gern dem Cache " Sea Rose Villa Cache " einen Besuch abstatten.

Dank der genauen Koordinatenangabe kamen wir bei einer kleinen Wanderung zügig in das Finalgebiet, wo wir nach etwas Suchen den " Schatz " schnell finden und problemlos heben konnten.

Mit großer Freude durften wir uns muggelfrei in's " Logbuch " eintragen.
Achtung ! Logbuch sehr nass !!!

Sehr schöne und pfiffige Versteckidee.

Anschließend noch etwas die herrliche Umgebung genossen.

TFTC u. Danke für's Legen und Herführen an diese Stelle.

Nette Cachergrüße an den Owner vom Grünbacher Holzmichel mit seiner lieben Holzmichelin aus dem Vogtland / Germany.

Soeben sehen wir, dass dieser " Oldi - Cache " archiviert wurde !!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="799686444"><groundspeak:date>2018-09-04T11:55:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1937">Kat</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache is on private property.  The house is being sold and access will no longer be available.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="799686056"><groundspeak:date>2018-09-04T11:54:17</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1937">Kat</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache is on private property which we are selling.  Public access will no longer be available.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="796963251"><groundspeak:date>2018-08-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="20050280">Ariberna</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Mi primer caché en Jamaica.
Vaya pedazo container. Fui a correr una mañana a las siete menos cuarto y aproveché.
No lo pidude firmar, estaban muy húmedas sustres  bolsas.Lo dejé cabeza abajo en el árbol en dónde estaba bastante expuesto.
No había nadie por la zona, sólo un poco de ropa colgada.
No cojo ni dejonada. Había michos juguetes, pins cochecitos, etc pero húmedos y algo oxidados.
Gracias por esconder y compartir.
Jamaica en estado puro.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="791107385"><groundspeak:date>2018-08-03T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15700156">!FIA!</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">FIRST jamaican cache!! That makes 19 countries for me! Salz69 and I were vacationing close by and we asked a cabbie to bring us here and other stops. Found it with no problem.  TFTC!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="26.4394" lon="127.77925"><time>2001-02-03T00:00:00</time><name>GC1FB</name><desc>Maeda Point Cache by Joseph Eaton (adopted by Team_Maddocks)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1FB</url><urlname>Maeda Point Cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="507" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Maeda Point Cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Joseph Eaton (adopted by Team_Maddocks)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="6591474">Team_Maddocks</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Japan</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Okinawa</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This is the oldest active geocache in Asia (see Related Web Page above), but it is not the first cache ever on Okinawa. It is Okinawa's first cache revisited and maintained!
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
Come prepared for a steep climb and don't forget gloves, sturdy shoes and bug spray, shorts are not recommended. It is recommended to go around Low Tide, give or take a couple hours.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Even if your little ones can't make it to the cache, this is still a nice area to take a walk, go running, or just spend some time relaxing. So brings the kids, walk the dog. Pack a picnic and stop along the trail for lunch. The location is also popular with divers and swimmers with caves to explore from both the ocean side and from the land side.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Park at the Maeda Point parking lot and follow the paths to get started. At the parking lot, go along the trail following the SCUBA divers. When the divers start hiking down the stairs, stay right and follow the path past the building. The path continues on straight, but if you walk around the trees there is a narrow road. Follow that road to the apartment building. Follow the trail that starts up again at the apartment building. Take that path all the way till you see a cave-like path through the trees on the left. Watch your step down this path, especially if it's wet. I do not recommend taking toddler or very young children any farther, there are places on this trail that you will need to use both hands to hold on to ropes or climb on coral. Once you find the search area, you will need to climb, and the children will not be able to join you unless you give them a lot of assistance. At the cache location, you will be up inside, but you will have a view of the sky (obstructed only by tree like bushes) but your GPS signal will be reduced due to the high cliff face right next to you.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The container is covered so look sharp. Read the spoiler for more info. If you can not find this cache please log a DNF Did Not Find so we can check on it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Joseph said this would be one of many caches in Okinawa... How right he was!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are a lot of good pictures in the gallery from years past, but keep in mind this cache has moved due to tide &amp;amp; erosion of the rocks supporting the first location, so pay more attention to the pictures posted on the page itself&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;History lesson:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Originally started by Joseph Eaton, and in the same area, but moved slightly by Sojournen. It has been maintained by several local cachers. Originally this cache was a 1/1 but Sojournen moved the cache to a more difficult area.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thanks to the great cachers who help maintain this epic hide throughout the years..&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>[Hint two, this will help you put hands on cache] 
Once you find the starting place for your search (See Picture), as you're walking in from the sea look up and to the left for lots of sky. Yeah, it's up there. 

[Another Hint]
The two rocks covering the cache are tan, they are not as gray and weathered like the others.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1355412357"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7944223">Kupfergraf</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Taking a few days off and then to visit the oldest geocache in whichever country we’re visiting has become a tradition. This time, too, I had a travelling companion (not my chief of staff and love of my life), which meant we paid a bit more attention to art, culture, food and shrines. After a long stopover in Hongkong, including a day trip to Macau, we travelled via Okinawa and Yakushima, then on to the main Japanese islands from west to east. On the way back, we chose Seoul as our pre-final stop. 

It was exhausting, hot, chaotic, wet, sandy, windy, steep, exciting, salty, breathtaking, surprising, delicious, … basically everything a geocaching trip can offer. Many thanks to all the cache owners who, with their time and effort, laid a very solid foundation for this tour. Brilliant! Greetings from Saxony! Unfortunately, with so many caches, I can’t always write a personalised log. Most of them would have deserved one. We’ll be raving about this trip for a long time to come.

With a good plan and waypoints (parking at the dive centre is ideal), this cache is no problem at all. The gloves from 7/11 weren’t even necessary. Once there, the photos from previous loggers are a great help. It’s brilliant that this cache is still being maintained. A favourite is a must. The location is breathtaking</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1352786066"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-04T17:03:28</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25336212">gunnmutt</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Neat hike and lovely island history.
I think some storms have caused damages and a few of the ropes I would not trust. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354930298"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1884773">Consolador</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found during the third day of my three-day visit to Okinawa. As I investigated old caches at Okinawa yesterday, I found out that the oldest cache in Japan is this one. Therefore, I had to include Meda Point in today's itinerary. Other goals included OIST University, Cape Manzano, and an aquarium visit, and I also attempted an FTF at the T5 cache on the east coast.
As we woke up a little late, our first stop was brunch. Then we went to OIST University to see the clean rooms there with our friend who works there, followed by the Meda Point. We stopped near this cache, but I was not sure how to get to it. After a few seconds walking on the pedestrian, I realised that I had to go where I thought. I omit from my mind all the dangerous animals that might be there and descend that wet, slippery path to the beach. The place was really beautiful, so I enjoyed it a lot. I was just afraid that I wouldn't be able to find the cache. Photospoilers helped a lot not only with access but also with finding the cache. It was not as difficult as I expected, finally. Thanks for this Japanese "cache dinosaur" and FP+ for its maintenance.



</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1343264935"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-29T16:33:27</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="32732385">Cachinator_79</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The path to the cache is blocked off with ropes. It says do not enter.  Wondering if it’s unsafe or just one of the many random signs that get put up around here. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1337321008"><groundspeak:date>2025-12-09T16:07:57</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="38826759">Samurai6</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This was quite the adventure to claim. Parked at the Maeda overlook because of all the no parking signs. Paid 500 yen and walked. 4 to GZ. My friend Jaques whom I introduced to geocaching spotted the side trail to ground zone. Pictures helped greatly to get to where we needed to be as well as log from sasamichicken. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="49.248967" lon="-2.109533"><time>2002-12-15T00:00:00</time><name>GCB662</name><desc>Jersey number One by Tony, Steve, Dawn &amp; Joy.</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCB662</url><urlname>Jersey number One</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="46690" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Jersey number One</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Tony, Steve, Dawn &amp; Joy.</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="21916">CaptainAJ</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Large</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Jersey</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>On the Northern coast of Jersey, Channel Islands.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Suggest you park at Position N49 14.829 W002 06.683, From this carpark the coast path is well marked. The cache is just off the path but there is 230 wooden steps from the top of the cliff to the cache point. 
There are no ramps so wheelchairs or perambulators are a deffinite no no.

The views are well worth the effort.

3rd Sep 2009.
Cache maintenence carried out. Replaced the original container with waterproof ammo box.
Most of the contents water damaged so were removed.

First time we have visited in the summer and I congratulate all those who managed to find it in the bracken.

I have added a "Killer Clue" taken from the path. Use this in the last resort.

3rd September 2011.
A little cache maintenance, renewed the log books.
Cache box is dry, apart from the effort required quite easy to find.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Located at the base of a small tree.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1365039958"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T22:03:13</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7366365">cathnphiljones</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">260 odd metres didn’t seem far from the parking area but it wasn’t an easy treck. Lots and lots of steps down and then we had to clamber through the brakes before we found the cache. Log soon signed and we found our way back to the path using an easier route than the one we had come up by. Still though had to go up the 200 odd steps to get back to the car. Thanks for setting and keeping this one going.😁😁😁</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364429606"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T19:37:33</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="28236158">toulous1</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hiking from greve le lecq to rozel !
Weather is pretty good we are Lucky !  6 hours journey, and 25 km for Amazing landscape. We loved it.
Obsviously i manage to find some caches !
More than 20 years old that's amazing. Tree is not as little.
TFTC from France
1 FP</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364386950"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-30T16:42:34</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="27767238">SaSi1115</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Goog to find at low tide, thanks!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364387355"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7294760">Bitifean</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Gemeinsam mit Leofreund und Sharulfo gefunden. Merci</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364174971"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5092595">Leofreund</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Für einen Tag ging es heute für Sharulfo und uns nach Jersey, nachdem wir vor drei Tagen schon die Nachbarinsel Guernsey besucht hatten.
Uns standen rd. 11 Stunden zur Verfügung, die wir nach Kräften nutzten, um möglichst viele Cachearten zu finden 😎. Im Laufe des Tages kamen so etwa 75 Kilometer Fahr- und etliche Tausend Meter Laufstrecke zusammen, und am Ende waren wir ziemlich müde 😴.
Aber auch erfolgreich 😁!

Zum Terrain kann ich nur sagen: UFFF!

Es bedankt sich für diesen Cache bei CaptainAJ mit einem Gruß aus der Schwebebahnstadt 🚟 Wuppertal der Leofreund.

Mein Fund Nummer 13465 um 13:53.
Wir haben mit 'TeamW' geloggt,  und auch nicht unbedingt an letzter Stelle, sondern gerne da, wo andere eine Lücke gelassen haben.

Sharulfo and we spent the day in Jersey today, having visited the neighbouring island of Guernsey three days ago.
We had around 11 hours to spare, which we made the most of to find as many different types of caches as possible 😎. Over the course of the day, we clocked up about 75 kilometres by car and several thousand metres on foot, and by the end we were pretty tired 😴.
But also successful 😁!

As for the terrain, all I can say is: Phew!

Leofreund sends his thanks to CaptainAJ for this cache, along with greetings from the suspension railway city 🚟 Wuppertal.

My find number 13465 at 13:53.
We logged with 'TeamW',  and not necessarily at the very end, but happily wherever others had left a gap.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="30.328967" lon="35.4388"><time>2001-11-14T00:00:00</time><name>GC282A</name><desc>Petra by Steve (Licorice)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC282A</url><urlname>Petra</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="10282" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Petra</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Steve (Licorice)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="28262">Licorice</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="10" inc="1">Difficult climb</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Jordan</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Jordan's first geocache! This cache is located in Petra (Jordan) on a lookout above the Habees Crusader Fort and can be found on a typical day visit to Petra.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;img src="http://www.geckobeach.com/GPS/licorice01.jpg" width="240" height="180" alt="Petra Geocache" align="right" /&gt;The cache is well hidden within the rock formations of Petra. To reach the cache location you will have to follow the trail through the Siq, past the Treasury and Theatre and to the City. Once in the city there are a couple of trails leading to the cache location. The cache is hidden in a very nice lookout location with 360 degree views of Petra.
&lt;p&gt;The cache is located in a 500 mL plastic bottle named 'Petra 1'. Note that the use of GPS once near the site may prove to be difficult due to the overhanging rocks blocking satellite coverage.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Elevation is very important for locating this cache and the values can be found from previous finds listed below (they are encrypted). Also take a look at the photo logs to show the location of this cache from your starting point.in the encrypted spoiler below.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This cache can be found on a day trip to Petra as you must pass its location to visit the city or to climb to the Monastery.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;a href="https://www.geocaching.com/blog/2021/01/new-country-souvenir-jordan-with-geocache-of-the-week-petra/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.geckobeach.com/GPS/GOTW%20Large.jpg" width="883" height="300" alt="Geocache of the Week" align="right" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Cache is located at about nine hundred and ninety metres above sea level (about as high as you can go on the hill in this area) and is hidden in a hole covered with rocks.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1354335554"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-10T10:30:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="39929232">Randulinas59</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">🐘🦓🦒🦁🦏🐪🌸
Thank you! Merci! Grazie! Grazia fich! Obrigada! ¡Gracias! Efcharisto! Danke! Asante! Shukran! شكرًا لك
 🐘🦓🦒🦁🦏🐪🌸

The cache is in good condition, maybe next cacher can bring a piece of paper as logsheet is full.

Fotolog because I forgot the pencil.

1 TB out!
0 in!

In February 2023 we started our long-term travel through Southern and Eastern Africa then we shipped the LandRover to Oman to explore the Arabic Peninsula.
Sometimes we do Geocaching.
Thank you ALL for hiding caches and taking care of it. You ALL showed us interesting places and facts which makes travelling more interesting as we see and know things now not even mentioned in travelguidebooks.

Greetings from 🇨🇭 Switzerland 

www.randulinas.ch

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1350021999"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-19T19:48:14</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="36960046">JadedSpy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Was quite a climb but so worth it - incredible view I haven’t seen mentioned anywhere else! This is the beauty of geocaching, finding the hidden spots. Thank you for the cache! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1347744556"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-07T15:35:27</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54658945">Prairiewolf1</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it on 3/2/2026</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1347128035"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-02T16:43:41</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="51874746">Cmo123</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks!! Left travel bug CRWRI7</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1346885544"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-01T15:49:52</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="28058620">atelierolomouccz</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Really nice place with no other people around. We have a great time here 💜 thanks </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="49.8218" lon="73.107667"><time>2002-08-10T00:00:00</time><name>GC8E15</name><desc>Vladimir Saved by bjohanso</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC8E15</url><urlname>Vladimir Saved</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="36373" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Vladimir Saved</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>bjohanso</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="9477">GeoBrad</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Kazakhstan</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This virtual cache is located towards the outskirts of Karaganda, the second largest city in Kazakhstan, and gives a glimpse of a relic of Soviet Times.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The cache is a large statue of Vladimir Lenin and a reminder of the former status of Kazakhstan as a member republic of the USSR.  The statue was almost destroyed in the late 1990s, but was saved by remaining members of the Communist party in the city.  If you look closely you can see the hole under the left shoulder where they were going to put the dynamite to blow up the statue.  To log this cache send me a photo of yourself with your GPS in front of the statue. Note that the statue was moved around 2011 from the center of town to the outskirts. Thanks to some cache finders the coordinates are now updated as of 10/2014.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The statue is near the Lenin Theater.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1342566010"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="11363">Lord Cunning</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">14382 1/2 together with PaLaRunCa.
A 5days adventurous trip to Kutaisi GE, Astana KZ and Karaganda KZ.
228 km from our hotel in Astana to this virtual, Kazakhstan's oldest cache, by InDrive.
We enjoyed the trip with our driver who used to know his way to Karaganda.
2 caches found there, this virtual and a nearby EC.
TFTC and grtz from Belgium.
See also PaLaRunCa’s log and his added photos.

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1342564951"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10102634">PaLaRunCa</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Kazakhstan, our 82nd cache country, and we owe that entirely to the club of our hearts! 🇰🇿 💙🖤

At the end of August, I was sitting on the edge of my seat during the draw for the 2025/26 Champions League. When Kairat Almaty came out of the bowl and it soon became clear that it would be an away match, I did everything I could to be there! When Lord Cunning heard me talk about my cunning plan, he was immediately on board, another club supporter joining in! :) Because of the winter date and conditions, the match venue was changed to Astana, the furthest possible European away trip.

Our journey went via Kutaisi in Georgia to Kazakhstan, where we arrived on Monday evening at -20°C. After a few attempts to take a photo with our eyes closed, we both had local internet. :) We discovered the InDrive app, which would prove incredibly useful during our stay.

On Tuesday, well wrapped up against the cold, we went to explore the city: our event at the iconic golden Bayterek Tower, the multi-cache at the Defenders of the Motherland monument with its eternal flame, a walk along the Aqbulaq promenade beside the frozen river, and then an Adventure Lab in the old part of town. At lunchtime, we enjoyed a typical Kazakh meal. To finish the day, we returned to Bayterek to enjoy the beautiful view from the top over the many new buildings, often clad in gold. The sleeping guard with his baton next to the golden elevators never knew a thing. :)

And then, of course, it was time for the main reason we were here: the match against Kairat in the Astana Arena. We bonded with locals, supported our team, met great people, saw three Borats in real life, and we won 1–4! :) We even became famous worldwide: on the club’s Instagram, on camera several times during the live broadcast, in the highlights on the VTM news… they just couldn’t get enough of the Lord’s bear hat. 😂 To top it off, I was able to make a Kazakh boy incredibly happy with my blue-and-black scarf. Wonderful to see his little face light up. :) Amazing atmosphere, a European away trip at its very best, and definitely one to repeat! Now just hoping for another interesting draw. ;)

We stayed an extra day to drive to Karaganda on Wednesday. Janibek took us exactly where we needed to be, to the Lenin statue. Google Translate did its job, so we were never truly lost in Russian translation. The obligatory selfie, and in this case a “lordie” too, with Lenin earned us our 55th oldest cache!! 😀 We also visited the earthcache about iron ore at the mining museum. After a coffee in the local mall and a visit to the Orthodox church, we headed back to the new capital. The end of a fantastic four-day trip!

When two hobbies and passions come together… Club Brugge meets geocaching, this was our trip to the land of the Golden Sun and the Steppe Eagle! 💙🖤 🇰🇿

Thanks, Dirk, for the great company and the many, many, many stories. 😂 You really should have tried the horse milk too…

Of course, thanks as well to all cache owners for making our hobby vibrant!

Tftc bjohanso!

Discovering our world one box at a time! 🌍 #33165

Rating when found: D1.0/T1.0

Feel free to discover the trackable on our gc profile! 🐒🦍</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1347454233"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-19T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4471472">Just75</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I really like virtual caches.
They are usually not very demanding, you don't have to spend hours and hours there, you don't have to drive dozens of kilometers, and yet you will see and remember places that you would never have known without these caches.
Thank you very much and I will give you a point.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1261612113"><groundspeak:date>2024-09-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25319695">Skat17</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Тайник взят. Спасибо. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1241487795"><groundspeak:date>2024-06-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2852634">Rumtreiber67</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Zusammen mit Postfranz auf Kasachstan Fahrt diesen schönen Virtuellen besucht. Vielen Dank und herzliche Grüße vom Rumtreiber aus Braunschweig, Deutschland.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="0" lon="36"><time>2000-06-15T00:00:00</time><name>GC53</name><desc>Rift Valley by Hans-Georg Michna</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC53</url><urlname>Rift Valley</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="83" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Rift Valley</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Hans-Georg Michna</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="44136">hgmichna</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="0">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="53" inc="1">Park and grab</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="0">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="0">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="46" inc="0">Trucks/RVs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="58" inc="1">Fuel nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="38" inc="0">Campfires</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="29" inc="0">Telephone nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="62" inc="1">Seasonal access</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Kenya</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;p&gt;One of the earliest virtual geocaches and perhaps the first on the equator. Certainly the first documented confluence on the equator, but this geocache already existed before the word confluence became common.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Located on a large plantation, it is relatively easy to reach with an off-road-capable car when it is dry, but plan at least 1½ hours altogether from the main road.&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;Due to the people who live and work in the area it is not possible to actually stash away anything. So this became the first virtual geocache. You have to provide at least one convincing photo to prove that you were there.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The access description is no longer matching reality, so I have deleted it. Please read the latest log entries for news and information. The following text may no longer be correct.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The place is on a large plantation that grows sisal or other crops. The &lt;b&gt;N 0° E 36°&lt;/b&gt; spot is exactly on the eastern side of a canal that runs through the plantation in a roughly SE-NW direction. If there is water in the canal, then is just a tad too wide to jump over (unless you are a well-trained jumper), so to reach the place from the main Nakuru-Baringo road you have to cross the canal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Do not enter the sisal fields without permission. Ask the people who work there. They are usually friendly and helpful.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align:center;font-size:88%;"&gt;&lt;img src="http://michna.com/gps/images/dscf7856.jpg" width="640" height="480" alt="Looking from the cache position southeast along the canal (2015)" style="border:1px solid black;" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Looking from the cache position southeast along the canal (2015)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align:center;"&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.google.com/maps/d/edit?mid=zlWdSXsrL-tQ.kXMFlWysCRyU&amp;amp;usp=sharing"&gt;Map of the the probably easiest approach&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="http://michna.com/gps/n0e36.gpx"&gt;GPX waypoint and track&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="http://michna.com/gps/n0e36.kml"&gt;KML waypoint and track&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first 30 visitors have been entered into the virtual logbook for that stash and published on my Web site &lt;a href="http://michna.com/gps/#Virtual_Geocache_on_the_Equator"&gt;http://michna.com/gps/#Virtual_Geocache_on_the_Equator&lt;/a&gt;. That list ends 2025, so all subsequent finders can be found in the log at geocaching.com .&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please post a few photos. The place can change rapidly and we want to know what it looks like now.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Warning: The geocache may become difficult to reach by car when it has rained a lot. You may have to walk the last, possibly muddy bit of the way in suitable boots. Consider skipping this cache during the height of the rainy season, usually around April (the long rains) and, to a lesser degree, around October (the short rains).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are already quite a few log entries, but not all of the people have found the actual cache. Some only drove by on the main Nakuru-Baringo road. This is still nice, but does not count as a find. Finding the cache is a bit more involved.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Nearby destinations possibly worth visiting&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Naivasha"&gt;Lake Naivasha&lt;/a&gt; – several hotels, lodges, and other interesting places.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Nakuru#Lake_Nakuru_National_Park"&gt;Lake Nakuru National Park&lt;/a&gt; – a lake with flamingos and pelicans. There are a few lodges inside the park.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Bogoria_National_Reserve"&gt;Lake Bogoria National Reserve&lt;/a&gt; – another lake with flamingos and pelicans. One relatively luxurious lodge.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Baringo"&gt;Lake Baringo&lt;/a&gt; – a lake with over 500 bird species above and around. One small lodge and camp site with a nice restaurant: Roberts' Camp. Other hotels and lodges nearby. Boat rides available.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hans-Georg&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1360992099"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5909880">SimmyJellers</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I thought my days of finding year 2000s were over. But here I stood. I cannot believe the emotions that overcame and overwhelmed me for no reason at all. no short logs, character limits stink. i'll do my best.
I’m used to traveling by packing up my campervan and letting it lead me wherever I need to be. This time meant throwing everything in a duffel and getting on a plane for what felt like 100 hours to Africa. Wifey planned a return after a trip 13 years ago went a bit sideways. She was here about 10 days before me, and I flew into Johannesburg, then on to Victoria Falls where we met up for my amazing 2+ weeks in Africa.
Travel couldn’t have been smoother. I spent the night at the Johannesburg airport, wandered for the virtual and adventure lab, and found a traditional micro in the parking lot. The log was in disrepair, so I left a fresh one—hope that’s OK. Next morning, off to Victoria Falls to see my wife for the first time in a couple weeks.
A couple days at Victoria Falls Lodge felt like living on our own island. Sunrise and sunset boat rides, a trip to the falls, game drives, and incredible food and hospitality. The mist made visibility tough, but when it cleared, it was amazing. We did the falls stroll, taking photos and collecting nonsense for my silly hobby.
The Victoria Falls walk was one of my favorites. Also, today was the day “waterfall” finally clicked… water… falling. Duh.
This was just our meetup—our trip started after. Overnight in Nairobi, then off to the Maasai Mara. We’ve been to Africa before, but never experienced kindness like this. As a silly American tourist, I’m always grateful for how welcome the world makes me feel.
One game drive we got a flat tire in a mud puddle. I wanted to help, but was reminded that’s not how hospitality works.
Another day, I got to explain geocaching in 30 seconds—scavenger hunt, treasure hunt, hide and seek. Eyes lit up. Our guide stopped at a tree I somehow knew, I showed him my phone: 40 feet that way. We walked over, I pulled out something that had been there 10+ years, and his mind was blown. Followed by, “where’s the next one?!”
Now our guide is in, zigzagging the Mara looking for caches.
We saw the closest thing yet to a kill—three lions stalking a herd—but the herd got tipped off. Bad for tourists, great for the animals.
One morning we were out five hours trying to see everything and find hidden treasures in the Mara Triangle. We got one, missed one. But knowing treasures existed in his homeland made Stephen so happy, it made me even happier.
We found one at camp, missed another—he even offered me a shovel at GZ. I declined, but I have a feeling he goes back without me.
After the Mara, back to Nairobi and on to Nakuru. The ridgeline drive is something I’ll never forget. Next morning we visited the equator and Rift Valley. As Richard understood what we were doing, he got more excited. By the end, he had the app and wanted to play hide and seek too—another convert.
Rift Valley was my geocaching highlight—the one selfish day I asked for. I did not hitchhike there like one of the raddest dudes I’ve ever met, but I made it on my own two feet. Richard was incredibly kind and accommodating—having a local made all the difference.
Explaining why I wanted to stand on this exact spot… I told it so many times I don’t even understand it anymore. We saw the water swirl test—something I’ve known forever—but watching it spin different directions (and not at all) within 20 feet blew my mind.
On the plantation, a few people helped us reach Raza, who welcomed us and said we might not get all the way by car. When wifey said we were coming back I begged for this ridiculous side quest. Because she’s the best, it happened.
Side story: Richard got pulled over and nearly extorted. He stood his ground— but nobody got a bribe from him. He was pissed and said when you’re not guilty, there’s nothing to be afraid of. The officers sentence, “you are traveling with 2 white people and don’t have $10 to make this go away?”, will forever bounce in my head with great laughter.
After Kenya, on to Rwanda for the highlight. This time we trekked with mountain gorillas. I even got to swing on vines like and with the silverbacks!
Seeing the gorillas and golden monkeys is an unquestionable highlight of our lives together.
From Rwanda we headed home. 3+ weeks for her, 2 for me—felt like a lifetime lived. Few layovers. Germany was the most exciting. I had 5 hours to kill. I wandered. Security never said anything, until I was at control to get back inside. He asked why I wander around aimlessly so much. I had a built in excuse. I was lost, looking for the the macdonalds. I finally found a nice officer who helped, I had an friend also with layover right now. His name is Gio. 1 guy chuckled, because I tell such good stories, and the other guy was extremely german about it. then it was home. 
Thanks to everyone who helped me have the most amazing life imaginable!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355115193"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-14T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10674268">Nelsfam1512</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Learned about this amazing geocache GC53 when it was printed on one of my Snow Globe Treasures. Love seeing geocaches around the world in places I've never been, this game is truly world-wide! Congratulations to all the dedicated geocachers who have found Rift Valley!!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1353082198"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-16T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="11316765">Kiwi14DD</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Heute in den frühen Morgenstunden starteten wir als Team K26DD (meisine, TwoPaddlers, moxx80, predator1337 und Kiwi14DD) zum eigentlichen Ziel unserer Reise nach Kenia. Dem GC53. 

Nach langen Vorbereitungen und dem knüpfen einiger wichtiger Kontakte, waren die besten Voraussetzungen geschaffen, dass dieser Tag zu einem besonderen Erlebnis werden konnte. Obwohl das ersehnte Ziel nur etwas mehr als 200 km von Nairobi entfernt war, dauerte die Fahrt mehr als 5 Stunden, bis wir vor dem Tor der riesigen Agavenfarm standen. Zumal die letzten Kilometer über sehr unwegsames Gelände führten.

Da unser Guide bereits zum zweiten Mal innerhalb kürzester Zeit hier ist, wusste er genau, was zu tun ist und übernahm alle Absprachen. Es ist schon sehr von Vorteil, wenn man jemanden dabei hat, der die Sprache der Einheimischen beherrscht. Nach einer kurzen Wartezeit war es endlich soweit .. ein Mitarbeiter holte uns ab und begleitete uns auf der Fahrt durch die Farm. Was für ein wildes Abenteuer! Die letzten Meter ging es dann zu Fuß übers Feld und den Damm hinauf. So kamen wir unserem Traum immer näher. Die GPS Werte stets im Blick, wurden die Schritte bald kleiner, bis es endlich die ersehnten 00.000 anzeigte. Wir waren angekommen .. bei genau   0 N und 36 E.

Irgendwo im Nirgendwo standen wir da an einem völlig unscheinbaren Ort und konnten es kaum fassen. HIER IST DER ÄQUATOR!
Ein tolles Gefühl, diesen besonderen Ort und den ältesten Cache von Afrika besucht zu haben. Natürlich wurden zahlreiche Fotos zum  Nachweis für unsere Anwesenheit geschossen. Das beste was uns bleibt ist jedoch die Erinnerung an das besondere Erlebnis.

Wir danken ganz herzlich unserem Guide, der uns sicher durch das Verkehrschaos und über die wirklich verrückten Wege gebracht hat und sind gerne bereit die Kontaktdaten weiter zu reichen.

Auch dem Owner hgmichna gilt unser Dank, da wir durch seinen Cache dieses verrückte Abenteuer erleben durften und unser Hobby mit einem außergewöhnlichen Erlebnis bereichert wurde.
Liebe Grüße aus Dresden senden Kiwi14DD.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1351292271"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-16T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7418114">moxx80</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Während unserer einwöchigen Tour durch Nairobi und Kenia haben wir (twoPaddlers, meisine, kiwi14DD, predator1337, moxx80 =&gt; Team "K26DD") wirklich sehr viel erlebt und dabei Land und Leute kennenlernen dürfen. Die obligatorische Safari durch den Nairobi-National-Park war dabei der absolute Höhepunkt!

Der Besuch des GC53 war der eigentliche Grund unserer Reise nach Kenia. Heute waren wir von Nairobi aus nach über 5 Stunden Fahrt durch teils unwegsames Gelände und etwas mehr als 200 km endlich am Konfluenzpunkt N 00 00.000 / E 36 00.000 angekommen. Die anwesenden Mitarbeiter erwiesen sich als sehr kooperativ ... denn sie wussten, warum wir hier sind 😎! 

Es ist schon ein erhabenes Gefühl, den ältesten Cache von Afrika einen Besuch abzustatten, umringt von Agavenfeldern und Sisal-Farmen! Die hier entstandenen Fotos waren reichlich und auch ein "Äquator-Bierchen" durfte dabei nicht fehlen 🍻!

Vielen Dank an hgmichna für diesen tollen Cache an einem eher recht unspektakulären Ort irgendwo im Nirgendwo!

-----------------------

During our week-long tour of Nairobi and Kenya, we (twoPaddlers, meisine, kiwi14DD, predator1337, moxx80 =&gt; Team "K26DD") had so many amazing experiences and got to know the country and its people. The must-do safari through Nairobi National Park was the absolute highlight!

Visiting GC53 was the real reason for our trip to Kenya. Today, after a drive of over 5 hours from Nairobi through partly rough terrain and a little over 200 km, we finally arrived at the confluence point N 00 00.000 / E 36 00.000. The staff on site were very cooperative... because they knew why we were there 😎! 

It is truly a sublime feeling to visit Africa’s oldest cache, surrounded by agave fields and sisal farms! We took plenty of photos here, and of course, we couldn’t miss out on an “Equator beer” 🍻!

Many thanks to hgmichna for this great cache in a rather unspectacular location somewhere in the middle of nowhere!

FP +1</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1346163915"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25219404">TrulliLOG</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The dream became reality. Three and a half years ago, I set about visiting as many old geocaches from the year 2000 as possible.

Of course, GC53 Rift Valley was one of these 112 active geocaches, and also the only one on the African continent. I read a lot, studied the old logs, and knew it would be better to have someone with me on the way to this trip who knew a bit about the area and, especially, spoke the local language.

A year passed, then another, and after I couldn't wait any longer, I decided to embark on the trip in October 2025.

By a bit of luck, I managed to get an address in Nairobi, and that's when the planning began. The date was set for the end of February, and the plane landed on time at 1:45 p.m. Immigration was very quick, and then the excitement began to build.

Who would be there to pick me up? In front of the airport gates, I saw several guides and my name on a pager. Perfect, that worked out well.

After some small talk, we set off for our first overnight stay at Lake Elementita.

After a relaxing night and a good breakfast, we set off for Mogotio, feeling refreshed. From there, we followed the new route.

Two years ago, I had serious concerns about how to cross the river, but now it's really no problem at all.

We drove along the private road to the gate and were greeted by the locals.

I was already the third geocacher this year, and the destination is well-known.

A phone call to the landowner gave us the go-ahead to drive the last 2.5 km.

The surroundings here seem to change monthly at the moment. While the last visitors to GC53 were able to drive to within 50 meters, our trip ended in front of freshly plowed soil 350 meters from Ground Zero.

Now I'm so close to the goal that the last few meters don't matter anymore. Our guide from the gate had fun with me and accompanied me all the way to the zero point.

We actually reached it; at first, we thought it was in the small river, but that was off by about 3.0 meters. Back up the hill, we moved in 10.0 cm increments until the GPS finally registered the hoped-for 00.0000 and 36.0000. I quickly snapped a photo as proof, and then came the great relief. Mission accomplished.

Back at the car, my guide was waiting and had filmed a great video and congratulated me on reaching GC53 Rift Valley.

It's a truly amazing feeling to be the 65th geocacher to visit this place in 26 years. I've often wondered why there aren't more visitors; it's such a fantastic experience in a very exciting country, Kenya. I'm almost certain I'll visit this country more than once.

A huge thank you to Hans-Georg Michna; without this fascinating place, I might never have gotten to know this exciting country.

I can only add one favorite to this trip; it deserves hundreds and hundreds of favorites.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="3.8575" lon="-159.359933"><time>2004-02-18T00:00:00</time><name>GCHRJB</name><desc>Where is Fanning Island by Team Fanning/MrGrubstake</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCHRJB</url><urlname>Where is Fanning Island</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="118960" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Where is Fanning Island</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Team Fanning/MrGrubstake</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="17148">Jennifer&amp;Dean</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="1">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Kiribati</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;font color="blue"&gt;&lt;big&gt;This is an easy cache for those fortunate
enough to find themselves on Fanning Island in the Republic of
Kiribati near the equator and almost 1200 miles south of Hawaii.
NCL does not call here any more and the sign post is now gone. But
it is easy to see where the sign post used to be.&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/font&gt;</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;font color="red"&gt;&lt;big&gt;In order to claim credit for this cache you
must send me a photo with you (and your GPS) in front of where the
sign post used to be! Do NOT post the photo - Send to
Jennifer.Dean.Cache@gmail.com .&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="red"&gt;&lt;big&gt;Please also take the time to write about
your visit to Fanning - about the people you saw and met, about
their culture they shared with you and your impressions. Enjoy your
visit on this idyllic atoll far out in the Pacific Ocean. Be sure
to take the time to visit with the people and learn about
them.&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="red"&gt;&lt;big&gt;I DO encourage you post as many pictures
as you might want to of the island and the people.&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="red"&gt;&lt;big&gt;Also, if you anticipate your travel to
this island and are able to - take some paper and pencils and any
other school supplies that the school children might be able to use
(books included).&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;small&gt;&lt;font color="black"&gt;Please, if you did not actually go to
this island - do NOT log this cache! I will be checking very close
for any attempts to log this cache without a
visit!&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1330104031"><groundspeak:date>2025-10-14T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="193287">GeoScavenger</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Tabuaeran - what a jewel. For those who appreciate the simple life and lack of technology this is a place to visit. No running water, no electricity thatched huts, cooking fires, the occasional small solar panel and led light.  We spoke to many wonderful residents, watched school kids sing and dance for HOURS,  during our cruise ship stop, bought beautiful hand crafted items, and even though we were first off the ship and last to leave the island it just wasn't long enough. 

Holland America is now the only cruise line that makes occasional (once a year)  stops here as part of their lengthy south pacific cruises and, according to many return visitors on the ship, is only able to land guests about 25% of the time... so we feel both lucky and blessed to have had the visit.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1162494961"><groundspeak:date>2023-04-26T23:03:49</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="17148">Jennifer&amp;Dean</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Were is Fanning Island was transferred from MrGrubstake to user Jennifer&amp;Dean</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="893719916"><groundspeak:date>2019-11-11T11:39:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="348486">diveduo</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">What a great stop this was!  Remote and beautiful place. Many smiling faces, young and old. Group singing at the dock and lots of tables out with the pretty shell jewelry that they make. I picked up a few things to help them out and as keepsakes. Walked all the way down to the school where some of the kids were in class.  Picture sent to CO.  Thanks so much for this cache!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="839383159"><groundspeak:date>2019-03-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4130928">rangerhal</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Visited this cache off of the Eurodam. An email was sent with a picture on April 7th after returning to the land of data. The  passengers and crew delivered over 50 boxes of supplies. Rained off and on but it was warm and gave us a chance to share shelter and visit with the islanders. We had fun wandering around the island. This is now my westernmost cache!  Thanks for the cache! Gets a favorite point.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="681642387"><groundspeak:date>2017-04-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2308096">AlpineTravelers</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found while cruising on Holland America Maasdam. Weather was stormy when we arrived, lots of squalls during the day. The weather did not stop the entertainers or the locals from coming out to greet us. Many handcrafted items were for sale and many items were purchased. we brought school supplies and dropped them off  at the school house and talked to some of the students. Life is very primitive from our standards but the locals seem happy with their life. Glad we made this port. tftc         </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="29.348183" lon="47.542267"><time>2006-08-24T00:00:00</time><name>GCXVTJ</name><desc>Welcome To The Rock by herk_cachers, Hey_Nav &amp; HerkRx</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCXVTJ</url><urlname>Welcome To The Rock</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="448807" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Welcome To The Rock</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>herk_cachers, Hey_Nav &amp; HerkRx</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="234732">herk_cachers</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Micro</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="1">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="0">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="1">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="38" inc="0">Campfires</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Kuwait</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;p class="MsoNormal"&gt;
&lt;span style='font-size:16.0pt;font-family:Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'&gt;
A quick easy micro with a great view. (Bring your own
pen/pencil.)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p class="MsoNormal"&gt;
&lt;span style='font-size:16.0pt;font-family:Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'&gt;
Nicknamed “The Rock,” Ali Al Salem Air Base is an important and
busy hub for peacekeeping operations in the Middle
East.&lt;span style='mso-spacerun:yes'&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; This micro is
located near a plaque and tribute to the joint operations
originating from here every day.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="MsoNormal" align="center" style='text-align:center'&gt;
&lt;img width="592" height="384"
src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/ad09542c-0974-4d34-a19d-6847889ef7e0.jpg"
     v:shapes="_x0000_i1026" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="MsoNormal"&gt;
&lt;span style='font-size:16.0pt;font-family:Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'&gt;
On 6 May 1997, after several months of negotiations, the flags of
the United States and Kuwait flew together for the first time over
this base in central
Kuwait.&lt;span style='mso-spacerun:yes'&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; It’s daily
mission – to support troops in harms way.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="MsoNormal" align="center" style='text-align:center'&gt;
&lt;img width="600" height="224"
src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/4c4a8035-90b1-41d9-8b9e-690bff1f0803.jpg"
     v:shapes="_x0000_i1025" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="MsoNormal"&gt;
&lt;span style='font-size:16.0pt;font-family:Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'&gt;
The weather here is consistently hot, so please be careful when
retrieving the cache as there are many metal parts in the
area.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="MsoNormal" align="center" style='text-align:center'&gt;
&lt;span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'&gt;
&lt;a href="http://www.wunderground.com/global/stations/40582.html?bannertypeclick=big2"&gt;
&lt;img src="http://banners.wunderground.com/weathersticker/big2_both_cond/language/www/global/stations/40582.gif"
     border="0" alt="Click for Kuwait, Kuwait Forecast" height="60"
     width="468" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
&lt;span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'&gt;
&lt;span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana; mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'&gt;
&lt;font size="1"&gt;Small note on cache maintenance: Hey_Nav and HerkRx
will assist. Thanks.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Weather beating you down?  Sit and take a break.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1351385085"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2340443">DisaV</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Жарко там сейчас, наверное.
https://t.me/parstodayrussian/200133</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1339244670"><groundspeak:date>2025-12-26T17:39:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">

