&lt;h2&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=844e18f8-94a5-4c5a-b69d-04ad1db8e725"&gt;Pith Helmet&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Behind a tree under rocks about 1.2 meter up from the walk way.
</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1029463552"><groundspeak:date>2021-06-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1051604">hennieventer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Any can help to replace because of covid I can not do.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="850067373"><groundspeak:date>2019-05-18T02:24:40</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1051604">hennieventer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Lets archive for now</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="836853681"><groundspeak:date>2019-03-28T21:41:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The cache appears to be in need of owner intervention. I'm temporarily disabling it, to give the owner an opportunity to check on the cache, and take whatever action is necessary. 

Please enable your cache by selecting enable on the right hand side of the listing , once the cache has been replaced/repaired, or checked that it is still in situ.

The [Geocache Maintenance guideline](http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) explains a CO's responsibility towards checking and maintaining the cache when problems are reported. Caches that have been archived for lack of maintenance will not be unarchived. This is explained in the [Help Center](http://support.groundspeak.com//index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=70)

**Please respond to this situation in a timely manner (i.e., within 30 days) to prevent the cache from being archived for non-responsiveness. If you plan on repairing this cache,but cannot get to it within 30 days, please log a note to the cache page (not email) to let the community know**

Knagur Green
Groundspeak Volunteer Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="834402648"><groundspeak:date>2019-03-17T13:18:16</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25596405">Jowelma_Gil</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I can’t find this cache,and the place is very dirty.
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="832393373"><groundspeak:date>2019-03-03T23:14:10</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="390665">jennergruhle</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This geocacher reported that the cache might be missing.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="21.1613" lon="94.8579"><time>2003-04-06T00:00:00</time><name>GCFA5A</name><desc>Mingalazedi View (Myanmar/Burma) by ooga booga</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCFA5A</url><urlname>Mingalazedi View (Myanmar/Burma)</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="64090" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Mingalazedi View (Myanmar/Burma)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>ooga booga</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="68818">ooga booga</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Myanmar</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>An easy virtual cache at a location that provides a spectacular
sunrise/sunset view over the surrounding countryside.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.groundspeak.com/cache/ec6fe0a2-5b8d-41df-89db-31e46e3e973d.jpg"&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Mingalazedi View&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;/center&gt;
The ruins at Bagan, in west-central Myanmar, are truly one of the
wonders of the world. By some accounts, there are over 4,000
temples, pagodas, and shrines scattered around the dusty plains
here, ranging in age from over 1,000 years old to still under
construction, and in size from a garden shed to huge fortresses.
They're one of the scenic highlights of Asia, if for no other
reason than the scale, yet Bagan is quite obscure compared to other
Asian architectural wonders like Angkor Wat or the Taj Mahal. 
&lt;p&gt;This virtual cache is located at Mingalazedi, a stupa built in
1277 at the end of the golden age of monument-building in Bagan.
It's one of the few structures you're still allowed to climb on in
the area, and it provides a great view at sunset of the surrounding
pagodas as they catch the last rays of the sun, and at sunrise when
the rising sun casts them in silhouette. It's also much less
visited than Pyathada, a nearby pagoda that's also a popular sunset
spot. This is a virtual because this temple is part of a UN World
Heritage Site, and to me it seems inappropriate to place a physical
cache near a potentially fragile, 800-year-old stupa.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.groundspeak.com/cache/de8c525a-0096-43f4-b64a-0d33c74cda75.jpg"
     align="left"&gt;&lt;strike&gt;Once you make the short but steep climb
     to the coordinates, you'll find a sign. For verification of
     your visit, email me what that sign says. Don't post your
     answer in your logs, even if encrypted.&lt;/strike&gt; EDIT: Well,
     it seems that climbing on the stupa is now forbidden. That's a
     huge bummer! Instead of climbing to the now-inaccessible sign,
     you can claim this cache by getting as close as you
     &lt;i&gt;legally&lt;/i&gt; can to the posted coordinates at taking a photo
     of yourself with your GPS.&lt;b&gt;Good luck!&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;IMPORTANT NOTE: The government of Burma is known to have
problems respecting the human rights of its people, and as a result
some have called for a boycott of tourists. If you do visit, I urge
you to travel responsibly, and most importantly, keep your eyes,
ears, and mind open as you're travelling around.&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1355401885"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-16T16:41:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1351184">SeekerSupreme</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Yes, it’s fenced and padlocked. The closest I could get to it was 28 m, which isn’t bad.  So many pagodas and stupas amount, I already lost count. Thanks for this virtual cache, my first find in Myanmar.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1259320537"><groundspeak:date>2024-09-11T11:30:23</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="29102498">cianfrusaglie76</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">La nostra mascotte è atterrata proprio davanti la Pagoda e per poco non rimaneva dentro il recinto a protezione di questo bellissimo luogo......
Prima di arrivare qui a Bagan i miei ricordi tornano verso Kakku, un luogo molto isolato ma molto mistico per la presenza di un sito affascinante!!!!
La MIKY ed io abbiamo immortalato quei piccoli e grandi Stupa con centinaia di fotografie e riprese da ogni angolazione possibile....
Una campanellina è stato il nostro souvenir......
A Pindaya la grotta dei Buddha ci ha fatto ricordare una puntata di Pechino Express....
I giorni a Mandalay sono stati intensi!!!
Grazie al nostro taxi-driver P. che non scorderemo mai (grazie per la dedica sil diario, P.!!!) abbiamo visitato tutto quello che c'era da vedere in questa splendida città e oltre.... Ci ha accompagnato fino ad Inwa e a vedere il ponte in teck ad Amatapura... Direi una brava persona ed un accompagnatore preparato!!
Infine qui a Bagan ci siamo innamorati del posto e dei suoi tempi e Pagode sparsi nella piana...
Li abbiamo visitati quasi tutti, grazie all'affitto di una e-bike e ai nostri... scarponi da trekking!!
A forza di stare scalzo nei vari siti religiosi qui ho veramente lasciato i miei scarponi e sono tornato in albergo scalzo….....!!!!!!!
Ci è mancato il volo sulla mongolfiera, ma sarà per il prossimo viaggio....</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1258601297"><groundspeak:date>2024-08-10T16:35:09</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="567157">Tommy_Laura</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">One week ago, we landed back in Mandalay and retuned back to the place we currently call home. After half a year of planning, we managed to make plans come true, and bring a family member with us. Laura and I have been living in Myanmar for a year now and it really isn’t often that someone gets a visitor, so we were already feeling quite special. After an enjoyable summer traveling through six countries before returning to Myanmar for the next year of our deployment. We had a little bit of relaxation at the beach in neighboring Thailand, before we flew back to Mandalay. A couple of days on the ground and getting back in the headspace of work, we were excited for the long-planned trip to visit the ancient city of Bagan. We knew we couldn’t travel far or wide, but we are one of the last in our group who have still not visited this area, and we finally made that come true this weekend. Laura organized the trip with our trusty (for security reasons) unnamed guide, who we know for a year now and knew he could show us the best of the best. Coupled with my curiosity and deep dive into geocaching history, we were sure to plan the maximum out of this trip. As I keep repeating, there have only *ever* been 77 caches published in the country we currently call home, and so when we moved here I knew geocaching would mostly die as my main hobby. Since the coupe, nearly every single cache fell into dismay as tourists, economic prosperity, and hope left the country. Yet, here we are, still with a sliver of hope.

We left work the moment we could, and after a relatively exhausting five hour drive, made it to our hotel for the night. As we were traveling with our accomplice and knowledgable guide, we called it a night, and got some much needed shuteye. Saturday however was the day for action. This was our only full day in the capital of the old buddhist empire, and with geocaching in mind, it was our time to explore places known and unknown in this sacred landscape. I had indirectly found a way to put every cache &amp; waymark in the area on our itinerary, and was excited to get going today. As we continued exploring Bagan today, we unsurprisingly found that we were pretty much the only tourists here, apart from the few domestic tourists wandering the area. Neither of us expected the sights we would encounter; endless pagodas, stupas, monasteries and chapels littered the area nearly more than the plastic trash blowing in the winds. History here was endless, and we were fortunate enough to to be traveling with someone knowledgable who could give us the hidden insight. 

We were crisscrossing the area after our lunch, the ladies decided to go for a short break to the hotel pool, while I continued to see as much of the area as I could in our short time here; this Mingalazedi View (Myanmar/Burma) stash was my eighth geo-stop today. As unique as things can get, this is the only virtual cache ever published in the country, as well as the oldest active one in the country; which was an excitement all in itself. But as past members have mentioned, even before the coup, the area was closed to preserve its archaeological integrity. When my companion and I arrived to the site, we took off our shoes and got as close to the massive structure as possible, passing a caretaker. After the archeological rules were put into place, this site is maintained by a local gatekeeper, who (controversy arises) waters these historically dry lands. But the closest we could get was next to **the barbed wire, which runs the perimeter of the stupa**. It was, even with the barricades and barbed wire, an incredible view and a testament to the old civilization. I snapped a photo of our nick at the location at 4:35 PM, making this our 7426th overall find, as today’s eighth of ten visited stashes along with eleven of the thirteen local waymarks. I snapped several photos around and took in the wonderful sights here, after which we talked about the history, old and recent, and continued our journey in the car. Thank you ooga booga for brining us here on this wonderful Saturday; it’s a shame that a magical and beautiful place like this is sealed off from the world, and the region which lived off of tourism has dried. We wish the best for Myanmar during our short two year tenure here, and hope others are able to visit and experience this unique land. Greetings from two expats calling Myanmar home, with another life changing experience visiting this unique area.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1194681172"><groundspeak:date>2023-09-13T23:31:51</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="44235810">simicatch</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Culer geokesch </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1146957548"><groundspeak:date>2023-01-31T17:12:23</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="33986018">Tracertjie</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Pagoda us gated from access. Got as close as I was allowed.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-24.748633" lon="15.335067"><time>2001-09-20T00:00:00</time><name>GC21C1</name><desc>Hiddenvlei by aapje</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC21C1</url><urlname>Hiddenvlei</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="8641" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Hiddenvlei</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>aapje</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="25120">aapje </groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Namibia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This cache is placed in the sand dunes of the hiddenvlei, part of the sossusvlei area. You walk a part of a trail through sand dunes to a viewing point. After that your on your own. You need a car to get to the car park, from the sesriem office approx 75 minutes drive. Walk from the car park to the vlei and back approx 5 km. Without searching for the cache this will take approx 2 hours. Through red sand dunes and burning sun (take enough water with you)
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div align="center"&gt;
&lt;table border="0" width="590" height="1" bgcolor="#FFCC00"&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td width="590" height="1" valign="top" align="center"&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font face="Comic Sans MS" color="#000000" size="4"&gt;Save Namibia’s oldest cache!!&lt;br /&gt;
The cache needs a container, the old one (renewed in 2013 is broken)&lt;br /&gt;information 28-10-2025&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&lt;font color="#800000"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
The cache is hidden in an outstanding area.&lt;br /&gt;
You need to inform yourself about whether conditions before visiting, and take lots of water with you.&lt;br /&gt;
Apearently seasons and whether conditons make a big difference in this area. &lt;br /&gt;
I have heard peoply where not be able to even get close because of heat but also because of waterfloods.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&lt;font face="Comic Sans MS"&gt;&lt;font color="#800000" face="Comic Sans MS"&gt;The cache needs a new container, please save the oldest cache in Namibia, it was renewed by Andre as for 25-10-2013 he placed an official Geocaching lock and lock container, thanks ...But due to whether conditions and 12 years of service, this container has gone, and only a plastic bag remains&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;font face="Comic Sans MS"&gt;***************************************&lt;br /&gt;
Information updated today 28-10-2025&lt;br /&gt;
***************************************&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363105620"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-13T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="19874898">Maxiiik</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nájdená v rámci dobrodružnej poznávacej cesty po Namíbii. Krátka zastávka cestou skrz krajinu.
Táto keška bola na mojom to-do liste čo by som chcel navštíviť. Napokon sa mi to podarilo, hoc som musel bojovať s nedostatkom času, takže som sem sem musel ísť veľmi rýchlo horúcou púšťou. Bolo to zaujímavé. Po príchode na miesto mi chvíľu trvalo identifikovať z fotiek miesto uloženia. Samozrejme že som hľadal na nesprávnej strane...

Visited on the adventure discovery trip through Namibia 🇳🇦
This geocache was one of my goals what to see/visit on my way.
It was not easy to handle it because of the lack of time, so I am very happy that I made it to go to the coordinates and find this oldest cache.

M&amp;M Vďaka za kešku / TFTC =)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357078380"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5513217">Sybmil</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thank you for leading us here.
Favorite point for the oldest one in Namibia </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360455347"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5847706">the6cachers</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Beim Besuch dieser Gegend war natürlich auch der Besuch dieses Caches eingeplant. Der Weg dahin war durchaus anspruchsvoll - Sand und viel Sonne. Hier lasse ich gerne einen FP.

TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354427404"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-11T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1873023">Tom &amp; Struppi</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Unbelievable it rained a lot. We replaced the paper against a container and hope we hide it very well. Look the picture.  
We came to search our 7000 cache. This is amazing the area and the oldest in Namibia.  Perfect for our special cache. Thanks forcreating and all Cacher  keep it. Best regards Katrin and Thomas</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362079809"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9396543">schillhoy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">During our road trip through Namibia, we visited Sossusvlei and this amazing Hiddenvlei. It’s a unique landscape that you simply have to see. Thanks for sharing!!!
Photo log!

Zu unserem Roadtrip durch Namibia besuchten wir das Sossusvlei und diese großartige Hiddenvlei. Eine einmalige Landschaft die man gesehen haben muß. TFTC!!!
Fotolog
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="27.99125" lon="86.83"><time>2003-05-23T00:00:00</time><name>GCG58G</name><desc>Kala Pattar by Boxi</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCG58G</url><urlname>Kala Pattar</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="70605" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Kala Pattar</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Boxi</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="65341">Boxi</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="0">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="0">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="0">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="0">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="53" inc="0">Park and grab</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="0">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="0">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="9" inc="1">Significant hike</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="62" inc="1">Seasonal access</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="43" inc="1">Livestock nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Nepal</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="6"&gt;Kala Pattar (5545 meters)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="http://boxitec.de/geocaching/bae.jpg" align="right" width="320" height="480" /&gt;On May 29, 1953, Edmund Hillary from New Zealand and Tenzing Norgay from Nepal became the first human beings to reach the top of Chomolungma (8848 meters) - called Mount Everest by the rest of the world.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This was about 50 years ago. In March 2001 we - Andi and me - did the 'Classic Everest Trek' from Jiri to Kala Pattar. This picture was taken a view hundred meters north of the summit of Kala Pattar. In the background you can see the Everest with its typical cloud.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To log this virtual cache you just have to enclose a similar picture to your posting. It should show you with the Everest in the background and if it is possible your GPS with your position. Maybe you could tell something about your hike, when you were there, how long it took you to get there, the route and so on.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Certainly I also accept all logs with pictures taken on the way from the basecamp to the summit of Mount Everest.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Enjoy your visit to beautiful Nepal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Boxi&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1354960814"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-12T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8231742">Beezee75</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I wanted to take my son on an epic adventure, and EBC is what he chose.  We found it challenging, and decided a helicopter down from Gorekshep was the best decision, BUT WE DID IT!  TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361812786"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-10T11:11:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13557135">endich</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">W piątek 10 kwietnia 2026 roku z powodów nie byle jakich odkryłem *sui generis loculus* - Kala Pattar (GCG58G).

--------

Namaste Nepal!
Kuzu Zangpo La Bhutan!

Found during my journey through Nepal and Bhutan.
Thanks for the fun!

--------

Thanks Boxi for the cache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1350830751"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-23T15:49:54</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7150193">smrtkid5</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Got to find this cache today in our hike to tbe top of the peak. So cool to get above 18000 feet. We had a really nice day but felt exhausted afterwards. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359028784"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-14T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13568709">waldaktiv</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A trip to Nepal. My first time on the Black Rock in 1992 🛘. 
Today, the same peaks still stand in the same place.
A magnificent, beautiful, and rugged landscape.
Thank you for this experience.

Reise in Nepal. 1992 zum 1. Mal auf dem schwarzen Felsen 🛘. 
Heute stehen immer noch die gleichen Gipfel am selben Ort.
Herrlich, schöne und strenge Landschaft.
Danke für dieses Erlebnis.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1336685311"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="220782">myshoes</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Made the EBC trek with Ian Taylor.  Quite a bit more challenging than I thought it would be; especially the Lobuche - Gorek Shep and final push to EBC.  The night before our final ascent Ferret and HowPow hiked Kala Pattar for the sunset.  Tough cookies those two.  TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="52.35565" lon="4.861733"><time>2001-01-21T00:00:00</time><name>GC198</name><desc>Amsterdam Urban 1 by Onwaarschijnlijk</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC198</url><urlname>Amsterdam Urban 1</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="408" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Amsterdam Urban 1</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Onwaarschijnlijk</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="2049">onwaarschijnlijk</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="26" inc="1">Public transportation nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="33" inc="1">Motorcycles</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Netherlands</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Noord-Holland</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>It's super awesome, it's Amsterdam Urban 1!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;Stay on the bridge, no need to climb to strange places.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Dear Geocachers, this is an urgent message from Onwaarschijnlijk:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4&gt;DO &lt;strong&gt;NOT&lt;/strong&gt; DROP STUFF INTO THE WATER&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And by STUFF I mean:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Cache&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Log&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;You (yes that did happen once)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you suspect that you are too clumsy or too stoned to handle the cache then get help or come back another time ;)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img src="https://img.geocaching.com:443/7f2a04e7-0372-4887-b6c7-32d1564a7a16.jpg" style="height:300px;width:200px;" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Happy hunting! :)&lt;/p&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Stick your head out above the water, look LEFT.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1365006942"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T19:30:27</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54909432">JUSTFORFUN130</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Structurally sound placement </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364961156"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T14:21:42</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9905865">A-team24</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings from the USA! Found with PezGremlin and this was our goal. That was super awesome! Tftc!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364955229"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T13:26:26</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54451033">NikMink</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nik&amp;Mink Found it THTC </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1365019737"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="32380140">Toschi80</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Gefunden...🤗....
Auch diese Dose konnten wir schnell entdecken und signieren...hier ist es sogar einen bisschen ruhig so das man problemlos suchen konnte...
Danke fürs herlocken und verstecken 👍 💪</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1365010588"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6494024">PezGremlin</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC! This old cache was the walking goal for today. A-team24 and I enjoyed exploring Amsterdam and this park. A nice and scenic spot for this old cache to be placed!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="12.108166666666667" lon="-68.25966666666666"><time>2001-12-30T00:00:00</time><name>GC316E</name><desc>Welcome to Kunuku-Land by The Mighty Penguins</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC316E</url><urlname>Welcome to Kunuku-Land</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="12654" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Welcome to Kunuku-Land</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>The Mighty Penguins</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="31293">Mighty Penguin/MAGX</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Bonaire</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Stay north of road. Lots of thorns and stickers. Very flat.  Very hot. Wear shoes!</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Welcome to Kunuku-land by the Mighty Penguins
&lt;P&gt;
Kunuku is Papiamentu for farm.  It is a land full of cacti and plants with thorns. The region is hot and the ground made of ironshore.  Wear heavy shoes unless you want to take thorns out of your feet. Long pants wouldn't hurt either. South of the road is private so keep off the salt company land, plus you don't want to disturb the flamingoes!  Please put the rocks back on top of the cache, otherwise the wild donkeys will disturb the container.  The plastic box contains the usual trinkets including a film container of Heinekenite, a man-made Bonarian gem (HA HA).  We penguins think this is the first geochache in Bonaire and the Antillies. Please watch your step, cacti ironshore and thorns abound. Look around for in this area are lizards, wild donkeys, goats and flamingoes
&lt;p&gt;
       Blue Skies
&lt;P&gt;
    The Mighty Penguin/MAGX</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Line up the yellow windmill with the northern radio tower.  Look for two very large cacti. The bush between them has the cache</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1362049961"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T17:28:51</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="20292518">Beeklust</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Einde middag lege duiklessen omgeruild en op de terugweg langs deze cache gereden.  Goed te vinden  . Dank je wel voor deze cache </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359808598"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-08T12:48:40</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="11259850">Spook007</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hier  moet je goede schoenen  aanhebben 
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1357670860"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="31704094">Deetje72</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">27 april 2026 12:27
13 TB -in 1 TB-out

Na de bruiloft van onze dochter op Wanapa moeten we natuurlijk ook cachen. We hebben veel TB's bij ons die graag achterblijven op het eiland. Het zou fijn zijn, als ze niet terug reizen naar Europa.

De cache was goed te vinden. Richt je op de juiste 2 grote cactussen en de plek is voor een goede cacher zo zichtbaar.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355169038"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-14T10:59:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8073872">Rieloon</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Leuk tochtje door de struiken! Steeds zoeken naar het juiste pad. TFTC! Owja dit is onze 1500e cache 😁🥳</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354649629"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-11T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5105270">Zascandiles</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">El primer caché de Bonaire nos descubre este ambiente tan hostil. Suelo complicado, plantas llenas de pinchos y agujas,... ¡Nos ha gustado mucho!

Además, el logbook original del 2001 continúa en el caché y es un gran testigo de su historia. 

Punto favorito,  sin duda 

Muchas gracias The Mighty Penguins por el caché y por mostrarnos este lugar.

Puedes seguir nuestras aventuras en Instagram: @geozascandiles

https://www.instagram.com/geozascandiles?igsh=dzlxemZ1ZDZhN2d0</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-21.178883" lon="164.888217"><time>2008-07-01T00:00:00</time><name>GC1E3EX</name><desc>Nouvelle Caledonie Premier Cache  by Nathan Giustizia</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1E3EX</url><urlname>Nouvelle Caledonie Premier Cache </urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="932820" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Nouvelle Caledonie Premier Cache </groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Nathan Giustizia</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="408310">goodlife101</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="0">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="0">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="0">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="10" inc="1">Difficult climb</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>New Caledonia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Approximately 7 km south of Pouembout. Parking is available at the base of the trail, near the VKP sign. The hike is about 4.5 km round trip, with a total elevetation of less than 400 m.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The hike takes you up an old mining road, and provides beautiful views of the lagoon from various look out points.  There are some steep and rocky areas so ensure you have proper footware for the hike.

We placed the geocache on Canada Day.  The cache contains a log book, Canadian coins, Canadian stickers, and several toys including a car, marbles, small note pads, stickers, and beaners.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Two steps more and you will start from ground floor.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1318363108"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-18T03:48:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="408310">goodlife101</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We no longer live on the area and the cache is missing</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1318362895"><groundspeak:date>2025-08-18T03:48:28</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="408310">goodlife101</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache is permanently disabled</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1283230381"><groundspeak:date>2025-03-02T14:06:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15189955">Cyril74360</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Ce géocacheur a signalé que la cache pouvait être absente.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1283230378"><groundspeak:date>2025-02-21T14:05:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15189955">Cyril74360</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">La boite n'est plus présente. Confirmé par un ami qui connaissait le lieu de la cache</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1200964776"><groundspeak:date>2023-10-15T14:30:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="47626407">LaurianeLbrd</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A priori au vu des commentaires, la boîte n’est plus la !</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-41.270556" lon="174.985667"><time>2000-05-26T00:00:00</time><name>GC46</name><desc>Geocache by Kevin Anderson (Wellington) by Kevin Anderson</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC46</url><urlname>Geocache by Kevin Anderson (Wellington)</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="70" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Geocache by Kevin Anderson (Wellington)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Kevin Anderson</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="303">wainuiomata</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="26" inc="1">Public transportation nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="37" inc="1">Horses</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>New Zealand</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>North Island</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>near Wainuiomata, New Zealand. White bucket.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363645089"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T15:36:33</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="47977698">RaeKaeFez</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Pretty special find. And I happen to be here on this big boi’s 26th birthday!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358439539"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5206885">totalh</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I was here after the meet and greet in Wellington. TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354660127"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-12T09:39:46</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5899593">Firebird71</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Richie and I are on a completely bonkers across the world trip for caching. We spent two days in Singapore 🇸🇬 before heading for New Zealand. 🇳🇿 We cached in the rain for two days here 🌧️ which we still enjoyed, before heading to visit Richie’s friends in Napier. We had a lovely time with them being shown around the sights. We also managed to introduce them to geocaching. 🤩 We were heading towards Wellington around now specifically to find this cache but now we have a second agenda… trying to keep ahead of/avoid Cyclone Vaianu. ⛈️ 🌀 

We parked up outside the gates last night in our camper 🚐 and set off for this cache after brekkie. It’s a very picturesque area but sadly the photos don’t come out so well on the gloom. We enjoyed our meander to GZ and the instant find of this golden oldie. I did some TB swaps before we headed back to the van. Fave point for sure! 💚

TFTC 😀 

Time 09:39

Find number 17704</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354696481"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-12T09:34:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="627866">oges518</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This is the pièce de résistance of our trip to New Zealand from the UK . We set off over a week ago and stopped off at Singapore before flying to Auckland to pick up a motor home. 
We made our way to Napier to meet an old friend of mine before heading down to Wellington last night and stayed in the lay-by by the locked gate. 
We got up in decent time this morning and headed to this one via the other two caches along the path and stopped to read the plaque about the now demolished houses. 

We couldn’t miss this one once at the Co-ords Love the ballast in this cache and the size of it , she ain’t moving anywhere  !! 

Prior to us this was on 666 faves so had to add another ❤️

Thanks to wainuiomata for the cache 
 
Find number - 12250

Time - 09:34:21 GMT+12

Day - Sunday




</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359777377"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-09T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9552311">Monkeycat0704</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**[DE]** 

Als Geocacher möchte man neue Orte, ferne Länder, interessante Gegenden und abenteuerliche Areale kennenlernen. Weiter weg von zu Hause als Neuseeland kommt man als Deutscher kaum; nicht nur deshalb stand dieses Land schon länger auf der Bucket List.
Durch die Ferienzeit des Nachwuchscachers war die verfügbare Zeit etwas eingeschränkt, sodass wir uns in diesem Urlaub nur auf die Nordinsel konzentriert haben. Mittlerweile wissen wir aber, dass wir dieses Land irgendwann noch einmal bereisen werden und uns dann die Südinsel vornehmen.
Neuseeland hat uns begeistert! Vor allem landschaftlich hat das Land einiges zu bieten. Außerdem ist es ein Traum für Geocacher, da die Cachedichte – verglichen mit anderen Ländern, die wir in den letzten Jahren bereist haben – außerordentlich hoch ist. Es gab viele interessante und lohnenswerte Caches zu finden; dies war einer davon.

**Aus Geocaching Sicht war das auf jeden Fall das Highlight der gesamten Reise! Noch genau 7 aktive Geocaches gibt es vom Geburtsmonat unserer geliebten Schnitzeljagd. Einer in Neuseeland, einer in Australien, der Rest in den USA. Deshalb war es ein absolutes MUSS diesen Cache hier zu finden. Am Abend fuhr ich alleine von Wellington los um diesen Cache zu suchen. Mir war nicht bewusst, dass sich dieser in einem Nationalpark befindet, der Schließzeiten hat. Am Eingang wurde mehrfach darauf hingewiesen, dass die Schranke Abends geschlossen wird und niemand mehr rein oder raus kann. Ich war ziemlich genau eine Stunde vor der Schließung am Eingang und hatte so etwas Zeitdruck. Zusätzlich war mir nicht bewusst, dass ich nicht ganz bis zu dem Cache vorfahren kann. So joggte ich vom Parkplatz aus und konnte den schönen Park gar nicht so sehr genießen. Natürlich war es kein Problem die schöne große Dose zu finden, es gan einen deutlichen Trampelpfad. Viel Zeit hatte ich nicht diesen besonderen Moment zu genießen, denn ich musste schnell wieder aus dem Park raus. Glücklicherweise schaffte ich es noch rechtzeitig aus dem Nationalpark und hielt dort kurz an, um mich zu sortieren und das Navi einzustellen. Kurz danach kam auch schon ein Parkranger, der tatsächlich das Tor hinter mir schloss. Viel mehr Zeit hätte ich mir nicht lassen dürfen.**

Vielen Dank für den Cache und beste Grüße aus Mainz, Deutschland

---

**[EN]**

As a geocacher, you want to discover new places, distant countries, interesting regions, and adventurous areas. As a German, it’s hard to travel much farther from home than New Zealand; not only for that reason, this country had been on our bucket list for quite some time.
Due to the school holidays of the young geocacher, the available time was somewhat limited, so on this trip we focused only on the North Island. However, we now know that we will return to this country someday and then explore the South Island.
New Zealand truly amazed us! The country has a lot to offer, especially in terms of scenery. It is also a dream for geocachers, as the cache density—compared to other countries we have visited in recent years—is extraordinarily high. There were many interesting and worthwhile caches to find; this was one of them.

**In the evening, I drove alone from Wellington to search for this cache. I did not realize the cache was inside a national park with closing hours. At the entrance, signs warned that the gate would close in the evening and nobody could enter or leave afterwards. I arrived about an hour before closing time and was under heavy time pressure. I also did not know that I could not drive directly to the cache, so I had to jog from the parking lot. The container was easy to find thanks to a clear trail. Unfortunately, I had little time to enjoy the moment because I needed to leave quickly. Luckily, I made it out just in time. Shortly afterwards, a park ranger closed the gate behind me.**

Thank you very much for the cache and best regards from Mainz, Germany.

---

**[MI]**

Hei geocacher, ka hiahia koe ki te kite i ngā wāhi hou, ngā whenua tawhiti, ngā rohe whakamere me ngā wāhi whakaihiihi. Mō tētahi Tiamana, kāore e tino taea te haere tawhiti ake i tō kāinga i Aotearoa; ehara i te mea nā tēnei anake, kua roa kē tēnei whenua e noho ana i runga i tā mātou rārangi wawata.
Nā ngā hararei kura o te geocacher taitamariki, he iti noa te wā i wātea, nō reira i tēnei haerenga i aro mātou ki Te Ika-a-Māui anake. Inaianei kua mōhio mātou ka hoki anō mātou ki tēnei whenua ā tētahi wā, ā, ka toro atu ki Te Waipounamu.
I tino whakamīharo a Aotearoa ki a mātou! He nui ngā mea ka taea e te whenua nei te tuku, otirā i te āhua o te whenua. He moemoeā hoki mō ngā geocacher, nā te mea he tino nui te kiato o ngā cache—ki te whakataurite ki ētahi atu whenua i toro atu mātou i ngā tau tata nei. He maha ngā cache whakamere, whai hua hoki i kitea; ko tēnei tētahi o aua mea.

**Nā te iti o te wāhi, tirohia koa te tuhinga Ingarihi.**

Ngā mihi nui mō te cache, ā, he mihi aroha atu i Mainz, Tiamana.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="11.9869" lon="-86.1663"><time>2003-05-08T00:00:00</time><name>GCG34E</name><desc>Masaya Volcano Cache by On the Brenk</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCG34E</url><urlname>Masaya Volcano Cache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Virtual Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="68557" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Masaya Volcano Cache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>On the Brenk</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="111517">On The Brenk</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Virtual Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Virtual</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Nicaragua</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>No hiking required.  You can drive right up to this fascinating view.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>This virtual cache takes you to an active volcano in Nicaragua's Masaya Volcano National Park.  You can see the steam rising from the crater and occasionally rocks and boulders are spewed out.

During the pre-Columbian age, Masaya Volcano was an object of veneration by the indigenous people.  They believed the eruptions were signs of anger from the Gods and to appease them they offered sacrifices, which often included small children and maidens.

Later, during the Conquest, the Spaniards baptized the active volcano "La Boca del Inferno" or "The Mouth of Hell".  They then planted a cross, "La Cruz de Bobadilla" (named after Father Francisco Bobadilla), on the crater lip in the 16th century in order to exercise the devil.

The volcano was visited by a number of Spaniards in search of "the gold of the volcano". Gonzalo Fernandez de Oviedo in 1529 and Friar Blas del Castillo in 1538 were among the unsuccessful excavators.

In 1670, the Nindiri Volcano made its last eruption followed by the Masaya Volcano in 1772.  The lava formed by this later eruption advanced like a river of fire to the area now known as Piedra Quemada or burnt rock.  In 1852, a new crater, Santiago, was formed between the two existing volcanoes.

To claim this virtual cache, go to the coordinates indicated and take a picture of yourself at the site with a GPS, then upload the picture with your log.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364689858"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:23:16</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="33520544">ConnieandRick</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On a trip from Mexico to Costa Rica. After an action packed day around Granada and Apoyo crater, this was the last activity of the day. Fantastic experience. My selfie skills after dark aren't great though. Greetings from Australia.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355914532"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-18T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1917872">gw0143</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I landed in Managua last night after flying from Suriname via Panama. First time in Nicaragua. Not many caches here... This cluster of three at the volcano seemed like my best bet to find a cache in Nicaragua, so I hired a driver via one of the local ride sharing apps (I used the one called Ray) and lucked out in that I got a not too aggressive driver who spoke decent English and was willing to wait for me to take me back or take me on further sightseeing adventures - we ended up driving all the way to Granada and I got to see that nice town as well. He also took the attached picture of me at GZ.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362460672"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7366439">Rezi73</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Im Team „Untappd-Reisen“ – bestehend aus coolekuh, jojo71_geo, jowo2003, Rezi73 und Virtualboy – führte uns unsere diesjährige Reise durch Zentralamerika. Dabei besuchten wir Panama, Costa Rica, Nicaragua, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, Belize und Mexiko.

Neben zahlreichen Sehenswürdigkeiten und beeindruckenden Naturwundern konnten wir unterwegs auch einige Geocaches entdecken und loggen.

Ein herzliches Dankeschön an alle Cacheowner fürs Legen und Pflegen der Caches – ohne euren Einsatz wäre dieses schöne Hobby nicht möglich.

Viele Grüße aus dem schönen Sachsen in Deutschland!
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358015659"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2552416">Virtualboy</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Unterwegs in Zentralamerika mit dem **Team Untappd**: coolekuh, jojo71_geo, jowo2003, Rezi73 &amp; Virtualboy

Auf unserer dreiwöchigen Tour durch Panama, Costa Rica, Nicaragua, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, Belize und Mexico besuchten wir viele beeindruckende Orte, lernen neue Länder und Gebräuche kennen, testeten die lokale kulinarischen Köstlichkeiten und auch das einheimische Bier.

Natürlich habe wir auch etwas Geocaching betrieben und dadurch schöne Locations entdeckt.

Dieser Cache war auch dabei. 

Vielen Dank sagt Virtualboy

in: nichts
out: nichts

Danke für den Cache - Thanks for that Cache- Merci pour la. Cache - Dzięki za Cache - Grazie per questo Cache - Takk for cachen - Obrigado por isso Cache - Gracias por el Cache - Díky za keš - Ačiū už tą talpyklą - Paldies par šo Cache - Aitäh selle eest Cache - Спасибо за то кэш - Kiitos, että Cache - Tack för cachen - Tak for denne Cache - Hvala cache - Ευχαριστώ για τη μνήμη cache - 感謝您的高速緩存 - Önbellek için teşekkürler - Köszönjük, hogy a cache - Bedankt voor de cache - Graças para o cache - Dankon pro la kaŝmemoron</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355037879"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15377839">coolekuh</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Vor uns lagen 3 Wochen Mittelamerika!
Im erprobten Team: jojo71_geo, jowo2003, Rezi73, Virtualboy und coolekuh waren die Ziele klar.
In 8 Ländern mindestens 1 Cache finden, möglichst viele Cachearten pro Land, die ältesten Caches wenn möglich, aber last but not least viele verschiedene Biere testen.
All dieses ist uns sehr gut gelungen und ich bin mit unserer Ausbeute sehr zufrieden.
Außerdem haben wir viel gesehen und ich bin überrascht wie unbesorgt und sicher ich mich in allen Ländern gefühlt habe.
Die 3 Wochen waren anstrengend, aber sehr sehr schön, mit vielen neuen Eindrücken im Gepäck und sehr glücklich blicke ich zufrieden zurück.
Allen Ownern ein herzliches Dankeschön.
Wenn Bei Caches Antworten erforderlich sind, schickt immer einer aus unserer Gruppe diese.

¡Nos esperaban tres semanas en Centroamérica!

En nuestro equipo de confianza —jojo71_geo, jowo2003, Rezi73, Virtualboy y coolekuh— los objetivos eran claros: encontrar al menos un geocaché en cada uno de los ocho países, la mayor cantidad posible de geocachés de distintos tipos por país, los más antiguos si era posible y, por último, pero no menos importante, probar una gran variedad de cervezas.

Lo logramos con creces y estoy muy contento con los resultados.

También vimos mucho y me sorprendió lo despreocupado y seguro que me sentí en todos los países.

Las tres semanas fueron agotadoras pero increíblemente maravillosas, dejándome muchas nuevas impresiones, y las recuerdo con gran alegría y satisfacción.

Un sincero agradecimiento a todos los propietarios de los geocachés.

Si se necesitan respuestas para un geocaché, alguien de nuestro grupo siempre las envía.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="17.744417" lon="10.083433"><time>2006-03-27T00:00:00</time><name>GCTPKA</name><desc>Niger #1: L'arbre du ténéré by Weihnachtsmann + JustusBeliebig</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCTPKA</url><urlname>Niger #1: L'arbre du ténéré</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="355396" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Niger #1: L'arbre du ténéré</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Weihnachtsmann + JustusBeliebig</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="363840">Weihnachtsmann</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Micro</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="1">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Niger</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;img src="http://www.internet-address.de/flaggen/german.gif" name="German" align="left" width="25" height="14" border="0" /&gt;Dieser erste Geocache im Niger liegt an einer der bekanntesten Stellen der Sahara - Kreuzungs- und Orientierungspunkt der alten Salzkarawanen von Bilma nach Timbuktu.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;Sein Namensgeber, eine Schirmakazie, fiel leider 1973 einem Lkw-Geisterfahrer zum Opfer und steht nun im Nationalmuseum in Niamey in einem eigenen Pavillon. Noch immer jedoch ist die Stelle Synonym für Leben inmitten einer riesigen Wüste ... (http://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tenere)&lt;/p&gt;
Schon vor fast 30 Jahren, als ich das erste (und bisher leider einzige) Mal auf dem Weg von Tunis nach N'Jamena hier vorbei kam, hatte dieser Punkt eine magische Anziehung. Damals konnte ich ihn nicht erreichen, aber heute wurde dieser Traum wahr. Jetzt geht es weiter nach Bilma (N18° 41.879 E12° 53.732, UNBEDINGT auf GoogleEarth ansehen!) und dann - zur Sonnenfinsternis 2006 in der Wüste Nigers.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Wer plant, diesen Cache zu machen, kann sich gerne vorher mit uns in Verbindung setzen - die meisten werden keine Gelegenheit zu einem zweiten Versuch haben.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.internet-address.de/flaggen/french.gif" name="French" align="left" width="25" height="13" border="0" /&gt;C’est dans l’un des endroits les plus connus du Sahara que se trouve ce premier caché au Niger. Le Schirmakazie est à l’origine de son nom. Celui-ci a malheureusement été la victime de l’imprudence d’un automobiliste en 1973 et il est aujourd’hui exposé au musée national de Niamey. Cet endroit a encore aujourd’hui valeur de symbole pour la vie au milieu de ce désert gigantesque ... (http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arbre_du_T%C3%A9n%C3%A9r%C3%A9)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Il y a 30 ans, lorsque je suis passé pour la première (et jusqu’à maintenant malheureusement aussi la seule) fois à cet endroit, c’était sur mon chemin de Tunis à N’Jamena: cet endroit avait déjà une force d’attraction extraordinaire. A l’époque je n’avais pu arriver jusque là, mais aujourd’hui ce rêve s’est finalement réalisé. D’ici on repart à Bilma (N18° 41.879 E12° 53.732, il faut absolument regarder sur GoogleEarth !!) et l’on continue vers le lieu de l’éclipse 2006 observée depuis le désert nigérien.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Ceux qui envisagent de chercher ce caché sont évidemment fortement invités à nous contacter avant leur départ – la plupart n’aura pas de deuxième essai.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.internet-address.de/flaggen/english.gif" name="English" align="left" width="25" height="13" border="0" /&gt;This Geocache - the first to be hidden in Niger - is at a point frequented by the old salt caravans as they made their way from Bilma to Timbuktu. The lonely acacia tree that once stood here served as a useful route marker until, in 1973, it was knocked down by an allegedly drunk truck driver. It now resides in the national museum in Niamey, inside its own pavilion. However, the place itself is still a symbol of life in the midst of an enormous desert ... (http://www.the153club.org/tenere.html). The first (and sadly until now, only) time I passed this place was almost 30 years ago when I was on the way from Tunis to N'Jamena, and it was then that I found it possessed a magical attraction. At that time I couldn't reach it, but today this dream became true. From here one sets out again towards Bilma (N18° 41.879 E12° 53.732 - look on GoogleEarth!!) and, for us, to the observation site of the 2006 Solar Eclipse.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Anyone planning to seek this cache are strongly advised to contact us before their departure, as you probably won't get a second chance to find it!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="1"&gt;Small note on cache maintenance:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="1"&gt;Assarid Bachar, ein Tuaregfuehrer, der im Winter alle 14 Tage zum Cache kommt, hat uns versprochen, bei dessen Wartung zu helfen. Vielen Dank an Marie-Line für ihre Hilfe beim Übersetzen&lt;br /&gt;
Assarid Bachar, a Tuareg guide, will visit the cache site every two weeks in winter time to assist with needed maintenance. I am in e-mail communication with him. Thanks a lot to Marie-Line for her help with the translation.&lt;br /&gt;
Assarid Bachar, un guide Tuareg se rendant toutes les deux semaines en hiver sur le lieu de caché nous a promis de veiller à sa présence. English translation of the cache page to follow.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Hints auf Anfrage/ Hints on request</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1354705827"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-12T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="363840">Weihnachtsmann</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Heideneiabberau,
jetzt verstehe ich das endlich!  🙂
Hier gab es immer mal wieder Notes, die rassistische Bemerkungen in diesem Geocache kritisierten - und ich habe nie verstanden, was sie damit meinten!
NIGER ist ein Staat in Afrika, der heißt nun mal so, schreibt sich mit nur einem "G" und hat seinen Namen ungeachtet internationaler Proteste bisher auch nicht geändert. 😉
Und dies ist und bleibt eben der allererste Geocache, der in diesem Staat versteckt wurde!
Dass es leider aus politischen Gründen sehr, sehr schwierig und gefährlich ist, dorthin zu gelangen, finde ich selbst auch außerordentlich schade! So gerne hätte ich ihn noch einmal besucht!
Aber mit Rassismus hat das wirklich überhaupt nichts zu tun. 🙂

ENGLISH:
Oh my goodness,
now I finally get it! 🙂
There have been notes here from time to time criticizing racist remarks in this geocache—and I never understood what they meant by that!
NIGER is a country in Africa; that’s just what it’s called, it’s spelled with only one “G,” and despite international protests, it hasn’t changed its name so far. 😉
And this is and remains the very first geocache ever hidden in that country!
I also find it extremely unfortunate that, for political reasons, it’s very, very difficult and dangerous to get there! I would have loved to visit it again!
But it really has absolutely nothing to do with racism. 🙂

Translated with DeepL.com (free version)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1353640119"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-06T20:29:41</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Having had two need reviewer attention on this cache regarding the fact that the cache has a racist name I felt I needed to show that I had taken note....

 Please look at the name of the country it is placed in. The name of the country is NIGER. The same as the cache name. The word  which both GLBCrew and Kbnos  referring to is a derogatory slur and is  spelt differently.  
There is no need for reviewers attention on the cache and the CO is keeping fake logs under control . Thank you for maintaining both the physical and online section of the cache.
  </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1352379520"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="363840">Weihnachtsmann</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Because there was no reply from SeattleHunter, the following log has been deleted:





</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1352378773"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="363840">Weihnachtsmann</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">    Hello, Seattlehunter,

    I'm very sorry, but I'm not sure if you actually found my geocache “L'abre de ténéré” and logged it in person at the site. Unfortunately, there are a lot of fake logs for this geocache! Before I simply delete your found entry, I’d like to ask you to send me proof of your visit there.
        What exactly did the container look like?
        Where and exactly how was it attached?
        Send me a copy of your MyFinds Pocket Query file showing the history of your finds on your world trip.
        Send me one or more photos of your visit to L'abre de tenere. Of course, you can also provide credible proof in other ways that you actually found this geocache yourself.

    Best regards and good luck, Santa Claus

    Translated with DeepL.com (free version)

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1332588994"><groundspeak:date>2025-11-01T13:49:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="17744096">GLBCrew</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Racist log in this cache. Please remove it.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="7.785466666666666" lon="4.52865"><time>2003-01-18T00:00:00</time><name>GCC65F</name><desc>Geocache by styrax</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCC65F</url><urlname>Geocache</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="50783" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Geocache</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>styrax</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="97718">styrax</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Nigeria</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>The terrain is easy, about 20 meters off a very major road and accessible to virtually everybody.  The altitude is about 520 meters about the sea level.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The box is colored green and white and contains, a writing pad, a fountain pen, 3 teddy bears, a can of candy, 2 Lagbaja audio CDs and other varied items.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1207821942"><groundspeak:date>2023-12-06T11:02:25</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Due to no response from the CO after the request to maintain or replace the cache, I am archiving it to, stop it showing on the listings  and/or to create place for the geocaching community.

The [Geocache Maintenance guideline](http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) explains a CO's responsibility towards checking and maintaining the cache when problems are reported. 

Please note that if geocaches are archived by a reviewer or Geocaching HQ for lack of maintenance, they are not eligible for unarchival. This is explained in the [Help Center](http://support.groundspeak.com//index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=70)

If the CO feels that this cache has been archived in error please feel free to contact me within 30 days,  via email or message via my profile ,quoting the GC number concerned

Thank you for understanding

Knagur Green
Groundspeak Volunteer Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1198814739"><groundspeak:date>2023-10-03T15:40:38</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18990911">Knagur Green</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings 

We have received a request to archive your cache page as the physical cache appears to be in need of maintenance and there has been no recent indication that timely maintenance may be forthcoming.

 I'm temporarily disabling it, to give you an opportunity to check on the cache, and take whatever action is necessary.

You are responsible for occasional visits to your cache to ensure it is in proper working order, especially when someone reports a problem with the cache (missing, damaged, wet, etc.) or posts a Needs Maintenance log. Temporarily disable your cache to let others know not to search for it until you have addressed the problem.

Please enable your cache by selecting 'enable' on the right hand side of the listing , once the cache has been replaced/repaired, or checked that it is still in situ.

The [Geocache Maintenance guideline](http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance) explains a CO's responsibility towards checking and maintaining the cache when problems are reported. 

Caches that have been archived for lack of maintenance will not be unarchived. This is explained in the [Help Center](http://support.groundspeak.com//index.php?pg=kb.page&amp;id=70)

If you no longer wish to maintain the cache then the listing should be archived.

**Please respond to this situation in a timely manner (i.e., within 30 days) to prevent the cache from being archived for non-responsiveness. If you plan on repairing this cache,but cannot get to it within 30 days, please log a note to the cache page (not email) to let the community know**

Thank you for understanding 

Knagur Green
Groundspeak Volunteer Reviewer

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1198320003"><groundspeak:date>2023-10-01T15:57:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Needs Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7680062">Matisons!</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">In 20 years there hasnt been any visual proof, that someone has ever found this cache or is it even placed. I dont believe this cache physically exist. Also the owner is kind of "fake" profile, which doesnt really help on trusting this cache. Cache needs to be checked or archived!!!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1194707959"><groundspeak:date>2023-09-13T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="46930976">GioH18</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false"> n,k</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1143957340"><groundspeak:date>2023-01-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8237929">ballbreaker67</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Not easy at all, it took us almost one hour with 4 people but it was a lot of fun.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-29.020317" lon="167.969533"><time>2003-03-13T00:00:00</time><name>GCE80C</name><desc>Cascade (Norfolk Is) by BaldEd</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCE80C</url><urlname>Cascade (Norfolk Is)</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="59404" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cascade (Norfolk Is)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>BaldEd</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="23932">BaldEd</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="23" inc="1">Dangerous area</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Norfolk Island</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Norfolk Island, South Pacific.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;Access is from the car park at S29 01.322 E167 58.271. It is advisable to wear strong footwear. Beware loose rocks and cow patties.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Try to leave a small memento of your visit to Norfolk Island. In time it is hoped that this cache will contain only items of Norfolk Island origin.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is a 1 litre screw-top black painted container with logbook with room for some swap items.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;font color="red"&gt;Please bring your own pen to sign the logbook.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Under small rocks in a crevice between two large rocks 3m west of a tree.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1359708190"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-08T17:33:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="37998606">Deanodingodog</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On a drive around the island to briefly see everything we could. We only stopped for a couple of caches along the way.  This was one. 
Thanks :)
😎</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1347936209"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-08T20:47:40</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="28498682">Roscolly</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Tftc</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1347911950"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-06T14:21:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15447345">EatSleepCacheRepeat_</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We walked to this cache from the cockpit. It looked a bit scary at first but turned out to be a very nice walk along a well-established track. Neil took the low road while I tried the middle ground, and soon had the cache in hand.
Along the way we happened upon a tropicbird nest. They were not happy about our presence and made plenty of noise to let us know we needed to move along quickly, so we graciously obliged.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1348308340"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13397944">E_Smiley</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Cascade (Norfolk Is)
2.0/3.0 
Regular 
Traditional Cache 

Finding this cache was awesome. Lots of red tailed tropical birds were hovering above us when we were at gz.

Here in Norfolk Island with Eat Sleep Cache Repeat, Ardom, Alisnan and Team Bender (aka as CACHEQLD) to visit our good friend endeavour3, observe the Foundation Day and find geocaches while exploring the place. 

We really enjoyed our stay. Lots of laughs, great adventure and heaps of fun!  Totally and highly recommended!

Thank you for the cache BaldEd.

6 March 2026 3:52 pm</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1348237923"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4110655">Team Benders</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Out with the group to find this cache. Signed  under CacheQld . A fine mild day.  Thanks BaldEd. All good with this cache </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="60.332767" lon="5.2932"><time>2001-06-09T00:00:00</time><name>GCBBF</name><desc>Norges første, i Bergen, The first cache in Norway by Steinar &amp; Co</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCBBF</url><urlname>Norges første, i Bergen, The first cache in Norway</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Multi-cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="3007" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Norges første, i Bergen, The first cache in Norway</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Steinar &amp; Co</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="10440">Steinar, Bergen</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Multi-cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="26" inc="1">Public transportation nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="38" inc="0">Campfires</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Norway</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Vestland</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This is the first geocache that was placed in Norway.&lt;img src="http://www.geocaching.com/images/icons/icon_smile_big.gif" border="0" align="middle" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Part one is hidden 140 meters above sea level, near a playground for children.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;font size="4" color="red"&gt;Pleas note: There are VERY DANGEROUS CLIFFS near Part 2 and 3. Watch your children, and take care for yourselves.&lt;/font&gt;
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>For english, see further down.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;font size="4" color="green"&gt;Norsk:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Litt om bakgrunnen til denne turboksen:&lt;br /&gt;
I juni 2001 fikk jeg høre om geocaching fra en kollega. Da det ikke fantes noen turbokser i Norge på det tidspunktet, måtte jeg jo legge ut en selv. &lt;img src="http://www.geocaching.com/images/icons/icon_smile.gif" border="0" align="middle" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Jeg fulgte "oppskriften" som da var adskillig enklere. Man kunne til og med melde cachen på epost til den ene "approveren" som fantes på verdensbasis. Torstein og jeg gikk ut for å gjemme isboksen. Noen nabobarn spurte hva vi skulle med den boksen, og da jeg sa vi skulle gjemme en skatt gikk det som et jallarop gjennom borettslaget. På et blunk var vi en liten arme på veg for å gjemme skatten. Det gjorde jo ingenting om cachen ble kjent for ikke-cachere, da det ikke fantes cachere i det hele tatt i Norge... &lt;img src="http://www.geocaching.com/images/icons/icon_smile_wink.gif" border="0" align="middle" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
I løpet av de neste par åra ble det VELDIG mange som visste om boksen. Mot slutten ble den mugglet et par ganger i måneden. Siden det var den første i Norge, var det lite aktuelt å arkivere den. I stedet flyttet vi selve boksen, og brukte det opprinnelige stedet som Del 1 for en multi. Posisjonen til denne er nøyaktig den samme som i 2001. Ikke en eneste desimal er endret siden da. &lt;img src="http://www.geocaching.com/images/icons/icon_smile_approve.gif" border="0" align="middle" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Navnet på cachen er også uendret.&lt;br /&gt;
Del 2 er forøvrig også blitt litt for godt kjent bland gompene, derfor er det nå tre deler. På Del 2 ligger kun en henvisning til Del 3. Legg henvisningen godt på plass, med en stein over. Du kan også hoppe over Del 2 ved å legge følgende til minuttverdiene i posisjonen til Del 2 (NB! Ikke Del 1): 0.015 -0.001 (Omtrent rett nord for Del 2. "Litt" vest.)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Del 1:&lt;br /&gt;
Se etter noe naturlig som står skjevt, og let under. Der vil du finne en "lenke" med nødvendig verktøy for å komme deg til Del 2. Gransk verktøyet nøye. Det kan være tildekket av gress.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Del 2:&lt;br /&gt;
Ligger ved et flott utkikkspunkt. Her finner du henvisningen til Del 3, og den ligger IKKE på eller veldig nær stupet. Del 2 ligger mindre enn 100 meter fra Del 1.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Del 3:&lt;br /&gt;
Ligger også ved et flott utkikkspunkt, men enda farligere enn Del 2. Cachen ligger IKKE på eller veldig nær stupet. Hvis du har funnet Del 1 kan du beregne Cachen (Del 3) sin posisjon fra posisjonen du har fått for Del 2. :) (Se rett over beskrivelsen av Del 1.)&lt;br /&gt;
Lykke til!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;font size="3" color="red"&gt;Pass godt på barna og dere selv. Del 2 og 3 ligger nær veldig farlige stup.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;font size="4" color="green"&gt;English:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Some background:&lt;br /&gt;
In June 2001, a colleague told me about geocaching, but there were no caches in Norway. Therefore I decided to place one near home. I prepared an ice box, and Torstein and I went out to find a place to hide it. Some kids asked what we planned to do with that box, and I answered we were going to hide a treasure. In one minute, an alarm-based child rumor collected a small army of children. They followed us to find a good hiding place. Some of them brought one of their parents. I didn't mind that the cache became a very popular place for non-cachers. At that time ALL Norwegians were non-cachers...&lt;img src="http://www.geocaching.com/images/icons/icon_smile_wink.gif" border="0" align="middle" /&gt;. During the next couple of years, VERY many knew about the place, and at the end it was muggled twice every month. Since it was the first cache in Norway, I didn't want to archive it. In stead I moved it, and kept the original position as a Stage 1 of a multi. In 2006, Stage two was moved to a place with better view. Stage one is at the original position. Not even a digit is changed since it was placed in 2001. &lt;img src="http://www.geocaching.com/images/icons/icon_smile_approve.gif" border="0" align="middle" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
The name of the cache is also unchanged.&lt;br /&gt;
If knowing your math, you may also go straight from Part 1 to Part 3. Simply add the following minute values to the position of Part 2 (Note! Not part 1): 0.015 -0.001 (Almost straight north of part 2, slightly to the west).&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Part 1:&lt;br /&gt;
Look for something from the nature, that is not in its original up-right position, and search under it. There you will find the "chain" with the necessary tool to get to Part 2. Watch the tool closely. It may be covered by grass.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Part 2:&lt;br /&gt;
Located at a place with a nice view. Here, you will find a small note giving the final position. This note is NOT located on or very near the edge.&lt;br /&gt;
The distance from Part1 to Part2 is less than 100 meters.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Part 3:&lt;br /&gt;
Also located at a place with a nice view, but MUCH more dangerous than Part 2. The cache is NOT located on or very near the edge.&lt;br /&gt;
If you have found Part 1, you can calculate the cache position yourself, based on the given position of Part 2. :) (See just above the description of Part 1).&lt;br /&gt;
Good luck!
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>[Norsk:]
[Del 1:] Furu, Under rot, Venstre
[Del 2:] Under stor stein
[Del 3:] Under liten stein, i ei lita kløft
[English:]
[Part 1:] Pine, Under root, Left side
[Part 2:] Under big stone
[Part 3:] Under small stone, in small cleft
</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363457877"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T14:39:51</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="26613506">Schatzi070</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#13068

Zusammen mit Hallole unterwegs. Näheres siehe Halloles Log.

Vielen lieben Dank an Steinar &amp; Co für den Geocache!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363457874"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T14:39:51</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4526067">Hallole</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#26429

Für diesen besonderen Multi sind wir heute extra noch hergefahren. Zwar regnete es in Strömen, aber das sollte kein Hindernis sein.
Nach allerlei Schwierigkeiten wurden wir am Ende fündig. Nur haben wir im Regen leider ein Foto vergessen - schade.

Herzlichen Dank an Steinar &amp; Co für den Cache!

Anmerkung: Wir loggen inzwischen häufig an irgendeiner freien Stelle im Logbuch. Es ist für uns ein Rätsel, warum so viele Cacher freie Stellen überspringen, Logbücher von hinten beginnen, Logs über mehrere Felder schreiben oder raumgreifende Stempel nützen. Dies geht alles zu Lasten der Owner, die häufiger warten müssen. Wenn unser Log also nicht am Ende steht, dann ist es weiter vorn sicher zu finden!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361208567"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-15T19:30:27</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="11072672">JSB542</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Da har vi endelig fått tatt Norges eldste. Takker for at denne holdes i live.   </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360945685"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-14T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5700854">Martinda</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">19:15h: Found with the help of a  friend. What a beautiful view up here! TFTC,  Martinda (N&amp;M)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360303855"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-10T20:34:46</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9733494">silyam</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">På utvida langhelg besøk i Rådalen ble det litt tid til caching😊  At norges eldste cache befant seg i Bergen hadde vi ikke tenkt på. Da vi besøkte Troldhaugen ble det lest noen logger og da ble vi oppmerksom😀  Etter besøk på escape room med tenåringan svingte vi innom her på tur tilbake. Her skippa vi delmål og gikk rett på. Kjapt og greit funn. Supert å finne denne på cachens jubileumsår😄    grønt 💚 til co for at dere holder den vedlike. Tftc🌸 sm cara2006</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="24.583167" lon="56.015983"><time>2001-09-04T00:00:00</time><name>GC1B56</name><desc>Pirelli by P. LaRocque and A.Foley / adopted by Camel Master</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1B56</url><urlname>Pirelli</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="6998" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Pirelli</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>P. LaRocque and A.Foley / adopted by Camel Master</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1210477">Camel Master</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="1">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="31" inc="1">Camping nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="38" inc="1">Campfires</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>4.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Oman</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>The oldest cache in Oman. Jebel Sumayni, on the wrong side of the
keyhole. THIS CACHE SHOULD BE AVOIDED IN RAINY CONDITIONS.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>The walk takes you through a wadi, and should be avoided if rain is
nearby. Reaching the cache without a 4X4 is possible (park near the
paved road), but will add at least another hour to the roundtrip. A
4X4 is required to reach the nearest parking area. There is a great
place to camp at the beginning of the walk. Reaching the cache from
the parking area will take about 30 or 40 minutes (if you are
clever, or if you use the cheat-sheet available in &amp;ldquo;Why not
go find Pirelli?&amp;rdquo; GC1657B cache). The roundtrip should take
about 2 hours, allowing time to find the cache and take in the
scenery. According to Patrick LaRocque and Andrew Foley, who
originally placed the cache, it contained "a Logbook, camera (27
shots) and 27 vouchers for Pirelli stuff (hats, keychains, some
watches, shirts, etc). Pirelli gave it to us so it&amp;rsquo;s the
Pirelli cache." It now contains several items I left behind when I
replaced the cache in April 2007.</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Under rocks next to the tree</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1343580089"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2225990">erglis</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Auf dem Weg von Alain nach Sohar war dieser Cache Mein erstes Ziel im Oman. Mit meinem alten Studienfreund habe ich mich auf den Weg gemacht. Für die Zufahrt zu den Parkkoordinaten ist auf jeden Fall viel Bodenfreiheit beim Auto nötig. Wir mussten laufen. Ein Weg im Wadi ist nicht vorhanden. Intuition ist notwendig. Der Weg ist sicher keine schwere Tour, aber für den normalen Stadtbewohner schon eine Herausforderung. Mir hat es sehr gut gefallen. Gerne lasse ich ein blaues Schleifchen da. 

On the way from Alain to Sohar, this cache was my first destination in Oman. I set off with an old university friend. A car with high ground clearance is definitely needed to reach the parking coordinates. We had to walk. There's no path in the wadi. Intuition is essential. The route isn't exactly a difficult hike, but it's certainly a challenge for the average city dweller. I enjoyed it very much. I'm happy to leave a blue ribbon here.

Danke für die Dose Paldies par šo Cache Thanks for that Cache Merci pour la Cache Dzięki za Cache Grazie per questo Cache Takk for at Cache Obrigado por isso Cache Gracias por el Cache شكرا لأن ذاكرة التخزين المؤقت Díky za keš Ačiū už tą talpyklą Aitäh selle eest Cache Спасибо за то кэш 感谢您的缓存 Kiitos, että Cache Tack för att Cache Tak for denne Cache</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1339304353"><groundspeak:date>2025-12-26T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10102634">PaLaRunCa</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">One of our all time favourites!! What a fantastic spot! Favo, of course!! ❤️🇴🇲

Oman is the 52nd country where we have been able to find the oldest cache!!

------

After a four-day high-altitude training camp in the French Alps full of sports, games, enjoyment and relaxation, we’ve recharged our batteries and are completely ready for the second part of our Christmas holiday: an adventurous journey of discovery through the Middle East!

The main destination of our trip is what is often called Arabia’s best-kept secret: the Sultanate of Oman! The most convenient flight connections to get there aren’t necessarily the most interesting for a cacher, so we get to discover quite a few other beautiful places on the Arabian Peninsula along the way…

Part 4/1: after Jordan, Bahrein, Saudi-Arabia and Qatar... finally Oman! 🇴🇲

Our first full day in Oman, the 79th country on our GC map! The first stop of the day was the Sohar Fort, where we logged our first Omani find, a nicely hidden trad and also completed an EarthCache and a Wherigo.

After that, we continued our route towards the main goal of every new destination: the country’s oldest cache. We made one more stop along the way at impressive basalt formations in a stunning setting, where we were also able to spot many new bird species that were still unknown to us.

After stocking up on some local sweets, it was truly Pirelli time! After leaving the main road, we first drove a short off-road section with our 4WD rental, getting to within about one and a half kilometres of the cache as the crow flies. What followed was a beautiful hike through the dry riverbed (wadi), with some scrambling here and there along larger pools left behind after the heavy rainfall of last week. We were absolutely determined to make it this far, but to be honest, we had little hope of actually finding the cache. The last credible find dated back more than eight years.

For the final 80 metres, we climbed up the rock face, and there we saw the tree from the spoiler photo! 24 years later, much larger, but also older and barer. To our great surprise, we found the original cache there in perfect condition, including the original logbook with the co’s note at the moment of rehiding and the FTF from 2011. We took photos of all the pages of the logbook and are posting them in full with this log, because finding this oldie appears to be even rarer than the online logs already suggested... We were absolutely thrilled to find it here! We were holding a real piece of early geocaching history in our hands; almost an archaeological find, at least for us geocachers. :)

It’s a pity that this cache is so rarely visited, because it immediately earns a place on our all-time favourites list. An incredibly beautiful hike in a stunning, remote natural area. The silence here is deafening, no sounds of civilization at all, just pure nature. During our three-hour hike we encountered only two donkeys, many loudly croaking frogs thoroughly enjoying the fresh water, and quite a few birds. We enjoyed it immensely!


Tftc P. LaRocque and A.Foley / adopted by Camel Master!

Discovering our world one box at a time! 🌍 #33009

Rating when found: D2.5/T4.5

Feel free to discover the trackable on our gc profile! 🐒🦍</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1228454802"><groundspeak:date>2024-04-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4110776">flecki1</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Auf unserer Reise im Oman 😻 diesen Cache besucht.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="736008878"><groundspeak:date>2017-12-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3526164">BCandG</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Awesome awesome awesome! Great hike up the wadi. We took our time enjoying the mountains, trees, little frog filled water holes and so much more. Once we came around the last turn and started up the hill for the cache, unbelievably there were two muggles! So we took a break under the tree and had our lunch. Once we were finished eating they were gone and we could sign the log unseen.  We read in the log book that some cachers before us climbed up to the key hole. That is just amazing.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="587579610"><groundspeak:date>2016-04-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="13689422">whitsends</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Brilliant walk - rather wet underfoot. Should have been doing this yesterday but we were 'rained off'. You really wouldn't want to tackle this in bad weather. Getting the cache was made easier by the hints provided by a fellow cacher. What scenery! Loved it and you get a favorite point. TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="36.46055" lon="74.892233"><time>2004-04-20T00:00:00</time><name>GCJC8V</name><desc>109th Step by geodirect</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCJC8V</url><urlname>109th Step</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="136924" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>109th Step</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>geodirect</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="209177">geodirect</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Pakistan</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>General location requires long term planning but once in the
vicinity the cache location is relatively easy. Elevation is 2539 m
amsl. Try the yummy Apricot Cake whilst you are there</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Round metal pot with plastic lid contains Log Book and 2 x
Australian clip-on Koala Bears&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
