MPLC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="970321381"><groundspeak:date>2020-10-09T20:15:41</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="22734580">DaveWater</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it with Bwater 😀nice </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="969910239"><groundspeak:date>2020-10-09T20:15:04</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5248634">Bwater</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">After a drink for using wifi, went back, because I couldn’t read the hint offline,
Euh well 🤔 we don’t know if this is the original, because it was not difficulty 3 😳 but a big thanks for giving us a smilie in Monaco 🇲🇨 /GPC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="968304893"><groundspeak:date>2020-09-30T10:50:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5432714">sam&amp;co</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On arrive dans le Var , et une première emplacement du camping car est à L'Escarène  l' idéal pour vister Monaco .
On a vue le changement de la garde du Prince Albert et ... on à meme vue le prince Albert qui quiitait le palais !
A Monaco on visite les caches qui se retrouve sur notre chemin et après avoir payer 25 € pour le parking [}:)] on reprend la route direction Théoule-sur-Mer ou on gare notre camping car pour quelques jours.
Ce qui nous permet de visiter la cache la plus anciènne de la France ... **La vigie**

**FAVO**


**Salutations de la Belgique**

Les photo's ne sont pas nécessairement du **GZ**

Et naturellement on visite des caches qui se retrouve sur notre chemin !

Un grand merci à mon  **"O"** qui est la responsable pour les solutions des mysteries ! [^]

A gauche et à droite on laisse tomber un **FAVO**


**Juan Manuel Fang.** Thanks for this cache !

**30070**  on our  [:)] [:)] [:)] - List .




</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="14.756867" lon="-17.513717"><time>2008-07-19T00:00:00</time><name>GC1EC1R</name><desc>Ile de N'Gor by aeromac</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1EC1R</url><urlname>Ile de N'Gor</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="941062" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Ile de N'Gor</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>aeromac</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1590356">aeromac</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="38" inc="0">Campfires</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Senegal</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Petite traditionnelle sur l'île de N'Gor près de Dakar.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;i&gt;Small traditional cache on N'Gor island near
Dakar.&lt;/i&gt;</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br&gt;
&lt;center&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;N'Gor&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/38110206-1d44-44c7-b4af-5b36bd7a9028.jpg"&gt;
&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;Français&lt;/u&gt; :&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Située à quelques minutes de
l’aéroport en taxi suivi de 5 min de pirogue (départ de la plage du
village de N’Gor : 500 F CFA l’aller-retour), l’île de N’Gor a tout
pour plaire. Calme, indolente et ombragée, elle offre un espace de
bronzette et de balade qui convient aussi bien aux touristes qu’aux
Dakarois en quête de détente. Idéal pour faire des rencontres en
maillot de bain...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Avant l’arrivée des colons
français, l’île de N’Gor était inhabitée. Seules quelques chèvres
élevées par des pêcheurs lébous musardaient sur un territoire «
interdit », patronné par un mauvais génie.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Une particularité de l’île de
N’Gor : il n’y a pas d’électricité, seuls quelques panneaux
solaires et groupes électrogènes produisent un peu de courant.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;i&gt;English&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/u&gt; :&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;i&gt;Located at a few minutes from
the airport by taxi followed by 5 mn of typical pirogue (starting
from the beach of N’gor village : 500 F CFA roundtrip), N’gor
island has everything to enjoy yourself. Calm, indolent and shaded,
you can either sunbathe or walk around the island to relax yourself
like locals do. That’s a great way to meet people in
bathingsuit...&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;i&gt;Before the arrival of French
settlers, N’gor island was uninhabited. Only a few goats bred by
“lébous” fishermen used to dawdle on this “prohibited” territory,
thought to be possessed by a bad spirit.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;i&gt;N’gor island particularity : no
electricity, only a few solar panels and generating sets produce
electricity.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;font size="1"&gt;The maintenance arrangement for this cache is on
file with geocaching.com&lt;/font&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Attention ça pique ! Sous des pierres.
Beware it stings ! Under stones.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1359670263"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-07T23:35:01</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21442357">MarkusSchneider</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A quick find while exploring the island with my girlfriend while visiting Senegal for the first time. TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358680971"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-02T18:52:08</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="49720165">tercilla</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Genial</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358554739"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-02T13:00:42</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54250351">swpra</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354586213"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-29T16:09:06</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5983472">quirkykirks</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Great spot for a cache! Had a fun time searching for this one—almost felt like a secret mission. Loved the hide, and the journey was just as enjoyable as the find. Thanks for placing it! 😃👍 29 Mar 2026 at 16:09"**  
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1341337055"><groundspeak:date>2026-01-08T14:43:19</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="301288">GeoTyger</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Merci merci!! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-15.304" lon="35.371617"><time>2009-08-23T00:00:00</time><name>GC1XW64</name><desc>Makwawa Campsite by AAHydeAndSeek and S.A.M.</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1XW64</url><urlname>Makwawa Campsite</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1372686" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Makwawa Campsite</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>AAHydeAndSeek and S.A.M.</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="2291942">A1HydeAndSeek</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="31" inc="1">Camping nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="43" inc="1">Livestock nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Malawi</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>A traditional cache placed at the Makwawa National Scout Campsite
of the Scout Association of Malawi (S.A.M.)</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;b&gt;IMPORTANT: Please place the cache back as you find it to protect
it from locals and the local monkeys!&lt;/b&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Scout Association of Malawi was reestablised in 1999 after
being banned from the 1970 to 1994 under the dictatorship of
President Hastings Kamuzu Banda. It became a member of WOSM in
2005. Before 1964 Malawi was part of Nyasaland and Rhodesia where
Scouting had flourished since 1909.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The New Scout Association of Malawi (S.A.M.) has its main office
in Lilongwe and as of 2009 the Director is Steve Kanene (Chief
Chembe from Monkey Bay area!). The number of members is growing
fast. As of May 2008 WOSM had it shown with 4000 members and 1 year
later in April 2009 it had 10500. The girls belong to their own
organisation MAGGA.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;S.A.M. has established three campsites, one in each
administrative region in Malawi. Makwawa is the largest and most
well established. The estimated capacity is 150 although plans to
clear more camping areas and upgrade the infrastructure are
underway so that a National Jamboree can be held there maybe as
early as 2010.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is a box where there maybe tradeable Scouting items
like badges, however, the most useful trade for this cache is time
and energy. Many different Scouting groups from the USA, Scotland,
England and Norway, and others, have given time, money and effort
in establishing the campsite but more work is needed to develop it
further.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is placed by AAHydeAndSeek during the second Advanced
Woodbadge course, 19th - 23rd August 2009.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The campsite is open to non-scouts and is an excellent base for
exploring the Zomba plateau.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Welcome to Makwawa.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/5ec62074-9a7a-4a35-b560-4b5387e05bf1.jpg"
width="200" /&gt;&lt;/center&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>The secret behind Scouting.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1223365495"><groundspeak:date>2024-03-25T20:03:13</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2291942">A1HydeAndSeek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for all the visits to this remote campsite. I received some information suggesting the site was partly destroyed in a recent storm and the last visit seems to have confirmed this. The camp site warden who looked after the cache probably has better things to do. Still there is the cache at the Scout Association of Malawi (SAM) HQ in Lilongwe looked after by the office staff and an Earth Cache on the south edge of Lake Malawi.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1223023409"><groundspeak:date>2024-03-24T10:30:43</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2164922">jejoms</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">After a week in Malawi, I decided I wanted to find a geocache too. And then to my surprise, I found this one made by my (at least previously) fellow Norwegian geocacher AAHydeandSeek!

I drove up the bad roads and searched all the possible locations without finding the actual container. However, I hope the photoproof that I was here will do😊 And a great spot, no matter what - thanks for showing me!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1125894736"><groundspeak:date>2022-09-15T02:37:58</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="41095872">bigdaddy8746</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Fi</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1097487421"><groundspeak:date>2022-05-18T10:08:25</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="41100122">Dávid_12</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Tftc</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1081227969"><groundspeak:date>2022-03-06T21:45:32</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="39571176">Unic_Ghost69</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">👍</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="-8.538883" lon="-172.517583"><time>2016-11-09T00:00:00</time><name>GC6WRTF</name><desc>No Exercise? Exercise! by KiwiAoraki</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC6WRTF</url><urlname>No Exercise? Exercise!</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Multi-cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="5958217" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>No Exercise? Exercise!</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>KiwiAoraki</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="10490566">KiwiAoraki</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Multi-cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Tokelau</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;p&gt;Tokelau's first multi and yes, exercise is required&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p&gt;WP1 will place you in front of the hospital. There's a yellow sign with red lettering. Use numerical values (A=1, Z=26) to decipher the coordinates. Use only the words with &lt;strong&gt;red lettering&lt;/strong&gt;; ignore those with black lettering.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is an old plastic Kool-Aid container&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
S08 32.ABC&lt;br /&gt;
W172 30.DEF&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
A = the 2nd letter of the fourth word&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;B = the 3rd letter of the sixth word&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;C = the 4th letter of the fourth word&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;D = the 5th letter of the first word&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;E = combine the values of the 1st letters of the first and fifth words&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;F = the 4th letter of the fourth word minus 1st letter of the fourth word&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Getting to GZ will require about a 30 minute walk. Bring your camera, sunnies, and &lt;u&gt;PLENTY&lt;/u&gt; of water since Tokelau is hot all year! Enjoy the views!&lt;br /&gt;
 &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>In the larger tree directly south of the small stand-alone shrub. Covered by rock about knee height</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1338293008"><groundspeak:date>2025-12-19T12:50:54</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54234840">Gabrielfinder</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It would be cool if someone got this one day</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="654779699"><groundspeak:date>2016-12-08T05:40:51</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="115500">Crow T Robot</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Published</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="40.186317" lon="44.509667"><time>2010-06-21T00:00:00</time><name>GC2AK76</name><desc>Our Wedding-Church St. Zoravor by Troll1379+Cantarada</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC2AK76</url><urlname>Our Wedding-Church St. Zoravor</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1752314" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Our Wedding-Church St. Zoravor</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Troll1379+Cantarada</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1570775">Troll1379</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="38" inc="0">Campfires</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Armenia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div style="text-align: center; color: rgb(204, 0, 0);"&gt;
&lt;big&gt;&lt;big style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;This cache is dedicated to the
church of our wedding.&lt;/big&gt;&lt;br style="font-weight: bold;" /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
We are an mixed nation couple from Armenia and Germany,&lt;br /&gt;
after our wonderful marriage in 2008 we decided to hide a
cache&lt;br /&gt;
on this special place.&lt;/big&gt;&lt;small&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img style=
"width: 600px; height: 900px;" alt="" src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/f4292100-f16c-4981-8ee6-e652372e8c55.jpg" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;

&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;big style="color: rgb(255, 0, 0); font-weight: bold;"&gt;Please hide
the cache well again after you found it, thanks!&lt;/big&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href="http://www.andyhoppe.com/" title="Counter"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://www.andyhoppe.com/count/?id=1277145255" style=
"border: medium none ;" alt="Counter" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Under a small pile of stones... but not under the cross!</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364816127"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T17:27:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4048870">petitsllops</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Trobat 
A **Armènia**, descobrint llocs amb molta història i  Hi ha llocs al món on el passat no es llegeix als llibres, sinó que es respira en el mateix aire, gairebé feixuc, carregat de segles de resistència i memòria, vivint una molt bona experiència i signant catxés amb l’equip Mercè Salelles, Dosser i  Catalunya Team .
Aquest catxé en especial ens fa il·lusió per tractar-se del primer catxé amagat a Armènia.

Gràcies a  opted-out user per publicar.

**[ p e t i t s l l o p s ]( http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=7e9f9580-b5f4-41e4-9bfe-b1ae0426a33a)**</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1314816616"><groundspeak:date>2025-07-26T17:32:22</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3421196">19Dude65</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Aältester Cache in Armenien?</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1237476734"><groundspeak:date>2024-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="19914596">Rešek</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Díky za kešku na krásném místě. Škoda archivu.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1237292438"><groundspeak:date>2024-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="38116016">gali76</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for the cache ;)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1237162578"><groundspeak:date>2024-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8921102">cichalm</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Visited together with gali76 and Jirka0508, during a short vacation in Armenia.
Thank you for the cache, greetings from Pilsen 🇨🇿</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="25.06915" lon="-77.450367"><time>2003-01-13T00:00:00</time><name>GCC411</name><desc>The Caves by forman</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCC411</url><urlname>The Caves</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="50193" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>The Caves</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>forman</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="59944">forman</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Bahamas</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.theGBA.net" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.thegba.net/images/gba_logo_green.gif" border="1" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;div style="margin-left:2em;"&gt;\It is on West Bay Street.Check out the cave and all the bats!&lt;/div&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&amp;lt;4 January 2010 garrow replaced the cache – with the “small rock” cache well labeled and included logbook, pencil, coins and a few other swappable items. There is only a logbook and a Geo note. Bring a pencil. Find it and then check out the caves, Bring a flash light.&amp;gt;&amp;lt; If there are a few DNF's, before anyone gets carried away and does a “Should Be Archived”, give me a chance to post a note to get it replaced. Once it is archived most people will not see it. There’s not that many caches around here.&amp;gt; N25°04.153 instead of your N25°04.149. Please let us know if you see any bat activity too. They do travel from cave to cave on the island.
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>hidden in the rock about 4-5 feet from the ground and covered up</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1360771697"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-13T17:11:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18671687">Kiviuq</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for the cache! My 5731st find! UselessChicken and I decided today was the best day to come on out to the caves, see some bats, and find a cache or two or three. The jitney buses aren’t so challenging to figure out as we feared they might be, and we arrived at a GZ that was thankfully deserted of earthbound muggles. Took a minute to find this one, lots of potential hiding spots, but we were successful in the end. The cache is in good shape still. Afterwards we went to poke our heads in the cave and that was pretty cool</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359951252"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-09T10:26:20</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2644357">TeamGilbert</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found on Vacation.  TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359362499"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-05T13:29:50</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3605589">SpeedNose</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">After a short hike we were able to find this sweet little cave and the catch. TFTC and greetings from Germany🙂
Lots of bat activity in the cave by the way:)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1352759971"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-03T20:32:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="24266605">Eurêka71</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Find with Claudan during our vacations.
Nice place
TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1352730422"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-03T16:05:12</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="20950160">claudan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Avec eurêka 71 et geo vero en vacances au bahamas mplc 
Canada Québec Salaberry de Valleyfield </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="13.685433" lon="104.0162"><time>2009-10-28T00:00:00</time><name>GC21N8D</name><desc>Phnom Kulen National Park  by Aucoin.J</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC21N8D</url><urlname>Phnom Kulen National Park </urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Earthcache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1486155" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Phnom Kulen National Park </groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Aucoin.J</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="705532">Aucoin.J</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Earthcache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>Cambodia</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>None</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;br /&gt;
 
&lt;p style="width: 767px; font-family: Times New Roman;"
align="justify"&gt;Phnom Kulen is the holiest mountain in Cambodia. It
was here in 802 AD that King Jayavarman declared himself the
god-king and breaking away from the Java kingdom. This is the
birthplace of the &lt;a href="/about/history/angkor-empire"&gt;Angkor&lt;/a&gt;
kingdom and modern Cambodia.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>Located 30km beyond
&lt;a href="/destinations/siem-reap/attractions/angkor-wat"&gt;Angkor
Wat&lt;/a&gt;, it is an exquisite mountain region of magical, thundering
waterfalls, raunchy riverbed carvings and Cambodia’s largest
reclining Buddha carving on its summit. In Phnom Kulen National
Park you can see &lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;many red&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;sandstones&lt;/span&gt; from which
Angkor temples were constructed.
&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;Red sandstone&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;was
quarried here in this park.&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
 &lt;big style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;&lt;big&gt;&lt;big&gt;Geology of
the
park:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/big&gt;&lt;b style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
 &lt;img style="width: 766px; height: 336px;" alt="mineral sandstone"
src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/ee1d76e4-8116-42ed-8479-27f99aa45bfe.jpg" /&gt;
&lt;/b&gt; 
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;&lt;b&gt;There are several kind
of sandstones like for example&lt;/b&gt; &lt;i&gt;Lithic Sandstone,&lt;/i&gt;
&lt;i&gt;Banded Sandstone,&lt;/i&gt; &lt;i&gt;Quartz Sandstone,&lt;/i&gt; &lt;i&gt;Glauconitic
Sandstone&lt;/i&gt; &lt;b&gt;but in Phnom Kulen national park and listed
coordinates you can see mainly red sandstone.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Sandstone&lt;/b&gt;
(sometimes known as &lt;a title="Arenite"
href="/wiki/Arenite"&gt;arenite&lt;/a&gt;) is a &lt;a title="Sedimentary rock"
href="/wiki/Sedimentary_rock"&gt;sedimentary rock&lt;/a&gt; composed mainly
of &lt;a title="Sand" href="/wiki/Sand"&gt;sand&lt;/a&gt;-sized
&lt;a title="Mineral" href="/wiki/Mineral"&gt;minerals&lt;/a&gt; or rock
&lt;a title="Particle size (grain size)"
href="/wiki/Particle_size_%28grain_size%29"&gt;grains&lt;/a&gt;. Most
sandstone is composed of &lt;a title="Quartz"
href="/wiki/Quartz"&gt;quartz&lt;/a&gt; and/or &lt;a title="Feldspar"
href="/wiki/Feldspar"&gt;feldspar&lt;/a&gt; because these are the most
common minerals in the Earth's &lt;a title="Crust (geology)"
href="/wiki/Crust_%28geology%29"&gt;crust&lt;/a&gt;. Like sand, sandstone
may be any color, but the most common colors are tan, brown,
yellow, red, gray and white. Since sandstone beds often form highly
visible cliffs and other &lt;a title="Topography"
href="/wiki/Topography"&gt;topographic&lt;/a&gt; features, certain colors of
sandstone have been strongly identified with certain regions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;Some sandstones are
resistant to &lt;a title="Weathering"
href="/wiki/Weathering"&gt;weathering&lt;/a&gt;, yet are easy to work. This
makes sandstone a common &lt;a title="Building material"
href="/wiki/Building_material"&gt;building&lt;/a&gt; and
&lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Pavement (material)"
href="/wiki/Pavement_%28material%29"&gt;paving&lt;/a&gt; material. However,
some that have been used in the past, such as the
&lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Collyhurst sandstone"
href="/wiki/Collyhurst_sandstone"&gt;Collyhurst sandstone&lt;/a&gt; used in
&lt;a title="North West England" href="/wiki/North_West_England"&gt;North
West England&lt;/a&gt;, have been found less resistant, necessitating
repair and replacement in older buildings.&lt;sup class="reference"
id="cite_ref-0"&gt;&lt;a href="#cite_note-0"&gt;&lt;span&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;1&lt;span&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;
Because of the hardness of the individual grains, uniformity of
grain size and &lt;a title="Friability"
href="/wiki/Friability"&gt;friability&lt;/a&gt; of their structure, some
types of sandstone are excellent materials from which to make
&lt;a title="Grindstone (tool)"
href="/wiki/Grindstone_%28tool%29"&gt;grindstones&lt;/a&gt;, for sharpening
blades and other implements. Non-friable sandstone can be used to
make grindstones for grinding grain, e.g., &lt;a title="Gritstone"
href="/wiki/Gritstone"&gt;gritstone&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;Rock formations that are
primarily sandstone usually allow &lt;a title="Percolation"
href="/wiki/Percolation"&gt;percolation&lt;/a&gt; of water and other fluids
and are &lt;a title="Porosity" href="/wiki/Porosity"&gt;porous&lt;/a&gt; enough
to store large quantities, making them valuable &lt;a title="Aquifer"
href="/wiki/Aquifer"&gt;aquifers&lt;/a&gt; and
&lt;a title="Petroleum reservoir"
href="/wiki/Petroleum_reservoir"&gt;petroleum reservoirs&lt;/a&gt;.
Fine-grained aquifers, such as sandstones, are more apt to filter
out pollutants from the surface than are rocks with cracks and
crevices, such as &lt;a title="Limestone"
href="/wiki/Limestone"&gt;limestone&lt;/a&gt; or other rocks fractured by
&lt;a title="Earthquake" href="/wiki/Earthquake"&gt;seismic
activity&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;Sandstones are&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;i style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;&lt;a title="Clastic rock"
href="/wiki/Clastic_rock"&gt;clastic&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/i&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;in origin (as opposed
to either&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;i style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;organic&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
, like&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
title="Chalk" href="/wiki/Chalk"&gt;chalk&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;and&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Coal"
href="/wiki/Coal"&gt;coal&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
, or&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;i style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;chemical&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
, like&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
title="Gypsum" href="/wiki/Gypsum"&gt;gypsum&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;and&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Jasper"
href="/wiki/Jasper"&gt;jasper&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;sup style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
class="reference"
id="cite_ref-LF_1-0"&gt;&lt;a href="#cite_note-LF-1"&gt;&lt;span&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;2&lt;span&gt;
]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; &lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;They
are formed from&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
title="Cementation (geology)"
href="/wiki/Cementation_%28geology%29"&gt;cemented&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;grains that may either
be fragments of a pre-existing rock or be mono-minerallic&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Crystal"
href="/wiki/Crystal"&gt;crystals&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
. The cements binding these grains together are typically&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Calcite"
href="/wiki/Calcite"&gt;calcite&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Clay"
href="/wiki/Clay"&gt;clays&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;and&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" class="mw-redirect"
title="Silica"
href="/wiki/Silica"&gt;silica&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
title="Particle size (grain size)"
href="/wiki/Particle_size_%28grain_size%29"&gt;Grain sizes&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;in sands are defined
(in geology) within the range of 0.0625 mm to 2 mm (0.002-0.079
inches). Clays and sediments with smaller grain sizes not visible
with the naked eye, including&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Siltstone"
href="/wiki/Siltstone"&gt;siltstones&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;and&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Shale"
href="/wiki/Shale"&gt;shales&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
, are typically called&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;i style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;&lt;a title="Argillaceous minerals"
   href="/wiki/Argillaceous_minerals"&gt;argillaceous&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/i&gt;
   &lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;sediments; rocks
   with larger grain sizes, including&lt;/span&gt;
   &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Breccia"
   href="/wiki/Breccia"&gt;breccias&lt;/a&gt;
   &lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;and&lt;/span&gt;
   &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
   title="Conglomerate (geology)"
   href="/wiki/Conglomerate_%28geology%29"&gt;conglomerates&lt;/a&gt;
   &lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;are termed&lt;/span&gt;
   &lt;i style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;rudaceous&lt;/i&gt;
   &lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;sediments.&lt;/span&gt; 
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;The formation of sandstone
involves two principal stages. First, a layer or layers of sand
accumulates as the result of &lt;a title="Sedimentation"
href="/wiki/Sedimentation"&gt;sedimentation&lt;/a&gt;, either from water (as
in a river, lake, or sea) or from air (as in a desert). Typically,
sedimentation occurs by the sand settling out from suspension;
i.e., ceasing to be rolled or bounced along the bottom of a body of
water (e.g., seas or rivers) or ground surface (e.g., in a desert
or &lt;a title="Erg" href="/wiki/Erg"&gt;erg&lt;/a&gt;). Finally, once it has
accumulated, the sand becomes sandstone when it is
&lt;a title="Compaction (geology)"
href="/wiki/Compaction_%28geology%29"&gt;compacted&lt;/a&gt; by pressure of
overlying deposits and cemented by the precipitation of minerals
within the pore spaces between sand grains.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;The most common cementing
materials are silica and &lt;a title="Calcium carbonate"
href="/wiki/Calcium_carbonate"&gt;calcium carbonate&lt;/a&gt;, which are
often derived either from dissolution or from alteration of the
sand after it was buried. Colors will usually be tan or yellow
(from a blend of the clear quartz with the dark amber feldspar
content of the sand). A predominant additional colorant in the
southwestern United States is &lt;a title="Iron oxide"
href="/wiki/Iron_oxide"&gt;iron oxide&lt;/a&gt;, which imparts reddish tints
ranging from pink to dark red (&lt;a title="Terracotta"
href="/wiki/Terracotta"&gt;terracotta&lt;/a&gt;), with additional
&lt;a title="Manganese" href="/wiki/Manganese"&gt;manganese&lt;/a&gt; imparting
a purplish hue. Red sandstones are also seen in the Southwest and
West of &lt;a title="England" href="/wiki/England"&gt;England&lt;/a&gt; and
&lt;a title="Wales" href="/wiki/Wales"&gt;Wales&lt;/a&gt;, as well as central
&lt;a title="Europe" href="/wiki/Europe"&gt;Europe&lt;/a&gt; and
&lt;a title="Mongolia" href="/wiki/Mongolia"&gt;Mongolia&lt;/a&gt;. The
regularity of the latter favors use as a source for
&lt;a title="Masonry" href="/wiki/Masonry"&gt;masonry&lt;/a&gt;, either as a
primary building material or as a facing stone, over other
construction.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 style="font-weight: bold; font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;span class="mw-headline" id="Types"&gt;Types&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;Sandstones fall into
several major groups based on their &lt;a title="Mineralogy"
href="/wiki/Mineralogy"&gt;mineralogy&lt;/a&gt; and texture. Below is a
partial list of common sandstone types.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Quartz arenites"
href="/wiki/Quartz_arenites"&gt;quartz arenites&lt;/a&gt; are made up almost
entirely of &lt;a title="Quartz" href="/wiki/Quartz"&gt;quartz&lt;/a&gt;
grains, usually well sorted and rounded. These pure quartz sands
result from extensive &lt;a title="Weathering"
href="/wiki/Weathering"&gt;weathering&lt;/a&gt; that occurred before and
during transport and removed everything but quartz, the most stable
&lt;a title="Mineral" href="/wiki/Mineral"&gt;mineral&lt;/a&gt;. They are
common in &lt;a title="Beach" href="/wiki/Beach"&gt;beach&lt;/a&gt;
environments.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a title="Arkose" href="/wiki/Arkose"&gt;arkoses&lt;/a&gt; are more than
25 percent &lt;a title="Feldspar"
href="/wiki/Feldspar"&gt;feldspar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;sup class="reference"
id="cite_ref-LF_1-1"&gt;&lt;a href="#cite_note-LF-1"&gt;&lt;span&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;2&lt;span&gt;
]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; The grains tend to be poorly rounded and less
well sorted than those of pure quartz sandstones. These
feldspar-rich sandstones come from rapidly eroding
&lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Granitic"
href="/wiki/Granitic"&gt;granitic&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a title="Metamorphic rock"
href="/wiki/Metamorphic_rock"&gt;metamorphic&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a title="Terrain"
href="/wiki/Terrain"&gt;terrains&lt;/a&gt; where &lt;a class="mw-redirect"
title="Chemical weathering"
href="/wiki/Chemical_weathering"&gt;chemical weathering&lt;/a&gt; is
&lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Subordinate"
href="/wiki/Subordinate"&gt;subordinate&lt;/a&gt; to &lt;a class="mw-redirect"
title="Physical weathering"
href="/wiki/Physical_weathering"&gt;physical weathering&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Lithic sandstones"
href="/wiki/Lithic_sandstones"&gt;lithic sandstones&lt;/a&gt; contain many
&lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Lithic Fragment (geology)"
href="/wiki/Lithic_Fragment_%28geology%29"&gt;lithic fragments&lt;/a&gt;
derived from fine-grained rocks, mostly &lt;a class="mw-redirect"
title="Shales" href="/wiki/Shales"&gt;shales&lt;/a&gt;,
&lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Volcanic"
href="/wiki/Volcanic"&gt;volcanic&lt;/a&gt; rocks, and fine-grained
&lt;a title="Metamorphic rock"
href="/wiki/Metamorphic_rock"&gt;metamorphic rocks&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Graywacke"
href="/wiki/Graywacke"&gt;graywacke&lt;/a&gt; is a &lt;a class="mw-redirect"
title="Heterogeneous" href="/wiki/Heterogeneous"&gt;heterogeneous&lt;/a&gt;
mixture of &lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Lithic Fragment (geology)"
href="/wiki/Lithic_Fragment_%28geology%29"&gt;lithic fragments&lt;/a&gt; and
angular grains of quartz and feldspar, and/or grains surrounded by
a fine-grained &lt;a title="Clay" href="/wiki/Clay"&gt;clay&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a title="Matrix (geology)"
href="/wiki/Matrix_%28geology%29"&gt;matrix&lt;/a&gt;. Much of this matrix
is formed by relatively soft fragments, such as &lt;a title="Shale"
href="/wiki/Shale"&gt;shale&lt;/a&gt; and some volcanic rocks, that are
chemically altered and physically compacted after deep burial of
the sandstone formation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a title="Eolianite" href="/wiki/Eolianite"&gt;Eolianite&lt;/a&gt; is a
term used for a rock which is composed of sand grains that show
signs of significant transportation by wind. These have usually
been deposited in &lt;a class="mw-redirect" title="Deserts"
href="/wiki/Deserts"&gt;desert&lt;/a&gt; environments. They are commonly
extremely well sorted and rich in quartz.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a title="Oolite" href="/wiki/Oolite"&gt;Oolite&lt;/a&gt; is more a
limestone than a sandstone, but is made sand-sized carbonate ooids,
and is common in saline beaches with gentle wave action&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;big style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;&lt;big&gt;Kbal Spean site in
Phnom Kulen National Park
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/big&gt;&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;Kbal Spean in Phnom
Kulen National Park is well known with its spectacularly carved
riverbed, set deep in the jungle to the northeast of Angkor. More
commonly referred to in English as the ‘River of a Thousand
Lingas’. The name actually means ‘The Bridgehead’, a reference to
the natural rock bridge at the site. Linga have been elaborately
carved into the riverbed, and images of Hindu deities are dotted
about the area.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;The site is known for
its carvings representing&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Fertility"
href="/wiki/Fertility"&gt;fertility&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;and its waters which
hold special significance to&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Hindu"
href="/wiki/Hindu"&gt;Hindus&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
. Just 5cm under the water's surface over 1000 small carvings are
etched into the&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
title="Sandstone" href="/wiki/Sandstone"&gt;sandstone&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;riverbed. The waters
are regarded as holy, given that Jayavarman II chose to bathe in
the river, and had the river diverted so that the stone bed could
be carved. Carvings include a stone representation of the Hindu
god&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Vishnu"
href="/wiki/Vishnu"&gt;Vishnu&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;laying on his
serpent&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
title="Ananta"
href="/wiki/Ananta"&gt;Ananta&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
, with his wife&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
title="Lakshmi" href="/wiki/Lakshmi"&gt;Lakshmi&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;at his
feet&lt;/span&gt;&lt;sup style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
class="reference"
id="cite_ref-Time_2-0"&gt;&lt;a href="#cite_note-Time-2"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
. A lotus flower protrudes from his navel bearing the god&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;" title="Brahma"
href="/wiki/Brahma"&gt;Brahma&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;Kbal Spean was
discovered in 1969, when EFEO ethnologist Jean Boulbet was shown
the area by an essai; the area was soon off-limits due to the civil
war, only becoming safe again in 1998.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;Approaching the wonder
of Kbal Spean, ones need 1.km uphill walk to the carvings, along a
pretty path that winds its way up into the jungle, passing by some
interesting boulder formations along the way. Carry plenty of water
up the hill, as there is none available beyond the parking area.
The path eventually splits to the waterfall or the river carvings.
It is best to start with the river carvings and work back down to
the waterfall to cool off. There is an impressive carving of Vishnu
on the upper section of the river, followed by a series of carvings
at the bridgehead itself, many of which have been tragically hacked
off in the recent years. This whole area is now roped off to
protect the carvings from further damage.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;Along way, you may see
many of local coming here for picnicking which is not advisable at
all. Following the river down, there are several more impressive
carvings of Vishnu, and Shiva with his consort Uma, and further
downstream hundreds of linga appear on the riverbed. At the top of
the waterfall, there are many animal images, including a cow and a
frog, and a path winds around the boulders to a wooden staircase
leading down to the base of the falls and the pool. Visitors
between February and June will be disappointed to see very little
water here. The best time to visit is between September and
December. &amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
 &lt;img style="width: 768px; height: 297px;"
alt="kbal spean waterfall"
src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/b96abcff-5d36-44e2-87fd-c19091d19f26.jpg" /&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
 &lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;Kbal Spean is
generally a more rewarding place to visit a compared to Phnom
Kulen. Admission to Kbal Spean is included in the general Angkor
pass and the last entry to the site is at 3.30pm. An on way journey
to Kbal Spean is about 50km northeast of&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
href="http://www.pbase.com/boon3887/siem_reap"&gt;Siem Reap&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;or about 18km beyond
the temple of&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
href="http://www.pbase.com/boon3887/banteay_srei"&gt;Banteay
Srei&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;. Road from
Banteay Srei continues north to Anlong Vieng, formerly a stronghold
of the Khmer Rouge. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;small style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"
      lang="EN"&gt;Source:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/small&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: normal; font-size: 11pt; font-family: Times New Roman;"
      lang="EN"&gt;&lt;small&gt;free encyclopedia and other educational
      materials&lt;/small&gt;&lt;big&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
&lt;span style="font-weight: bold; color: rgb(255, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
Car park and entrance to Phnom Kulen National
Park:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold; color: rgb(255, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
N13.40.629, E
104.01.635&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;

 
&lt;p style="color: rgb(255, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman; font-weight: bold;"&gt;
&lt;font size="+2"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt;"&gt;&lt;big style="font-weight: normal; font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;big&gt;For the valid "cache found" log:&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;1)
&lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;you&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;have&lt;/span&gt; to
&lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;upload&lt;/span&gt; a
&lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;photo&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;of&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;you&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;with&lt;/span&gt;
GPS&amp;nbsp;infront of the waterfall&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;(N 13.41.126,
E 104.00.972,&amp;nbsp;you do not have to stand in the pool)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;2)&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;
send&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;me&lt;/span&gt; via e-mail
(Aucoin.J@seznam.cz)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;
:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;-&amp;nbsp; at
least three names of common sandstone types&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;3)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;&lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;
send&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="SpellE"&gt;me&lt;/span&gt; via e-mail
(Aucoin.J@seznam.cz)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;
:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;just few
meters above the waterfall (where you have taken the photo) you can
find the sandstone carved crocodile.&amp;nbsp;It
is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;
on the bank of the river (but depends on seasonal weather can be in
the
river)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;Which colour
does the sandstone&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;carved
crocodile&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span style="font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 153);"&gt;have ?&lt;br /&gt;
Can you see whole crocodile or just a head ?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="font-family: Times New Roman;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br style="font-family: Times New Roman;" /&gt;
